Flavor matches the aroma with a really nice malt profile that has complexity without being overly sweet and a crisp, dry finish with some subtle hop bitterness. Medium body.

Darker amber pour, good sized puffy white head, lots of lace. Bready aroma, some caramel sweetness. Bready up front, rye, caramel, subtlespice and hopping, earthy. Medium body. My default beer when I visit Cleveland - everywhere seems to have this at least in bottles.
pours a ruby tinted amber with a medium beige head. Aroma of caramel malt. Nice malt character. smooth creamy mouth feel. Semi sweet with just a hint of hop presence on the finish. Sweetish linger.

Pours a dark amber with a thick white foam head. Aroma is caramel and earth hops. Flavor is caramel, toast, earthy hops, with a dry, lightly bitter finish. Solid stuff.

Hits all the hallmarks of the Vienna style. Lightly malt forward with muted earthy slightly metallic continental hops. Pours reddish brown with a small ring of beige head. Little in the way of aroma. Very clean throughout. Nice lingering pumpernickel toast finish.

DATE TASTED: June 14, 2015... GLASSWARE: Hennepin pokal... OCCASION: Cavs/Warriors Game 5--have a good feeling about this one, so I will pair it with a good--and Ohio-brewed--beer... APPEARANCE: Amber, almost ruby red, dark but mostly translucent; head is off-white, swift and forms a halo around an island... AROMA: a slam of caramel with cherry, raspberry and other fruity hints; the hops are not so present, but in a lager, I am not surprised... PALATE: speaking of style, unlike any Vienna I have had--full-bodied, balanced between the teeth and the tongue, and dry--almost a winelike finish; the ABV is clearly a force... TASTE: again, the strength of a pinot noir, with caramelized malts and pepper, chocolate, and some cherry qualities as well... OVERALL: as formidable a lager can get, in terms of flavor and strength--balanced and full, with a pleasant, drinkability; something of a dessert lager (?) that finishes an evening properly...now, if only the Cavs can do the same...

Appearance: Muddy reddish-amber with a small ring of off-white foam and little to no lacing.

Bottle, thanks Colin. Nice clear copper pour with a big foamy white head. Some caramel and toasty malts in ok aroma. Taste - lots of flavour, lots of caramel and toasty malts again. Clean. Has a bit of an astringent twang I do not care for. Well crafted but just ok for me.

BBD 2/16/15. Pours a clear amber with a lovely rich dark ruby cast. Excellent head volume, World Class lacing and excellent retention.

Nice light nose of toffee with caramel malt notes over subtle noble hops with a touch of spice.

Heavy medium body with a creamy texture. Slightly above normal carbonation with a touch of effervescence in the middle and a nice burst in the finish. 

The World Class flavor profile is intense, complex and a masterpiece in balance. It begins with creamy blend of toffee and caramel against a slight sweetness that has a cracker character. In the middle, a nice noble hop flavor emerges over a mild bitterness. Against a fading bitterness, a nice spicy hop character emerges that is a bit tart, a bit clove like and has a pepper aspect - outstanding. The finish is a bit dry, but also has a sweet biscuit component. A slightly tart note lingers for a bit over a receding caramel and biscuit sweetness leaving the tongue with a slight pucker.

12 oz bottle, poured into a pint glass at approximately 40 degrees F.

A: Looks like free-flowing honey on the pour, which swells into a beautiful clear amber. Small streams of bubbles rise slowly from the bottom at the start, before dying away to leave the beer a deep amber shading towards russet. A thick head of foam forms, which slowly dies down to a cap. The lacing is minimal, but present.

S: Sweet toasted malt and caramel, wreathed around bready yeast with some faint notes of rich soil and ripe fruit.

T: Mother of god, this is a fantastic Vienna lager. The taste opens with sweet bread and lightly toasted caramel, before some hints of walnut, raisin, and pecan join in. Theres some slight bitterness from the malt, as well as an earthen, loamy bitter that offsets the sweetness just enough. Warm yeasty bread with toffee-like tinges form the finish, which lingers without overstaying its welcome.

M: A light, smooth, silky lager, with exactly the right amount of carbonation to avoid feeling flat without sparkling up too much. Just heavy enough to impart a feeling of drinking a good beer, while remaining light enough for refreshment duty.

O: I have yet to encounter another Vienna lager thats comparable to this one. Its virtually everything I could look for in this style, from the complex malt profile to the slight hop presence and the silken mouthfeel. This is a staple of my beer enjoyment.

Amplified toastiness of the grain bill & a strong Vienna malt sweetness that leans towards toffee/caramel but doesnt quite reach the sucrose requirements. Hints of raisin, apple, & flowers. Earthy hop profile (almost Engilsh-style) leads into a lasting biscuit malt & yeasty finish. This is a good lager.

Transfer from BA review from 7-3-12 - 
\Poured from bottle into pint glass

Appearance  Pours a lovely amber color with a big off white head that has a wonderful retention. The head faded very slowly over time to give a good level of lacing.

Smell  The smell is heaviest in a bready and biscuit aroma. These are mixed some lighter sweet caramel a mild citrus hop aroma.

Taste  A smooth lightly roasted and bready flavor meets the tongue. This is mixed with some light nutty flavors as well as a very light caramel flavor. The carmel fades and the nuttiness gets a bit stronger as the taste advances. While these flavors transition, notes of a citrus hop also come to the tongue. At the very end, the taste bitters ever so slightly leaving a rather nice bready-lighty bitter flavor on the tongue. Very pleasing.

Mouthfeel The body of the beer is just above average in creaminesss with a carbonation level that is just below average to average. Both are great for the lighter roasted flavors, but niehter are too intense to take away from the flavors and drinkability.

Overall  One fantastic easy drinking brew with great flavors. A great drinking experience for this Vienna.

Reviewed from notes.
Several times poured into a pilsener and a couple times poured into a pint glass - there really wasnt much noticeable difference.
The appearance was a nice golden amber hazy sort of color with a decent one finger white foamy head that dissipated within less than a minute. Once the head died, there was some light stringy lacing sticking to both glasses for the most part.
The smell had a nice roasty maltiness running all about the nose. Id say it was a decent caramel of sorts that made everything seem right about it.
The taste was slightly sweet, but not bitter. It was somewhat roasty, but also a bit nutty.
On the palate, it sat about a light to medium in body with a decent sessionable quality about it.
Overall, I say this was a good Vienna Lager well worthy of having again if I ever saw it again.

UPDATED: JAN 26, 2016 12oz bottle poured into an English Tulip pint glass. Buttery caramel, and fruit are the first aromatic impressions that struck me - a faint berry and/or orange citrus aroma. This gives way to a slight dampness / mildewy smell as the head recedes, but the buttery notes are present and eventually turn to a baked cookie smell. Theres also a faint roasted grain in there too. The head is a creamy, slightly yellow/brown shade, a hearty amount of which remains throughout the drink, and it leaves an abundant lacing along the glass. The head sits atop a very clear orange-brown ("deep amber" I suppose) beer. Its mostly a sweet beer, but a mellow sweet at that.. It has some spiciness to it too - root beer comes to mind as theres maybe anise or sarsaparilla notes to it, as well as perhaps some molasses? Theres some light roasted bitterness with an ever so slight hoppy kick too, but the hops only appear at the finish. Its a astringent too. Its a medium bodied beer with a decent amount of carbonation to it - although it goes down smooth. Theres a roasted flavor that sticks around shortly, but its a mostly clean finish. The hops also contribute a slight grassy coating of the mouth, but, again, it doesnt stick around long. As it warms up, the root beer flavoring disappears and is replaced by maple syrup and butter (pancakes came to mind) with some slight burnt toast hints.

12 ounce bottle into lager glass, best before 3/4/2013.  Pours slightly hazy orange copper color with a 1-2 finger dense cream colored head with fantastic retention, that reduces to a nice cap that lingers.  Light spotty soapy lacing clings down the glass, with moderate streaming carbonation retaining the head.  Aromas of caramel, pear, apple, toast, brown sugar, brown bread, floral, and herbal earthiness.  Damn nice aromas with great balance of malt and fruity notes with good complexity; good strength as well.  Taste of caramel, pear, apple, toast, brown sugar, brown bread, floral, light pepper, and herbal earthiness.  Lingering notes of caramel, light fruit, toast, brown sugar, brown bread, floral, and herbal earthiness on the finish for a bit.  Great balance of malt, hops, and fruity ester flavors; with a nice amount of robustness and zero cloying flavors after the finish.  medium carbonation and body; with a very smooth and lightly creamy mouthfeel that is nice.  Alcohol is very well hidden with almost zero warming after the finish.  Overall this is a fantastic Vienna lager!  Great balance of malt and fruity ester flavors with good robustness; and very easy to drink.  A highly enjoyable offering.

Appearance: A very deep amber color. Almost red. Theres a very nice head on this one, and it leaves some pretty good lacing as well.

Smell: As the bottle says, a <VERY> faint hop smell. Its really barely there.

Taste: Wow. The roasted malt comes through well in this one. The sweetness with the bitterness on the finish is fantastic... VERY tasty. It works perfectly as an amber lager. 

Mouthfeel: No complaints. Not much to say, other than that its medium bodied.

Overall, Im glad I randomly picked this up in a mix-a-six at the store I was at. I was glad to see these ratings when I got home, and even happier when I poured the glass and took a sip. This is even MORE enjoyable to me considering Ive had a lot of super hoppy beers/IPAs recently. Its nice to have something a bit malty after so much of that. All-in-all, a great beer. Some may be turned off by its sweetness, but thats what I think I love about this beer. The sweetness and bitterness just works very well. Would definitely get this one again.

800. on tap at pub. pours amber with fluffy white head. slight caramel and burnt hop aroma. taste is crisp refreshing slight sweet and citrus hop

Clear amber, minimal white head, soapy lacing.  Nose shows light fruity malts, bread, and a bit of caramel.  Flavor is a little less fruity, but still shows a fairly sweet malt profile.  Minimal hop presence.  Medium bodied, light carbonation, slightly sweet lingering finish.

Draft. Pours a deep copper color with a nice lacing head. Nice malty aroma with a hint of lemon. Dry taste with a nice mix of hops and malt. Kind of smokey as well. Solid balance with a complicated finish.
Draught somewhere in Columbus OH.  Probably the best Vienna I have had - not that I have tried many.  Good east drinking beer perfect for watching a game.

Exceptional vienna style lager. A nice amber brown pour, with a thin, disappearing foam on top. Delicious harmony of hops, malt, and alcohol. Decent finish with a clean carbonation to cleanse the palate. A nice session beer.
A different tasting lager. Bought in a Great Lakes variety pack that included two lagers, a pale ale, and porter.
Bottle from my secret Santa. Pours clear amber with a big light brown head. Aroma is sweet herbal malts, caramel. Taste is caramel and herbal malts, medium bodied, light bitter and dry end.

The beer is transparenty and amber colored with over an inch of dense, soapy, tan head. The aroma offers malt, lager yeast, fruity notes. The flavor is sweet, with a pronounced lager taste and lingering fruity malts. Biscuits and perhaps some crackers. Light to medium bodied. A bit heavier than your session type lagers. Well done and flavorful, though the sweetness, while not overbearing or cloying, per se, does limit my consumption. A solid beer.
Pours all red. Barely any head. Draft at arrow. Good malty taste. Mild hops and easy drinking. Good for the style
Amber pour with an off-white head. Aroma is caramel malt. Taste is caramal malt, crisp and tasty.

I think that this should be the reference for American-brewed amber lagers. Rich, clear amber with a finger of mouth-watering foam that looks beautiful and inviting in the glass. Delicate nutty, toasted aroma with a nice bready backbone and crisp hops peeking around the corner. In the mouth, light-to-medium lager body with a creamy texture and a flavor that is balanced and nuanced. Toasted, nutty malts that get clipped in the finish by just the right amount of hops. From a bottle, youll get slightly sharper, more pronounced carbonation, but the flavor and the aroma is very nearly identical. Great Lakes did a fantastic job with this beer - its far harder to pull together something like this than a huge, imperial-whatsit with huge grain and hops bills and barrel aging that buries flaws.
Impossibly red.  Crystal clear.  Sweet, malty, bitter after.  Nice mouthfeel.
Pours clear dark red..  White flufy head... Aroma is caramel and wood...  Taste is sour cherry malts. .bitter finish..  good for its style
Draft at lucky lab. Pours clear reddish copper with a small white head. The aroma Is floral with a bit of bread and biscuit. The taste is strong with a nice biscuit finish. Solid lager.
Copper colored with a slightly off white head. Aroma of sweet caramel, grains and bread. Sweet flavor with a small amount of hop bitterness. Clean finish.
From a 12 oz bottle at a tasting. Pours clear am er with a white head. Caramel notes in the nose. Tasty.
Poured copper with a thin, white head.  Aroma is mostly bread and floral.  Palate is very flavorful: grass, bread, a little bit of fruit.  Good beer.

Clear abler with a decent head that quickly turns to a thin coating on top. This does leave behind decent lacing. Aroma is faint, the temperature the bed was served at, quite cold, doesnt help me get much out of it....just seems clean, if thats a thing. The flavor is nice, light and fresh at first with a quick turn to some nice biting hops. Theyre mostly bitter and dont give much in the way of resiny or flowery flavors.

12oz bottle into a pint glass.

Pours a deep rich copper with a two finger off-white head. The head refuses to go away and the lacing on the sides of the glass is amazing.

Aroma of toffee, caramel, and chocolate along with a little bit of toast. Some yeast and cinnamon is also apparent in the aroma.

The flavor really has quite a bit going on. Caramel and toffee with dark bread up front with some cinnamon and chocolate lingering in the background. There is also a little bit of dark fruit. A mild bitterness comes in midway through but there isnt much hop flavor to go along with it. Malt is king. Mouthfeel is full but not too sticky. Really good job of keeping things fro getting too sweet which is easy in this kind of beer.

Overall, an amazing beer and one of the best I have ever had in the style. Definitely one to pick up when given the chance.
Sampled at GABF on Saturday October 13, second sessionClear copper color, tan head. Sweet, malty, grainy scent. Sweet, grainy taste. Medium mouthfeel, medium bitterness.

Brialliant clear dark amber,reddish ruby like a nice gem.Light head but nice froth,ring and some lacing.
 Candied carmel aroma with almonds/vanilla,fresh yeast,some cinnimon.
 The overall taste of this beer is very good,clean crisp malty carmel with some toffee or dark carmel/carmelized notes,maybe some butterscotch.Very smooth,with smooth hop flavor/bittering.This had the wow-factor upon drinking it.

12 oz. bottle. The color is dark brown and red. The head is small, beige, and bubbly. The aroma is toffee, hard cheese, bread dough, and coriander. The flavor is sweet, and fairly sour. The finish is bitter and sour and lingers for too long. The palate is medium, thick and sticky. Overall, this is a smooth and surprisingly complex lager, but the aftertaste is unpleasant, and the palate is too thick.
UPDATED: DEC 18, 2014 The best lager I have ever had. This is extremely smooth with a slight sweetness on the nose. Easy drinker, top of the style.
Bottle - from sampler pack. Deep copper-red color. Mostly clear. Aroma is quite malty. Good malty flavor with definite crystal malt. Somewhat hoppy finish.

Poured in a lager glass. Pours a clear amber with a thin, off white head and ok lacing. Aroma is bread, caramel, toffee, and a little citric hops. Taste is bitter up front. Grassy bitter flavors give way to caramel and a touch of toffee. There is a breadiness in there too with a nice malt flavor. Thin and easy to drink. This a fantastic lager.
Hands down the best lager Ive ever had. Smooth full of taste and flavor. It is a deffiently worth the money
Poured from a 12 ounce bottle. Toasted malts, hints of caramel, fruity hops. A easy drinking lager. Clean with a sweet finish.

UPDATED: SEP 11, 2012 Aroma:  Not much here, maybe a bit of cooked tomato.
Appearance:  More brown than amber red.
Taste:  A peculiar and clashing hint of watermelon, followed by a dirty cumin
flavor that must be the hops.  Even though the IBU is stated as being only 35, it tastes much more bitter.  Palate is average with an uncomfortable throat-drying finish. 
Update:  I was drinking it too cold.  The flavor is smoother than I first said, with more malt character showing, some nice smoky complexity, and a smooth hop finish.  Not bad.

Its so nice to see more and more microbreweries taking on lagers.  This beer justifies that excitement.  Slick mouthfeel, amber colored, rich in caramel and grain flavor, and perfectly balanced.  A bit high in alcohol to be sessionable, but you might try anyway.
Caramel in color... Minimal aroma.... Light caramel malt flavor, light hops on the finish... Floral hops on the palate... Okay for an amber
Nice dark amber color.  Slight aroma, cant detect too much of anything spice wise.  Good taste.

This is a wonderful beer for any season.  Along with its historical irony, the taste and body of this beer leaves very little to be desired.  It is much more on the bitter end of the spectrum so those who have a sweeter pallet of taste buds may not find this beer completely to their liking.  But those who enjoy a full flavored and resilient beer from the first sip to the last will find this very much up their alleyway.  Good out of the bottle but, as usual, is better poured .

12oz bottle. Thanks mike67. Pours a clear coppery brown with medium off-white quickly dissipating head. Aroma of toasted malted barley, caramel malt and yeast with some fruity notes. Taste same as aroma with some toasted grains and hops bitterness. A nicely balanced medium body, crisp with good carbonation on the palate. Finish is of toasted malted barley, caramel flavor, grains fruity with some lingering nutty aftertaste. Overall a good, crisp and refreshing brew.

Pours a nice amber color with a decent cream colored head.  Not much retention or lacing.  Tastes of malt, caramel with a slight hoppy aftertaste.  A decent beer, but nothing amazing.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
From bottle. Malty aroma and taste, thin head. Good round and balanced flavor but a little sweet I think.

Pours a medium amber, with a quickly disappearing cream colored head. Scent of toasty malts, caramel, biscuit, and a touch of hops. Taste follows nose with prominent notes of sweet toasted malts, toffee, and a fresh doughy taste. Well balanced mouthfeel with somewhat delicate carbonation rounds out this brew. Another solid beer from Great Lakes.

Extremely tasteful lager w/ a slightly bitter entry followed by a strong taste of caramel. The beer has the scent of a refreshing & flavorful lager. This is one to try again...

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Good beer,  if your in the mood for something hoppy but not over powering, this will do.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Nice lager. Aroma honey-fruit with attractive pour. Taste a little sweet but pleasant and quaffable. Good lager

12 ounce bottle. Redish-brown color. Moderate amount of carbonation.  Malty and slightly fatter then medium bodied. Sour caramel and malty flavors.  A little bit of grassiness sneaks into the taste.  Its a pretty mild beer thats good for sipping, but isnt very exciting.
Bottle.  Orange amber pour with little head.  Caramel, fruit, and sweet bread.  medium body, light but silky carbonation.  Very good.  Not overly sweet.
Bottle: Pours amber with a little head.  Great aroma of sugar and cake.  Very good flavor.

12 oz bottle (to glass) recd from summer secret santa - big toffee malt aroma (nice) - great orange amber pour with light head.  taste is like aroma plus some hops with an after taste - could be a little less sweet..

12 oz bottle from jsquire. Thanks Jeff! Pours clear amber with a large beige head. Smells malty, like caramel and toffee, and some mild (red?) fruits. Taste is sweet, like toffee, and mildly fruity with a touch of bitterness on the back end. Medium-bodied with a smooth texture and less than average mouth-carbonation, Great Lakes Eliot Ness finishes with a lingering fruitiness and a touch of bitterness.

(12oz bottle) Red amber body with a big light-beige, rocky head. Sweet caramel malt aroma, some earthy notes, hints of fruit. Medium body, oily mouthfeel, very smooth, some soft carbonation. Sweet flavor, strong caramel, as well as nutty, and earthy notes. Some grassy hops, too.

A great all around brew, just missing an aroma to make it perfect. Very smooth palate with tastes of caramel, malt, and some hops. Hops were evident but not over bearing. A tinge of floral and earthy flavored.

12 oz bottle.  Pours amber with a long lasting white head and nice lacing.  Aroma is of caramel malt and noble hops, hints of cherries.  Body is medium and slightly crisp.  Taste is of caramel malt in the beginning followed by herbal, earthy hops. Finish is long and dry.  Nicely balanced excellent brew.

What this beer lacks in aroma...well makes up for in taste!  Perfect amount of carbination,  tasty caramel and malty notes...with a long delicious after taste....top notch.  Delivered by a friend all the way from Ohio...thanks MB!
Clear golden color, small but thick tan head. Aroma of subtle caramel. Taste is light sweet malt.

Pours a clear caramel color with a medium tan head.  Aroma is malty/earthy.  Flavor follows suit...good balance...light caramel and earthiness.  Mouthfeel is medium and silky with a malty/earthy finish.  Basic but nice.
Mild tasting malt based ale, although the Cleveland brewery has better on offer.

Pours a rich, deep amber color, with a modest beige head on top. The aroma is a subdued combination of musty hops and a light bready sweetness. The flavor is much more potent, with big notes of fruity, sweet, and nutty malts being balanced by a dull, musty, earthy character, but there is also just a bit of an uncomfortable astringency and an alcohol burn. The texture is a bit resinous and almost syrupy, which is less desirable than the crisp, clean character that is the hallmark of most lagers, but it goes down fine. Overall, this rich, flavorful lager has some flaws, but I still wouldnt hesitate to buy it again.
Another awesome Great Lakes offering. Bottle, 1st Vienna attempt and loved the clean finish. Nice gold color with medium head; def. going to have this one again soon.

Bottle.  Pours a clear bright amber with decent off white head.  Smell is sweet caramel malts, light breadiness. Taste is light, but bright sweet malts, light frutiness, floral, and slightly bitter.  Finish lingers with a nice mix of bubbly, bitter and sweetness.  I can see why this is so highly thought after.

The very first beer I had from GL way back in the 1990s, and its nice that these brews are available locally. I wish I didnt find Viennas to be so dull for the most part. Decent bready nose, with an evident hop presence thats welcome. Nice mouthfeel, a bit prickly in ways that enhance the vibrant, refreshing qualities of the brew. Decent integration of sweet and bitter elements in the taste.

Pours reddish amber with a short tan head....
Scent is caramel, sweet, bready.
Flavour is the same plus a nice floral hopping.
Extremely good balance of sweet and bitter elements.
Great tasting, smooth, well done.
UPDATED: NOV 4, 2012 Variety pack, poured a dark amber with nice white head.  Aromas of bread, sweetness and caramel.  Taste brings on the hoppy grass flavor also.  Really nice lager.
Bottle. Caramel malt and light apple aroma. Amber with a small beige head. Caramel malt, bread, light grassy hops flavor.  Medium body and carbonation, slight dryness in the finish.  Very nice.

Pours a clear dark amber with a beautiful eggshell color, 4 finger head.  Very heavy on sweet malt in the nose, not too much hop aroma.  Very clean tasting, with a nutty character balanced out by toffee and caramel sweetness.  Not big hop character in the taste either.  This is a decent beer, but probably not one Id buy again.

Oh Viennas why oh why did you disappear for so long? The very best in this style make me feel like a very slight caramel is crystalizing in my mouth, then swimming down my throat with crispy goodness. This didnt disappoint at all. Surprised at the ABV! I had no idea while drinking it.

Originally reviewed: 12/8/08. Pours a dark caramel color with very small head which doesnt stick around. Lack of sticky lacing as well. Smells of nice caramel-esque maltiness, some grassy herbs, and some slight floral scents. 

Nice crisp mouthfeel pairs with mellow creaminess to make this highly drinkable. Sweet malty flavor with a slight hoppy bite right at the finish. As others have said, a pleasant break from the hoppy brews, but still plenty drinkable and plenty tasty.
Deep amber in color with a solid white head. Caramel, spice, grainy in aroma and flavor, some floral notes too. Really solid sessionable beer.

Bottle into Red Oak glass. Pretty, deep red-amber with a nice orange-tinted head. Aroma is faint, but nice. To me, this is less like a Vienna/festbier and more like an American red ale, but I guess thats just style technicalities. Flavor is pretty bitter. Palate is light and soft. I actually wish this had a bit more sweetness. Pretty good beer though--Ive been impressed with Great Lakes.

Cloudy Dark Crimson. Flavor is mainly sweet yeasts & malts with some nutty flavors and a slight grassyness to it, which is part of the flavor as opposed to standing out from the flavor. Very sweet tasting and smooth Vienna Lager overall!
Clear amber body with a frothy white head. Sweet malty aroma - including elements of bread and caramel - also a faint whiff of hops. Mild malty taste, finish is metallic and biscuity.
a deep amber pour with a little head.  malty sweetness, slightly biscuity.  a crisp refreshing brew.  im normally not a lager fan, but this one was really good.

Bottle. Clear amber color, medium tan head. Aroma of caramel primarily, also herbs. Taste is sweet from the malts. Medium body, sticky texture, average carbonation, can pick up the hops for balancing in the finish. Its definitely leans on the malt side but overall good flavor and a solid brew.

Location/Date:Bottle split on March 16th, 2012.
Appearance: Pours a copper red.
Aroma: Malty sweet aroma.
Taste: Really malt forward and sweet, similar to oktoberfest which I enjoy but heavier in alcohol than that style.
Palate: Light medium body.
Summary: Second beer in a row Im confused I havent rated(Stone Pale Ale, the first), a nice break from the hop forward beers I was drinking.
This has got a strong hoppy taste with a gorgeous amber color. I was actually surprised at how fragrant the beer is - it has a good strong beer smell. I like it.
Bottle. Mahogany brew with a faint nose of toffee. Flavor is a lovely blend of caramel, graham cracker, and bread. The mouthfeel is soft and welcomes in a warm, wheat toast finish. Excellent.
Pours an amber with off-white head, little lacing.  Aroma of balanced hops and great malt backbone.  Flavor matches well and makes for a pretty decent brew.

Amber with a solid, off white head.  Caramel, bready malt nose, light floral and herbal hops, honey.  Flavor is sweet at first, some bitter noble hops followed by a dip of butter and ending bitter and lightly roasty.  Its fine, but a little on the bitter side for the style.
Living in Ohio I always have some Elliot Ness in my fridge, probably my favorite session beer. Great balance all around, it wont knock your socks off but is just a good beer any time of year.

The pour is a clear mahogany with a sizable, off-white head. The aroma is of crisp malts; gentle, floral hops; and a touch of honey and licorice in the background. Its nice and subtle overall. The mouthfeel is good and clean, with a thin body and carbonation that doesnt get in the way. The taste is mostly dry, with malt notes and floral hops being perceivable on the tongue. It gets sweeter and maltier as it warms up a bit, but past a certain temperature it no longer is as enjoyable, so you just have to find the sweet spot. Hard not to like, really, but theres only so much you can do within the style. For the abv, there arein my opinionbetter session beers out there.

Bottle pours deep amber with a khaki head. Aroma is sweet, doughy and lightly toasted. Flavor is basically more of the same with a nicely paired earthy bitterness. Overall body is moderate and the finish is moderately
bitter. I guess I was expecting something a little bigger based on the name alone, but received a solid yet unimpressive session beer.

Deep amber color capped by a slight off white head. Nose is big and malty. Taste trends sweet but grass and hay do their best to balance. Alas, its a failed mission. Medium bodies, dont let this one stick around long enough to warm.

Rated via BeerBuddy

From notes.  First reviewed 12/28/2009.  Served on tap in a pint glass.

Eliot Ness pours a deep burgundy color. When the draught arrived, it had a thick, taupe head, which slowly clung to the side of the glass. A residual ring and thin film remained for the life of the beer.

A nice, smooth toasted malt aroma, with a bit of spice. A light fruity hop smell is present as well.

The smooth bready malt flavor is the preliminary and most dominant flavor, nuanced by a light caramel flavor. The hop flavor itself is fairly balanced, with a light citrus flavor. A bitter aftertaste lasts just a moment. Definitely a bold lager, with exceptional balance.

Moderate carbonation, with a nice balance between the chewy malt and puckering hops feels. Very smooth.

The subtle transition between malt and hops, along with the smooth feel, make this an easy choice for a repeat.  By far the best selection for the style I have ever had.
Golden red; thick, milky head.  Crisp, doughy, just hints of hops and bitterness, slight pepper aftertaste.

Great whit head with a dark amber coloring.  Flavored a good but not outstanding.  Slightly bitter finish. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Clear dark amber with slowing dissipating head and slight lace.  Taste is semi-sweet caramel malt with enough hops at the end to bring things to a good balance.  Very tasty for the style - typical of Great Lakes offerings.  Recommended.
This is one delicious beer. Good job ohio! Very well balanced malts. Unnaturally balanced. Are all beers of this style so good? Wow. Also the name is good.

Bottle. Faint hop scent, as stated in description, but I also picked up a sweet dough aroma as well. The appearance was a translucent dark amber after a carbo loaded pour, white frothy head with decent lacing. The medium-light body was slightly sticky in texture, and the taste was impressively complex (the strong point of my rating). The taste progressed: sweet malt, muted hay hoppiness, then a tortilla chip almost pretzel like grain, and a bitter finish. Quite a rollercoaster of taste.
UPDATED: MAR 4, 2012 Pours a relatively clear mahogany w/ some yellow head. Taste is straight-forward..roasted malt and a little spice.
Bottle.  Caramel malt and grass aroma with a hint of pepper.  Dark amber color with large light tan head.  Sweet caramel malt and mildly bitter herbal hops flavor.  Decent body.  Not bad.
12 ounce bottle purchased at Archer Liquors by Midway-Chicago airport for $8.99/6-pack Very good!
Fairly malty, though not too sweet. Hints of caramel and nuts with a balanced overall taste. A bit of hops in the end, but not bitter. A rather smooth and drinkable beer.

Ar: Slightly sweet dough, spicy hops, a bit of melon.
Ap: Clear orange-amber - small off-white head with poor retention - small amount of lacing.
T: Toasty malt with a very light sweetness - medium-low spicy bitterness - clean, firm, and malty throughout.
P: Medium-light body with medium-high carbonation - finish is dry.
O: Solid all-around amber lager.

Low malty sweetness, with a minor toasted undertone. No hop. No fruit esters. No diacetyl. Bright clear amber/red. Good head retention. Creamy off-white/tan color. Malt characteristics up, light toast, light sweetness. Followed by light hop bitterness, both of which continue through the aftertaste. Medium body, medium carbonation, slight creaminess. No alcohol warming. Overall, well balanced between the malt and hops, without either one controlling the beer. Soft and creamy, slight sweetness.
bottle.bb 021512 medium amber color with strong frothy root beer foam, aroma is sweet caramel, woody, flavor has caramel, some vegetal note, light fruit, sour bitter finish

Poured a copper color with a medium sized off-white head.  Aroma has lots of caramel malts with apples and bread.  Taste is sweet and malty with bread and some dough.  Some slightly fruity flavors as well.  There is a scotch-like flavor I cant put my finger on.  Finish is smooth and with some hops and honey.  Very nice.

Bottle left in my fridge after a party. Light roasted malt and hop aroma. Nice balance of complex maltiness with a soft sweetness and a slightly bitter hop finish. Pretty good, especially for the style.

bottle.  pours a clear amber with a very small white head.  malty nose with fruity esters and a hint of tea.  flavors of fruity malt with a bready note.  a zingy noble hop finish with a hint of lime.  almost medium body.  very balanced.  a sessionable type beer.
A little malty, hints of honey, pours medium brown, and light white to creamy head.

12oz bottle from Binnys in Naperville.  Crystal clear amber with a thiny, fizzy white head.  Aroma is fresh white bread and caramel.  Flavor pops nicely, bringing forward honey and caramel on top of sweet green fruits finishing with another wave of sweet honey.  Light body, light-to-moderate carbonation.

Bottle from trade with coldbrewky, many thanks. Dark amber color with small beige head. Aroma of  caramel, honey, bread. Taste, honey, malt, toasted bread, dates. Brandy like finish with light bitterness in background. Good.
Just about as perfect as one would hope on all counts. Really good when its fresh.
Bottle.  Clear copper pour with a small white head.  Malt aromas.  Not a bad lager, kinda sam adamish, with caramel malt and hop notes..
(bottle) clear dark amber colour with small tan head; aromas of fruit, figs, brown sugar; rich, balanced  flavour with long light bitter finish; excellent overall

Its a very boring style done perfectly.  If you like amber lagers then Im sure you will love this but it is what it is.  Taste is lightly sweet with a clean dry finish.  Aroma of hay, toast, and light caramel.
12 oz bottle, big sweet Malty aroma. Looks dark. Crisp finish. Caramel body, its def the most complex vienna Ive had and one of the most interesting lagers

bottle.  Poured clear auburn with a medium rocky beige head. Sweet caramel aroma. Medium mouthfeel, a bit tart, average carbonation. Flavours of caramel malt, some roasted nutty notes. Finishes moderately dry.
Pours a medium brown with an offwhite head.  Fruit and caramel malt aroma.  Medium-full body.  Quite malty palate with just a hint of noble hops.

Pours a medium amber with a hefty off white head.  Aroma is sweet malt and some hops.  Taste is rich and malty with caramel and butterscotch.  Hop presence makes itself known, but like a good Vienna or Munchener, it does not assert itself.  Smooth drinking session lager here.

Pours dark amber with good tan head, looks great. I cant pick up the aroma so well maybe its me, small hop notes and a bit of caramel and biscuit malt.taste is pretty biscuity as well with hints of caramel and a perfect crisp slight bitter finish, good beer.
Sweet hoppy aroma, malty taste with sweet finish. Beautiful color. easy drinking
Bottle from craft beer outlet. Pours an amber/red, sweet malty flavor. Nice drinkin beer.

A: The beer pours a somewhat cloudy copper color with about two fingers of khaki colored head.

S: Nice sweet caramel and toffee malt aromas to this. Plenty of toasted bread/malts are also there. There is a touch of yeast and some floral and spicy hop notes. Very nice nose.

T: Fairly sweet, but not overly so. Caramel and toffee malt flavors are there with some toasted bread. Light floral and spicy hop flavor and very faint bitterness.

M: Medium bodied with medium carbonation. Very crisp.

O: An extremely well done lager. I very much enjoyed this.

A lovely deep amber in the tall glass as advertised.  Thinner half inch head looks oily and leaves nothing behind.  Body has some biscuit tone but is mostly off center malt and does have a distinct dry rye tone even though it touts that is brewed according to Bavarian beer purity.  An interesting view on a Vienna.  Drinkable. Alcohol is not noticeable.

Notes of caramel and biscuit start off this beer.  It pours a clear reddish-amber, with a thin white head.  Slight caramel sweetness, balanced with earthy hops.  This is fairly thin on the palate, and is very easy to drink.  A nice respectable beer.

Pours super clear rich orange with a healthy 1 finger head.  Aroma is sweet biscuit, clean bready caramel, floral and earthy hops.  Taste is rich toasty bread with hints of fruit and spicy bitterness.  Body is medium-full, avg carbonation, long bready spicy finish.  Overall, this used to be one of my go-to bargain beers.  Highly balanced with a bit of extra kick for a lager, 6.2%abv, paired with a rich chewy body and full malt flavor, this is a really great session beer.

Pours a copper gold with a one inch head mostly lasting. Nose is malt and grains. Fairly creamy on the palate, the taste is mild with flavors of malt and grain ending with a nice floral note of hops. A better than average amber lager. Pairs well with beer nuts and pretzles.

On Draft at St. Stephens with Papa Steve. Pours a translucent, shimmery amber with a pillowy beige head atop. Aroma of cream, bitter hops, marzipan, and some odd, sweet spice notes. Medium to light bodied, especially given the ABV, with a juicy, creamy, flavor-bearing palate. Flavors are light and subdued, with the cream and almost sour lactose notes dominating the intial rush and a smooth, bitter hop finish. Very, very good stuff.

12oz bottle from Chucks poured into a lager glass. Light amber with 2 finger of frothy off-white head. Aroma of sweet caramel malt. Taste starts out lightly sweet and ends lightly bitter. Slight taste of caramel. Medium light bodied with a somewhat thin yet sticky texture. Lively carbonation and a slightly bitter finish. Overall, not too shabby. Not my favorite beer from these guys but definitely drinkable.

Serving glass: Poured from bottle into Pilsner glass.

Appearance: Rich, fiery amber with tan colored head and a single lacing ring.

Aroma: Very malty smelling, with caramel, bread dough, dark fruit, and a touch of noble hops.

Taste: Loads of bread dough, cherry and caramel upfront before becoming more spicy and slightly bitter, with notes of hay and noble hops. Good malts, good hops, but not sure the two mesh very well.

Palate: Moderate carbonation, medium to full body, fairly smooth and creamy. Off-dry finish.

Overall: This is a massive Vienna Lager, almost seems like a Bock version of one. Very tasty and complex, but not the easiest drinking Vienna out there.

12oz bottle poured into snifter, split with my brother. Dark amber color with a bubbly head. Aroma has hints of dark wheat and malts, Flavor is a tad sweet but has a pleasant sweet malty finish. Not too shabby.

(bottle, sampled 6/4/10). Clear amber color. Medium off white head. Moderate bready malt aroma. Light sweet malt flavor. Avg duration. Light bitter finish. Slick/thin texture. Moderate carbonation. Fair lacing.

12 oz bottle got in a trade with drfabulous. Used a pint. Nice red poor with lively carbonation. Although no head.  Nose of malt and caramel, very pleasing. Flavor is much the same. Caramel with toffee to give it a touch of sweetness, a little bit of hops to balance the sweetness. This is really drinkable.
Always good. A reddish-brown amber with a lot of sweet, fruity malts and caramel as well.

On tap at the Green Onion in Utica. Clear amber pour with a really good sized frothy head. Nose holds nice biscuity malt character, subtle floral hops, and a touch of nice fruity esters. Flavor holds further bready malt, light and refreshing hop presence, and excellent fruitiness with tones of plum and peach. Well balanced and a really nice lager.

8/14/11. 12oz bottle. Not quite clear amber/reddish pour with a nice, creamy tan head that sticks forever and laces quite a bit. Light aroma of caramel and nuts with a touch of graininess. Nice malty flavor of caramel and again nuts for sure. Distinct hop bitterness but earthy and not overwhelming. Nice.
Pours a deep orange body with a thin, persistent head. Caramel dominates the flavor profile. Toffee and nuts complete the beer.

Draft in a pint glass. Pours amber with off-white head. Lots of effervescence. I cant identify the aroma, but I do recognize this flavor. A little bitter and a tiny bit sweet. Finishes a little metallic, but goes down very well.  OK, the aroma reminds me of port I once had. Never had this type of beer before and I am intrigued.

Poured a copper color.  Aroma of caramel malts.  Lite bitter and lite sweet.  Med body, ave carbonation. Creamy texture.  A great full flavored amber style that has good hop/malt balance.  I am impressed with beers from this brewery.
Rich amber color. Sweet malt upfront, but nice hop bitterness in the finish. Solid body with medium head.

Date: July 29, 2011 Mode: Bottle Source: Apple Valley Liquor, Apple Valley, MN Appearance: Translucent copper with slight amount of head and no lacing.  Aroma: Hoppy.  Flavor: Little bit sweet, medium bodied, slight carbonation and a slight bitter finish Other: Pretty good brew, not my favorite style but I would have again.

I had this in a bottle at a friends BBQ.  Stinks like a barnyard upon opening, which tells me there is some serious barley going on.  Kind of a sweet flavor, maybe a little caramel-esque. Slight bitterness at the end for a nice clean finish.  Nice creamy mouth feel.  I really liked this one.

Bottle. Copper beer with a dark cream colored head. malt and caramel aroma with light mineral. Caramel and earth flavor with light mineral notes. Medium bodied. Caramel/toffee lingers with earth and light mineral.
A nice tasting Vienna.  Smooth, clean, crisp, larger brew.  A small white head, good CO2 mix.  Solid brew.

Bottle at home, rated against BJCP 2004 guidelines.  Aroma:  sweet, caramel hints (inappropriate for the style), toasted malt character.  Appearance:  cream colored frothy head, deep amber-red, fairly clear, wonderful lacing.  Taste:  sweet, slightly floral, toasted notes.  Palate:  creamy, medium body, medium-high carbonation.  Overall:  extremely good, and fairly good interpretation of the style.
Bottle at Thai 9. Finally an OH beer in Dayton! Pours a nice copper color. Very still with no real head. Very light aroma. Pretty light taste too; just a hint of caramel and spice. Okay though.
Amber pour from bottle with a thin white head.  Nice balance of malt and hops, with a touch of caramel thrown in.  Balanced and refreshing, I will drink this one again.
Bottle: pours dark amber with a thick frothy head, aroma is malty, slight sweetness, taste is malty, fairly dry, medium bodied. Nice lager.

330ml Bottle. Ap 4 Clear amber orange with big off white head and excellent lace retained thoughout. Ar 6 Caramel, grain, biscuits, grass, apricot. T 8 Med-light body, complex malt, grain - caramel + apricot hop and a medium grassy bitterness. P 3 Lingering malt complexity, toast and a light bitterness linger. O 16
Bottle. Poured a light copper color, with a thin white head. Aroma was malty, almost a biscuit. Flavor was crisp and clean, not exactly my thing, but not bad. Enjoyable enough.

8/29/2009
Pours a deep ruby/amber color with a huge bubbly beige that leaves lots o lace on the way down the glass. Smell is a sweet fruity malt aroma with a hint of earthy floral hops. Taste is sweet with malts. Burnt sugar caramel fruity and bready with just enough of a hop bite about midway through to keep the sweetness in check. Crisp carbonation, medium body, Oily almost creamy sensation in the mouth. Its been a while since Ive had a great Lager. This is one. Easy drinking smooth sessionable brew.

12 oz Bottle.  Appearance is amber, slightly brownish color with medium head.  Aroma is somewhat subdued with elements of caramel, toasty malts, and some hay.  Taste is very malty with flavors of toast and caramel prominent.  There is also a weird off-flavor I couldnt quite peg, but it definitely made the taste slightly less pleasant.  Hop character is very subtle with almost no bitterness coming across.  Palate is medium-bodied, fairly clean, lively carbonation, with a sweet, long-lasting finish.

12 oz bottle from PA. Pours a crystal clear reddish/amber color with a thin lacy head. Nice crisp, malty aroma. Medium to light body with a clean crisp finish. Nice malty notes upfront, with a clean enjoyable finish. Really well balanced and enjoyable lager. Overall: (A)
12oz bottle. Clear, orange color with lively orange bubbles. Medium and persisting white head. Very smooth beer, light hops aroma but very drinkable. Not much to it, though.
Pours a dark amber color with medium white head. Malty caramel aroma. Lightly sweet flavor of toasted malt and bit of caramel in the finish. Thin-bodied. Very good for the style.
Apr 25, tap @ The Grest Lakes, Cleveland. Dark amber, tart hoppy, thin body, fruity and very drinkable. Finishes with a great tart malty aftertaste.
Dark amber pour with a nice white head. Toasted malts and some earthy hops on the nose. Hops, coffee and caramel back this one. Not outstanding but very solid

Dark amber pour, thick tan head, lots of carbonation, but it didnt detract from the flavor.  More full mouth feel than expected, very smooth taste.  Sweet, but nicely so.  Nothing too challenging, but still, looking forward to the other 5 out of this 6.

Bottle. Clearer, nice ruby copper brown color with a thin white head. Light herbal, leafy hops and some malty sweetness in the aroma. Nice bit of hops, which I wasnt expecting, caramel, and toffee with a touch of sweetness, but a drier finish.  Reminds me of a tamer Brooklyn lager in some respects.  Very drinkable.
POurs deep amber with notes of malt.  Malt drives heavy over the light hops and the longer finish.
Pours muddy brown with very little head. Not a ton of aroma from this one. Taste is fairly malty. Not a lot of linger to this one. Meh!

12oz bottle in a tumbler.  Pours amber with a thin, cream-colored head.  Aroma of nuts, slightly toasted malts, with some dough and light hops.  Flavor about the same.  Average texture.  A pretty good beer.

This beer pours a very pretty amber with a light white head. The head lastes only about 30 seconds. It is very clear for its color, lacing is pour but it carbonates quickly with a swirl.

The aroma is very light, hard to detect anything. There are notes of light hops but they are kind of skunky.

The taste leaves much to be disered. The taste is very light you hardly taste anything, but what you do taste is tea. Its really not good.

Mouthfeel is ok, but I couldnt drink more than 2 sips before I had to dump it.

Pours reddish brown with a  creamy off white head.   Very pretty aroma. Smells like candy, and toffee. With a slight grassy note. Tastes good. Very drinkable, sweet and malty the toffee comes through a bit dry and it has some delicate hop flavours as well. finishes clean.  This is a great vienna. Perfect for style.

Bottle. Thanks to the Winnipeg crew, not sure if it was Kris or Scott, so thanks to both! Pours clear toffee/tawny, 1-finger off-white head, lacing is spotty to good. Nose is perfumed and floral, atop a sticky-pudding grain/malt baseline, notes of white grape and earth can also be detected. Flavours of spicy malt, sticky toffee pudding, raisin/dates, light earth, raisins turn to white grapes, turn to dates. Great stuff! I can see why its considered a classic!
355ml bottle from jsprime. pours bright red with a small off white head. nose of cara malt and backing hops. flavour is similar. easy drinking and could get you in trouble at 6.2%. nice.

Pours a medium clear maroon. Head is easy to adjust and it seems perfect. Aroma is exactly what I expect a good amber lager to small like. Just the right amount of caramel, which is essentially none. The flavor hits you in the lower back of your mouth and is a good mix. Its a borderline great beer because at bit of caramel bugs my tast buds. I guess Im not a malt roaster. I do give this beer high marks, however.
Bottle.  Apparently I dont agree with the masses because I really did not like this beer. It had a bitter taste weird taste for me.
Amber red with a medium head. Was very smooth. I will try a few more really clean ending.
Love the color.  Great aroma sweet spicy and malty.  Really clean with a brown sugar hint and the finish is nice and bubbly and wet and malty.

Deep beneath the placid surface of the Great Lake, an ancient behemoth of vast and hideous evil slumbers. The Elder beings abominable dreams touch upon a nearby brewmeister, who witnesses visions not meant for human minds to comprehend. Driven mad, he concocts a brew, in the Vienna lager style of his guilds predecessors, from the blood of a murdered inspector -- and some rich carmelized malts. It pours a deep amber with some frothy foam that leaves behind nice lacing, and a sweet, malty aroma. The taste is biscuity and fruity, well balanced with a bit of a hoppy kick at the end. One can hardly taste the blood.
UPDATED: JUN 16, 2012 Very nice malt profile, which makes it juicy and almost thirst quenching.  About perfect.

Another fine offering from Great Lakes. Nice hoppy and malty aroma with a splash of citrus and herbs. Appearance is a deep amber, copper with moderate white lacing. Taste is slightly sweet with the hops and malt well defined. thin feel, oily feel, on the palate.

Nice amber lager with a sweet aroma .  Taste was a bit to the harsh bitter side for a lager.  Not bad but there are better. I was happy to have tried the other selections from this brewery or I might have believed the Mistake by the lake statement about Cleveland. Good frothy head and nice lacing.  An unusual beer in that it looked better than it tasted.  Not awful just a disappointment.

Poured into a flute.

4.5 A: Clear orange amber color. Two fingers of creamy head with excellent retention and lots of lacing.

4.0 S: Lots of crystal maltiness. A touch of fruitiness. I touch of spicy hops.

4.0 T: Sweet graininess first. Good hop balance with enough bitterness for my tastes.

4.5 M: Medium body. Good carbonation. Really creamy.

3.5 D: Really good, but a bit cloying.

Serving type: bottle

Reviewed on: 07-08-2009 02:48:04
Pours a great amber color with a samll white head. Aromas of Caramel malts that are backed by hops. Flavor is of hops and bitter backed by a crisp malt flavor. Nicley balanced brew!

Bottle  Pours a clear amber with a small off white head.  The head fades quickly, but laces fairly well.  Aroma is grass, honey, grain, dark fruits and floral.  Has a good carbonation.  The flavor is decent.  Very drinkable.  Has a medium body.  The texture is watery.  A easy drinking beer.  Not too deep in flavor but still fairly good.  has a decent finish and a lighter aftertaste.

Clear amber/copper color with an off white head that had average girth and retention, but left some patchy lacing.  Some burnt orange and yellow highlights caress the sides and bottom of the glass.  The head settled to a fine film.  A sweet, rich smelling malt is the first fragrance I pick up on.  Some fruity hops abound.  Almost smells like a mild Oak barreled Kentucky Bourbon.  The fruitiness seems to be a cross between grapes and peach.  Not for sure.  With the taste, I am again picking up the very sweet malt with some fruity, bitter tinges.  Picked up the Oak flavoring of Bourbon again.  Its mild, but in there.  Medium mouthfeel.  Nicely smooth and dry with a sophisticated alcohol warmth.  The flavor is wrapped across the palate gently.  The brew has an almost slick or oily feeling.  This is a nice little beer.  A complex beer in my opinion in both aroma and taste.  It seems to be rather sweet, so that may get to me after a while, but I could set a few back with relative ease.
Pretty hoppy - almost tastes like an IPA.  Rich reddish amber color. I heard this was really good and I didnt like it as much as I thought I would. Not bad, though.

12 oz bottle from a mix 12 pack - Nice amber color with a thin lasting head. Aroma is nice sweet toasted bread with a touch of fruity darker caramel malts. Flavor is sweet and toasted  and a bit fruity.  Not overly hoppy but just enough bitterness to clean the palate. Nice clean, crisp finish.  Solid.

Pours clear amber with a copper core and a 2 finger, creamy beige head that has great retention and leaves a decent amount of lacing. Aroma is sweet malt, toasted grain, toasted nuts, floral hops, a touch of honey and grass. Flavor is dry roasted nuts, husky grain, honey, a little woody pine and floral hops. Palate is light to medium bodied moderately carbonated and off dry throughout. Really nice, well balanced and crisp Vienna. One of the best Ive had.
Good amber lager.  Dark carmel color.  One inch head.  Average lacing.  malty and tad hoppy.  This is what amber lagers should taste like.  Welcome beer from brother in Chicago.  Thanks bro.

Pours a lovely ruby copper with a thin off white head. very good clarity.  Nose- biscuit, grains. Very malt forward, layers of grain. Caramel, nuts, toast.  Hops take the background here, but do add some balance to the malts and show up on the finish.

G: Poured into a Sam Adams perfect pint.

A: Good, solid amber color that is quite transparent and has a strong off-white head with plenty of carbonation.

S: Strong malt sensation--the grains really come through with a tiny bit of hop bitterness at the end.

T: Quite omplex for a lager. Grassy notes in addition to the traditional malt one would expect from a Vienna. The amber notes are definitely there and enhance the flavor.

M: Fairly smooth with a moderate amount of carbonation. Sort of heavy mouthfeel for a lager. No noticeable alcohol.

D: Definitely drinkable. A little heavy for a lager though. maybe I just wasnt feeling this one last night, Ill have to try it again soon.

Great beer!  It is nice to find a good example of this harder to find style. Nice and malty with just enough Munich malt to give it that rich sweetness contrasted with the nice hop flavor and subtle aroma.

Appearance:  clear ruddy amber with a nice one-finger bubbly head; good lacing.  Aroma:  caramel, malts, some very mellow hops.  Taste:  sweet and crisp with malts and caramel, some slightly bitter hops.  Finish:  short and clean, slightly bitter.  Notes:  A very nice amber lager.  Well-balanced, with the hops providing just enough bitterness at the end to clear the way for the next gulp.

Bottled sample. Amber in colour with fairly strong carbonation. Aromas are of dark honey, rich munich or vienna malts, and some earthy and floral hops. The lightly kilned malts take centre stage in the mouth, along with elements of bread dough, carame, and herbal hops. In spite of the malt-forward flavours, the palate is not overly heavy or cloying, and the bitterness is firm and refreshing. Good stuff!

Bottle, shared at Hop Leaf, Chicago (second visit). Clear deep amber, thick creamy head leaving ropy lace. Fruity caramel aroma and flavour, but rather generously malty, making things seem a little bolder. Very nice without being over the top.
user_location: the land of bitumen, beef & beer, Alberta, CANADA

text: Im discovering that I am NOT a lager fan.  However, I can recognize that, as a lager, this one is top notch.  Its got that typical euro-lager wet cardboard malt/stale hop aroma.  That nasty euro-lager flavor, thankfully is not there.  Nice, not overwhelming malt with that "stale hops"  flavor being very subtle, but the bitterness is there, but a nice bitterness, not the "yuck" bitterness of mass-market euro-lagers.  This would be a fantastic session beer as it goes down s-m-o-o-t-h.

12oz bottle pours reddish amber with average thick head, and good lacing.  Aroma is earthy with deep notes of bready sweet malt.  Flavor is doughy with malt up front and a little touch of bitter hop to balance it but mainly is on the malt side.  Good medium heavy body almost creamy for a vienna very enjoyable

Clear copper with nice head, nice lacing... Hoppy aroma, almost has an american citrus hop aroma underneath toasted malts... Not very lively body, toasted malts, some light citrus, very good flavor for a lager...

Nose is subtle showing some hay and slight malt toast, a bit of dough and dried grass. Head retention is barely hanging in there. Mid palate shows medium body with roasted red grain. Slightly creamy and sticky texture. Resiny Piney hops and soft carbonation show up with the mildly bitter finish.

12oz bottle thanks to TheSevenDuffs. Enjoy by 09/25/10.

Appearance : Clear shiny mahogany with a medium foamy and creamy head. Lots of lacing.

Aroma : Caramel with some fruits. Nice light citrusy hops. 

Taste : Caramel with light citrusy hops. A bit veggy. Finish is crisp and dry with some caramel and hops. A bit mineral on finish.

Overall : Soft carbonation, very drinkable. Very well balanced and quite tasty. Ive had better Vienna however.

Bottle, pour is amber with great creamy head and solid lacing. Aroma is great malt and sugary sweetness that lingers. Taste is crisp and creamy with a solid hop and malt mix. Palate is sticky and dry with good carbonation. Solid tasting beer will drink again!!

Bottle pours a clear copper amber with fair offwhite head.  Nose is sweet fake caramel and corn.  Flavor is  a little better, with a semi-grainy, malt sweetness and some mild floral hop bitterness for balance. A little nutty on the tail. Fairly refreshing, and decent for the style, but nothing special. Maybe I need a fresh bottle?  Eliot Ness was the man though...
bread, nuts, resin, floral, cheese, golden, clear, minimal head, medium sweetness, lightly bitter, lightly sour, light body, sticky, lively,

From a bottle.  Pour is deep amber in color.  Aroma is caramel malt and grassy hops.  Flavor shines in this beer.  Sweet caramel with raisins to start and a nice and slight bitter finish.  Really delicious.

On tap at Maggies on the River in Watertown, NY. Clear deep amber color with a nicee head that lasts with good lacing. Looks inviting. Malt & caramel aroma, traces of fresh grain & sweetness. Full malt and caramel flavor. nice dry finish to offset the sweetness.  Medium body, creamy and smooth. Very well balanced with no real hint of the ABV.
 Great drinker, much better than I ever expected. Goes down very easy. Requested another wihout hesitation.

Bottle - Pours a very dark amber.  Medium sized off white head. Nice retention.  Some lacing.  Very mild aroma.  Flavor is of sweet caramel and malt.  Very rich.  Really nice beer.  Probably one of the best ambers Ive had.  Will certainly drink it again.
Tap @ great lakes - really soft body, arouma is bready and toffee malts and a bit nutty. Very sweet, piney hop finish, tasty and sessionable.

12 oz. bottle. Appearance- Bright deep amber mohagony with medium off white head. Aroma- Rich malty notes. Bready and some caramel. A little hops. Taste- Rich malt but not a lot of sweetness. Just enough hops in the finish to balnce it out a little. Palate- Creamy mouthfeel. Soft finish. Overall- A delightful beer. A great beer when Im hankering for something a little on the malty side.
I would drink this again.  It was very "soft" in the aftertaste and although it doesnt taste like it too much, my mouth "felt" like innis and gunn after.  Would buy again.  REALLY like the colour.

Whole Foods, DC ($10): Pours a lovely amber color (very bright and fancy looking), with a ephemeral but also quite pleasant beige head. The aroma is the weakest part of the beer being mostly caramel malts and is not so noticeable when cold, but becomes more prominent as it warms up (as is of course the course of all aromas). The palate and the taste are the true champions of this beer and I dare say that they champion quite well. The beer in your mouth goes through a few successive stages beginning with a smooth and creamy feel and some malts and then hitting some slightly bitter hops and uncovering a yeast note and finally coming to the finish, which is indeed a splendid culmination. Kind of dray aftertaste after that. Very well-balanced and nothing bad about it.
Poured from 12oz bottle, pours a clear amber color with white head, aroma has a nice touch of hops mixed in with the malt, a pretty decent balanced beer with a nice malty taste.

Bottle: Pours a Dark amber color, with modest white head. Smells more like a malty sweet bread, (the malt comes through here more than the hops in comparison to the dortmunder), and the flavors are similar with very light hops. Lightly Carbonated, slightly bitter, another (Great) lakes brew!
Poured from the 355mL bottle. Overly oxidized. Earthy flavour. Not that great but maybe because it was so oxidized.

UPDATED: AUG 27, 2010 Drank from the bottle. Aroma was of light caramel and hops. Taste and palate followed the nose as the caramelized malts turned into a light hoppy finish. Good overall beer. One that I would like to try again in a glass or on tap. Had on tap: This beer reminds me of an IPA through and through on tap. It is a completely different beer. Color is amber with a medium, off-white head that diminishes over time leaving good lacing. Hops are what I taste through the entirety of this beer. Not a problem, just unexpected.

12 oz. bottle: Drunk it out of the bottle. Mellow aroma, and could not really judge the appearance. Very smooth amber ale with just enough hops to make me want to try it again. Very good with food and enjoyable overall.

12 oz. bottle. Toasty aroma features cracker and biscuit scents as well as peach. Smell reminiscent of that of an English bitter. Dry hops in the aroma. Refreshing and appetizing smell. Pours a clear amber with good effervescence (moderate amount of slow-rising bubbles). Moderate to large amount of uneven, taupe head. Keeps its head well as you drink. Produces good lacing. Flavor matches the aroma. Dry start, fruity finish, and bready malt taste in between. Palate is a little crispy but mostly soft in body and largely unremarkable. Eliot Ness is very good for what it is. Its a high-quality beer in an underrepresented style.

12 ounce bottle.

A: Pours a deep amber with a foamy beige head.
S: Not much to the nose here, just a bit of malt if anything.
T: Caramel malts dominate the palate with not much else in sight.
M: Light bodied, smooth, and creamy.
D: Despite the limited smell, this beer is well balanced and worthy of a session.
I am starting to like this brewery more and more.  Since I am a porter guy, I decided to get the mix pack of these.  So far, all of these beers have been good.

Cloudy copper color with a thin white head.  Good lacing. Aroma of caramel and toasted malts.  Thick and creamy with caramel, some toasted malts and a slight hop bitter finish.  Heavy for the style but quite enjoyable.

Bright cpper color. Citra hop aroma, tastes like grapefuity hops. Mild
body, starts weird, but grows on you. Dirty laundry finish.

Pours a clear amber color with a reddish tint. Nice cream colored head with a touch of lacing. Caramel malt, dough, herb-like noble hops in the nose. Medium bodied, yet very drinkable. Light carbonation with a lasting finish. A good deal of caramel malt sweetness, balanced by a semi-dry, tea-leaf-like finish. Great character. Refreshing and enjoyable every sip. A winner!
Eliot Ness spent his life attempting to enforce Prohibition. What better way to honor him than to name a beer after him, and drink it too.

Had out of a bottle at Wilde, Chicago IL.  It pours a brown-copper color with a thin, white head. Aroma is of toasted malt and caramel.   The caramel leaves a sweet aftertaste in your mouth.  Easy finish.  Nice Beer

Bottle. Pours a clear amber color with a small off-white head. Has a fruity malty caramel aroma. Fruity malty caramel flavor with some bitter hints. Has a fruity malty caramel finish with some bitterness in the aftertaste.

This one poured with the expected red color, low carbonation, long lasting head, and clean floral hops.  It tasted a little more roasty than you would expect from a Vienna, but that was OK.   One you could make a session out of.
user_location: Lake in the Hills, Illinois, USA

text: I do like Vienna lagers and this is good one. My only issue with it is that every few sips I thought, "Is this a slight bit too heavy?" Nah . . . I must have lost my mind every 5th sip or something like that.  Another around good beer from Great Lakes.  Serving: Bottle

Serving: 12 oz. bottle. 
It pours a copper color with a frothy, white head.  The nose is relatively light with notes of toasted malt and a bit of caramel.  The caramel comes to the forefront in the taste.  Light toast notes emerge as the beer warms.  Light to medium mouthfeel with average carbonation and a short to medium finish.  This would make a great daily drinker and is worth seeking out.
From bottle. Pours a deep orange colour, nice white head. Nice caramel malt aroma. Very satisfying candied sugar semi-sweet malt flavor, with a nice bitterness as well.
From a bottle poured a brown color with a fair amount of head.  Heavy sweet malty flavor with a lingering finish.

Very nice indeed.  Malty aroma. very beer like.  Some try to be to wine like. Nice amber with a lacing head that hangs around. Taste is quite nice, malty and earthy with a nice hop dry, bitterness. Finish is very crisp, dry and clran.

nice amber pour with a medium tan head.
aroma is caramel, and toasted marshmallow  maltiness with a light fruitiness 
Flavour is very nice toasted malt.Caramel. something almost like rye breadiness and a light woody hop in the finish.

The one and only ketchepillar was so kind as to bring some Great Lakes beers over to the house last week, thanks Sam! The beer pours a deep orange color with a good head and some great lace. The aroma has some cooking spices with some lovely herbal hoppiness with plenty of fruity notes with just a bit of alcohol. The flavor is some great toffee notes with some deep roastiness the likes of which I rarely find in an amber colored lager. There is a nice bitterness and toasty character and is largely fruity. This is one heck of a beer.

Awesome. I love me some Vienna. Parsley and other fresh garden spice-ish stuff. Nice, hard to place hoppiness. A little bit of dusty malt character that is actually good. Parsley is a bit of a let down in the flavor, but I bet it is spot in were this bottle super fresh. It was probably a couple months old.
Pours brown with a smallish white head.  Aromas of caramel, butterscotch.  Refreshing finish, slight diacytal but not to offputting levels.  Pretty well made lager that hits the spot.

Pour is a nice dark amber with garnet tones as well. Not much head to speak of.

Lots of malt in the nose, caramel, molasses, currants, toasted marshmallows. Just a hint of grassy hops as well.

Taste is again very malty, with most of the nose confirmed. Nice smooth finish that lingers pleasantly with malt goodness as well.

Palate is Comfortably medium plus, coating but not cloying, and alcohol and carbonation are nicely balanced.

Overall definitely one of my go-to beers since it is readily available here, very tasty, very drinkable, and well made.

On tap at some bar and Ive had quite a few bottles of this but I havent got around to rating it.  First of all, wtf is up with all these people calling this a scotch ale?  Its about as vienna as it gets.  When I think of Viennas, i think of this beer.  Pours a tawny amber with an off white head.  Aroma of crackers, toffee, dough, some leafy hops.  Flavor is classic: dry, toffee, caramel.  Dark bread.  With some light hops hanging about.   So smooth and nice.  One of the best lagers in the world.

Pours cloudy, light brown with a hint of red.  Small tan head.  Rich, sweet malty aroma with a hint of hops nailing it down.  Bit of peaty flavor in there as well.  Taste is sweet but not overpoweringly so, medium body with a smooth mouthfeel.  Very good American scotch-style ale; avoids being too heavy, as many in the style can be.

12oz bottle. Pours dark amber. Small white head with no lacing. Malty aroma- sort of similar to Oskar Blues Old Chub Scottish Ale. Flavor is nicely balanced malt and hop, medium carbonation, slightly bitter finish. Less impressive overall compared to the other Great Lakes beers, but still good.

Clear dark amber with a small white head. The aroma reminds me a bit of a scotch ale. Some nutty peat, caramel, and floral hops. The flavor is nice, with sweet caramel, roasty grains, and clean bitterness. Very delicious. Medium body with prickly carbonation. Nice brew.
UPDATED: DEC 30, 2013 Tap. Clear amber pour with minimal white head. Aroma of malt, caramel, bread. Taste is malty. Decent.

Bottle. Medium sized light tan head atop a amber body. Aroma is lots of malty caramel, light toast, floral hops.  Taste is medium sweet and mildly bitter. Flavor is caramel, honey, bread, floral notes and a bit of spice. Body is medium and and a bit sticky. Tasty.
Pretty excellent.  Deep copper/reddish amber color.  Plenty of body with a spicy, hoppy finish.  Yum.
Solid amber color. A rich caramel malt taste. A moth aroma. Ver solid and the abv only detectible in the finish.

Dark coppery color w/ some chill haze(?), small head dissipates quicly.  Fruity esters reminiscent of an ale.  Very slightly sweet malty taste with medium body and full mouthfeel.  Very ale-like in the finish as well.  Pretty good.

A- Served on-tap in a pint glass. Body is a beautiful transparent medium red hue. Bright white head is about 1 1/2 fingers-and foamy. It eventually subsides completely and some lacing is left behind in the glass.

S- Nose is of medium strength and is a perfect balance between bright citrus hops and smooth caramel malt. This is a lager?

T- Initial flavor is quite bright and is full of citrus hop flavor with a great balance of sweet caramel malt in the background. The finish is consistent with the initial flavor with just a slight touch of bitterness and maybe a hint of piny hop flavor. A mild bitterness lingers along with a lot of sweet caramel malt.

P- Low carbonation and very smooth body. Mouthfeel is exceptional for a lager.

O- This is another one that I have had available to me since I started craft beer and didnt try until now. Its wonderful-the perfect balance of citrus hops and caramel malt. Both Eliot Ness and Dortmunder are excellent lagers from Great Lakes.

Serving type: on-tap

Reviewed on: 01-30-2008 19:15:25
--

My Bottom Line:
Deeply bready malts, spicy hops and delicate caramel create a most efficient, slender Vienna.

Further Personal Perceptions:
-A thick head of foam settles upon the clear coppery amber.
-The spicy hops provide levelled bitterness.
-This is relatively dry, like most of Great Lakes staple products as a matter of fact.
-Bubbles are quite present in the mouthfeel yet do not hinder on the drinkability.

Bottle.

UPDATED: APR 26, 2010 De couleur ambrée claire et légèrement effervesente. Dégage de légères odeurs de beurre, de houblon et de noisettes grillés. Mince en bouche, elle assèche légèrement le palais. Le houblon est présent, mais sans plus.  Elle offre de petites notes de caramel, de pain aux noix, de beurre et dhoublon frais. Bonne petite bière.
Had this on tap.  Sweet malts, carmel, but not rosted or burnt.  Crisp hop flavors usual to Vienna lagers with the expected clean finish.  Deep redish amber color.  Overall seemed a bit thin.

one of the most stunningly beautiful beers ive ever seen. pours a clear ruby poegranate color with a teafroth white head. incredible lacing. nose heavy with light fruit, fresh strawberry, breadiness, plum, caramel. flavor is dark fruit, caramel, plum, toast, and floral hops. finish is long and bitter turning to maltiness as it lingers.
Dark red-orange, beige cover.  Bready toasty aroma.  Taste is a bit metalic, toast, biscuit, caramel, grass.

Served from 12 oz. bottles at Brixies Spring Tasting in Brookfield, IL. Poured to my fluted fest glass, a clear, brownish amber, with decent, off white foam to the head, and clingy, dots and dashes of lacing. The aroma was toasty, light German malt nose, light grain, and a touch of caramel. The flavor continued these notes with light, hop bitterness, and a subtly dry finish.

Bottle.  Pours a medium, creamy, pitted, off-white head.  Lasting and lacy.  Clear, amber body.  Sweet, bready malt in the nose along with light herbal hops.  Flavor is full of sweet malt - bread crust, light raisin and caramel dominate.  More light, herbal, slightly musty hops complement the malt.  Medium bodied, sweet up front and lingering, but not cloying or unpleasant.  Lightly bitter with average carbonation.  Overall a classy, delicious Vienna.  I could drink the hell out of this if it were available here.  Super clean and flavorful.

UPDATED: MAY 15, 2010 $9 / Sixer- This is my second rating for this beer.  Unfortunately, I had to downgrade this beer on second tasting.  This is good, but not as good based on first impression.  Good lager, but a little funky.  Perhaps this is from the yeast or the odd hop selection that a "Vienna" style lager is made with.  Good for a session--sort of.

Pours orange red with white head that laces fairly well.  Aroma is caramel and biscuity malt.  Taste up front is a bit of hops with grass and floral notes, leading into caramel and bready biscuit malt with a bit of a dry but clean finish.  An above average amber ale, but nothing too incredible about it.

A reddish amber vienna with a thin off white head. In aroma, light caramel malt with light fruity esters. A nice sweet nutty  malt in mouth, with light hops, decent oily mouthfeel, not bad. On tap at brewpub Greenes Ale House, Oswego, NY, Feb. 7 2010.

Pint at Greenes Ale House (Oswego). 07FE10.
App.:  Clear copper, no head.
  
Aroma:  Kinda vegetal, some toffee/caramel, nutty, line sanitizer, some leafy, earthy hops, kinda British.
  
Palate:  Medium body, prickly carbonation.
  
Flav.:  Nutty, fruity caramel, apricot, berries, some dank, earthy hops, pretty nice; somewhat sweet with sufficient bitterness and a tasty malty finish.

Starts slow, ends well.

Thanks to hudsonphotog for sharing this beer.

The beer pours an amber color with a cream-colored head. The aroma is lots of biscuit malt. The flavor is toffee, caramel, biscuit malt and some fruit. The beer is slightly sweet. The mouthfeel is medium and the carbonation is medium.
Bottle from a trade with phaleslu. Pours dark amber color with off white head. Caramel malt aroma. Sweet caramel flavor with some bready malts. Medium body with soft carbonation. Thanks Peter.
Amber in color with an offwhite quickly gone head. 6.2% alcohol content.  Caramel notes. 12ounce bottle from multipack.

12oz bottle from Andersons in Toledo courtesy of the in-laws.  Soft caramel, butter and corn aroma.  Slick thin texture with little to no carbonation.  Tastes are butterscotch, grain and light hops. Crisp quick finish.  Relatively good balance of everything -- combination doesnt do it for me overall though.

Transparent red-mahogany with a thin, bubbly cream head. Rather plain nose of heavy caramel and light grain. More caramel in the flavor, earth and rainwater, some minor leaf, hints of mixed nut in the finish. Whatever hop once existed is drowned out now, leaving behind the caramel sweetness that, on its own, doesnt hold this one up. Thankfully the nut and rye in the flavor help it out. This review is getting more positive as it goes, reflecting that the beer kind of grew on me. Nice nutty finish, meshed well with the caramel.

12 oz bottle. Pours a deep golden amber with a small off white froth. Aroma is of caramel, toffee, a little bit of corn lightly grainy and a soft dark fruitiness. Flavor starts okay, a bit grainy, soft caramel malts, dark fruits, crisp floral hops towards the finish. A tiny booziness in the finish as well. Medium body and a light fizzy carbonation. Not great but okay for the style.
bottle thanks to thirdeye11.  deep amber/ruby with a cream head.  nose is orange clover honey mostly.  great on the palate with flavors of malts, honey and a smooth finish.

Another decent beer - I also like their creativity in naming the beers - burning river, edmund fitzgerald, eliot ness, etc.  Beautiful appearance - solid head and incredibly clear amber color - still amazed at how clear the beers from this brewer are.  Aroma of bread, malt, yeast, flavor is maltier than expected, very rich and sweet but also turns watery in the finish.  Didnt like that too much.  This beer is decent but not their best.

12 oz bottle

Another freebie left over from a recent party this one was another respectable beer.  I would not hesitate to buy a pint if this were the best option and in some cases it might be around Ohio.  For the price this is a nice year round option that mixes things up from the usual "big beer" equation.  Recommend it to your friends who do not rate and simply want to drink good beer that they can find almost anywhere.

Aroma / Appearance - Deep ruby red the body absorbs around half the light that filters through.  Carbonated with a bubbly head it suggests positive things are to come.  The aroma reminds of a sun bleached deck that is drying out from a recent application of wood stain.  Waxy chocolate hovers the edge like a Hersheys kiss in a bowl of candy.
