Flavor / Palate - The mouthfeel was surprisingly full.  After spending some time enjoying that aspect I discovered a nice depth of cherry wood, chocolate, and malt balls.  The hops that come forward never dominate but complement the other flavor profiles well.  If I were to drink this regularly I think it would make a nice spring beer for when the season changes from imperial stouts to lighter lawnmower styles.
Bottle from Thirdeye11.  Orange pour with a white head.  Grain and bread aroma.  Taste is malts, grass, and some honey.  A little bitter.
Bottle courtesy of thirdeye11. Clear orange pour. Very little head. Aroma of bitter notes with bready flavors on the finish.  Flavor of about the same.  Malts and dry notes.

( 12oz bottle thanks to BA Desaparecido) Pours clear copper with ring of bubbles. Nose of orange clover honey, sweet grains, and toastiness. Taste of grains, honey, and toasted caramel with a sweet oily body. Really nice Vienna.
(draught) reddish amber with very little head. Slightly sweet caramel malt aroma. Flavor is caramel malt with a little hops in the finish.

pretty good for a brown ale, which Im not usually a huge fan of.  Not overly malty and very clean and refreshing.  A bit of roasting as well.  Very enjoyable and flavorful without being too heavy.  Had both draft and bottles and both were good.

Pour is an amber-copper with a light white head. Aroma is sweet, with a dry hops in the background. Flavor was pretty sweet with caramel/honey notes. Not tremendously heavy, but strong enough, with just enough hops. Solid.

UPDATED: MAR 18, 2010 Pours clear red with a small dissapearing head and the best lacing I have ever seen.  Aroma is cherries, peaches, some orange peel and yeast with hops in the background.  Tastes tart with some caramel, candies, and mild hops.  Very refreshing. Finish is grapefruit but not terribly bitter.  Excellent beer all around.
Draft:  Poured an amber color with a nice head.  The aroma was malts and lager.  The flavor was caramel malts, toasted nuts and grains.  Overall this brew was an easy drinker.  Keep it coming!

Amber pour with an offwhite head.  Aroma is deep toasted caramel malt and light hops.   Mouthful is crisp and sweet, persistent caramel malts throughout with some noble hop bitterness.  Light and refreshing, very pleasant.

Been waiting a long time to rate this bottle.  Nose full of grain, caramel, toast, a little earthy and wood.  Biscuit.  Body is a beautiful, clear amber leaning toward ruby, with a rocky tan head.  Taste is as above but with smoky accents and light nutty notes.  Sweetish and earthy, rich toffeeish malt, complex.  Crisp medium body, smooth and meaty, very quaffable, low and persevering bitterness, dries out somewhat.  Very good!

12-oz. Pours a murky dark amber with a loose off-white head that fades quickly away to a ring of foam. Rich caramel nose with earth and wet leaves under that. Creamy medium body with soft but active carb. Earthy deep mid-palate, also showing caramel and wet leaves. Nice typical malt-rich amber, very solid.
Bottle To Pint.   Nice Earthy aroma followed by a wonderful semisweet caramel taste. Nice beer

Bottle. Pours a very clear, red-amber with a thin layer of head. Only a tiny bit of lacing (a few patches here and there) Not much of an aroma.Taste is like a roasted carmel, a tiny bit sweet and hoppy.

Bottle from my Secret Santa. Deep amber pour with a thin off white head. Smooth crisp caramel malt taste with a touch of noble hop bitterness. Earthy hops and some caramel round out the aroma. Very nice session brew.

Bottle, pours a clear reddish brown with a thick tan head. Aroma  is not existant. Taste,  is much like the aroma not a lot there. a little malt but outside of that nothing. very cloe to drinking water. lousy beer.

12 ounce bottle from Chicken Chucks. Pours a clear amber with a medium white head. A smooth rich malty nose, caramel and toffee. The flavor is similar; smooth caramel, toffee, slight oxidation, rich fruity malts. Nice.

12 oz. bottle from Baba Budans, their December 2009 beer of the month ($2.25!).  Pours a clear amber color with a small off-white head.  Aroma of toast, caramel, hops, dried fruits, and earthy notes.  The flavor is also nice and toasty, with minimal hop bitterness to go along with the caramel malt sweetness and light roastiness.  Light-medium bodied, with active carbonation and a crisp, almost sugary-sticky mouthfeel.  Easy to drink, and a good year-round go-to beer from Great Lakes.  I couldnt believe I hadnt rated this yet.
Refrigerated botte.  Pours a deep amber red color.  The taste is dominated by heavy earthy hops with some malt sweetness.  Not a big fan of the style.  This brew is certainly not a session beer.

72oz growler from brewpub.  nose is good roasty, biscuity malt with hint of aromatic savory spice.  malt forward without being too sweet, subtle hopping does the trick.  translucent dark amber with good carb and bitter lacing.  some fruitiness shines through in finish.

This is a fantastic lager that can be purchased many places throughout Chicago in bottle form.  Aroma is mostly malty, lightly roasted and a hint of caramel.  Very easy to drink with a fantastic light malt aftertaste, but crisp at the same time.
Amber color with good head. Tastes of caramel, malt, and licorice. Very good example of the style.

Location: 12 oz bottle from jcos, 11/22/09 


Aroma: The nose has lots of caramel, toffee, and sweet fruits, with notes of cereal/bread and earthy hops

Appearance: Pours a clear amber color with a disappearing off-white head and light lace

Flavor: Flavor is medium-high sweetness, with a bit of earthy bitterness for balance

Palate: The body is light-medium, with some lively carbonation, and a somewhat sticky mouthfeel

Overall Impression: 
Overall, this is turns out to be a well-structured and tasty beer, maybe a drop too sweet for my palate, but very good none-the-less.  One that works well as both a highly drinkable brew, and a nice example of its style.  Truly a nice beer that, that you might say even borders on being "Untouchable" (sorry, I couldnt resist, it was just too easy...)  No, its not quite that good, but it is really solid, and I cant pass up an easy joke.
Nice amber almost red color.  Good head and aroma is full of caramel and other sweet smells.  Very smooth tasting with caramel and nice malt flavors, would definitely recommend.

Sampled at 2009 Pittsburgh Brufest. Poured a nice amber color with a frothy white head that left some lacing. Basic malty aroma. Good flavors of caramel malt, wheat, and some fruit. Not usually a big fan of this style but this was definitely good.

(Bottle, Monks Café, Wallingatan, Stockholm) Amber colour with brief, frothy, beige head. Malty, slightly fruity nose with caramel, toasted grain, apricots and orange peel. Malty taste with notes of toasty grain, caramel, a touch of orange and apricots. Turning into a bready finish with a mild, spicy bitterness and a touch of sweetness. Well balanced and tasty beer.
UPDATED: NOV 21, 2009 this is a pretty nice amber lager. nice rye and hops noticeable, and a little sweet. not my favorite style, but this was a nice beer.
From a bottle. Excellent brew.  Amber color, good malty aroma.  quite smooth with a sweet malty taste.
This has a rich, malty aroma and a nice ruby amber color. The flavor is smooth and quite tasty for a lager, with a whopping 6.2% to boot. This is one of the best lagers Ive ever tasted.

12oz bottle.  great copper/amber color.  just right 2-finger head, maybe a touch of fruit in the nose?  Sweet, caramel malt flavor with an immediate, but light bitterness that sticks through the finish.  A bit of toasted bread?  Very good.

355mL. Awesome. Poured a clear amber with an enormous yellow head that has awesome retention and leaves excellent lacing. Spicy rye aroma with some strawberries, All-Bran cereal, cream of wheat, caramel malt, cornbread, brown sugar....very earthy. Taste is excellent: massive hop backbone with rye toast, earthiness, buttered biscuit. A killer session beer! LIke drinking spiked brown sugar cream of wheat.

Bottle.  Deep red pour with a head that lasts throughout.  Aroma is full of a sweet malt caramel and hops.  Flavor is the same with a touch of honey.  I was expecting to get over poured with hops on this one, but I enjoyed this a lot.
Bottle.  Amber pour.  Light tan head.  Hops, caramel, honey and bready notes.   Flavor is sweet and has some caramel, honey, yeast and hops.  Pretty good stuff.

Pours a deep dark red amber with a off white head with a red hue. Aromas of burnt hops and malts like caramel. Flavor is a little bready with undertones of caramel and crisp hops with a sort of earthy overtone like it was aged or barreled. Clean finish. For some reason when I drink this, its like Im drinking an "old school" kinda beer.
Pours a very attractive deep amber color and clear ... off white head sweet caramel malty aroma and sweet malt caramel taste slight bitter finish medium body this is a good one

I tried the Great Lakes Oktoberfest before this... and they seem like identical beers to me... So yeah, this pours a deep amber, nice frothy tan head... not much of an aroma... Really malty, almost zero bitterness.... A great session beer.. I actually really like this stuff, and its great for football season

I grew up near the GLBC so I am very familiar with their products.  I had Eliot Ness for the first time at a recent wedding that had a variety of GL beers.  I enjoyed it the most out of what was presented.  I nice smooth taste to it.

12 oz bottle (Wine Works, Springfield, OH) - Aroma: low toasted (malt) Appearance: reddish amber color, clear, and white head; Flavor: low toasted (malt), malty, dry finish, low to mod bitter; Mouthfeel: mod body, med carbonation; Overall: dry, complex malty, hopped beer.

Bottle. We finally got this in eastern PA.  Aroma light toast and dirt.  Pours a nice amber with a lasting head. Flavor is a light caramel and strong bitter hop to it. Palate overall is good nice balance though its bitterness endures.  Overall nice.

Date: August 09, 2009
Mode: Bottle
Source: Tasting, Ticker
Appearance: clear dark amber, fine beige head, drippy lace
Aroma: lightly sweet caramel malt aroma, nice bready character, light earthyness
Flavor: rich bready malt flavor, light caramel sweetness balanced by plenty of earthy hops, light bitterness
Aroma: 6/10; Appearance: 7/10; Flavor: 6/10; Palate: 6/10; Overall: 13/20
Rating: 3.2/5.0Drinkability: 7/10
Score: **+/4

Clear, glassy reddish orange. Big creamy head. Tiny, slow carbonation bubbles. Head is proud and sturdy.

The smell is earthy amber malt. A mild flowery hop. Rich and bready. Estery to balance the gritty malt. Darn good.

The malt is still earthy like soil, but also German bitter. A little flowery in the hop with a bitter citrus spice. Not bad. Caramel and butterscotch at the tail end. Hops poke through with more warmth.

The feel is smooth but with a gritty, rougher texture at the swallow. A solid amber. Balanced, earthy, bitter and flavorful.

Bottled. Deep amber color with cherry tints. Big hop bitterness with medium to full Vienna malt flavor. Smooth and well rounded with a strong, hoppy finish. the malt is slightly over-run by the bitterness, but altogether an interesting, flavorful interpretation.
smooth malt aroma with spice and toast. A touch of alcohol too. Caramel, brown suger, vanilla, and brown bread. Just enough bitterness to balance the malt.

UPDATED: AUG 26, 2009 Caramel malts dominate the aroma with a hint of hops hiding under the surface.  Solid start to this surprising lager.  The appearance is wonderful.  Beautiful deep amber pour with an off white head.  Never seen a lager look this one.  Beautiful beer and an easy drinker.  Similar to the nose, caramel malt dominates with a touch of hops on the end.  Pretty full bodied for the style, perfectly carbonated.  Would love to have this available on a regular basis.  Well done Great Lakes.

Bottle from Archer Liquor. Pours reddish copper with a foamy off-white head. Aroma of sweet caramel. Near medium body with foamy carbonation. Flavor is caramel and odd bits like nuts and stuff. Flavors arent weak. Its not very bitter, and thats how it finishes. Ok amber. Maybe better than ok, but more something would be better yet. Finishes more sweet than bitter, but it is rather smooth. If less than bitter is your thing, you will love this.

Bottle via trade.  Copper color with a lasting white head.  Aroma is sweet malt, grain, and brown sugar - not too pronounced overall.  Flavor, however, is great, with caramel malt, nuts, brown sugar, and a little bit of citrusy/earthy hops on the finish.  Smooth, creamy palate thats fairly full for a vienna.  High overall rating because its excellent for the style.
12oz bottle. copper color.  Aroma of malted body, nice caramel.  Flavor of pale malts, some wood notes.  Aged very well, nice lagering.  Well balanced.  Not my type of beer, still really good.

Hard to believe I havent rated this - good thing I grabbed some on the way through Ohio - this is very malt-forward, even for a vienna, but its got a nice buttery character, and some biscuity dryness on the back that acts as a good transition to the beers hoppy finish - a bit of fruity character and nutty qualities throughout - this brewery does great things with lagers.

tobacco, winey smell, malt and dark sugar. it is darky ruby in the glass with a head that laces. it has a sticky grape,wine taste, burnt malts dry but with a burnt sugar taste. dry and oily mouthfeel. incredibly good
This is a very nice beer.  Candied cherry aromas and flavor with a lingering finish.  Enjoyed this very much.
Aroma is roasted nuts, grainy malt.  Flavor is similar with more a more sugary malt.

355 mL bottle.  Copper orange with a small white head.  Malty aroma with a touch of earthy hops.  Smooth malty flavour, with just enough hops to balance the sweetness, without getting in the way of the caramel.  Just a nice, drinkable beer; nothing fancy.

Are we alone in this infinitely vast and yet tiny world we live in? Are there creepy crawlies that go bump in the night? Is Bigfoot real? Does the loch really have a Ness? I dont have the answers to those and other burning questions of mythology, but I can offer you an alternative. He is smaller than his motherly namesake, but the Eliot Ness that I hold in my hands is an amber lager from Great Lakes Brewing. Based in Cleveland, Ohio, Great Lakes has an amazing standard portfolio of which Elliot Ness is part one of them. Based not on myth but fact, historically speaking the Eliot Ness is named after Mr. Eliot Ness himself, a notorious agent and advocate of prohibition in the 1920s. Ok, a bit removed from being front page news in the latest Enquirer, but far more invigorating and fascinating, and if nothing else, definitely controversial for this beer geek.


He burbles and boils over in my glass as a copper-tinged head churns above deep amber depths with brilliant copper highlights reflecting in my eyes. While his head holds fast, his nose captures my rapt attention with toast glazed in sweet, crunchy caramelized sugars. A bouquet of floral esters and fields of grass carry under it a soft whisper of lemon, melon, and orange. Sweet, toasty, and rich with nutmeg and cinnamon sticks adding the final touch. Amber lagers and amber ales are rather incongruous unto themselves, but there is usually a reasonable level of uniformity and expectancy. So far, the Eliot Ness from Great Lakes has performed admirably. I throw all inhibitions to the wind and dive headfirst into the deep-end. Effervescent and vibrant, the top of my tongue tingles with fresh lemons and key limes while a sweet, meaty undercurrent of oranges and cantaloupe lingers with a tropical kiss. Each quaff leaves trails of lace sticking to the sides of my glass, much like his honey sweetness sticks to my lips. His malty finish is subtle and lightly crunchy with soft grains, toast, and caramelized sugars. Rinse and repeat; each quaff is admirably refreshing and soothing at the same time. A growing presence of dryness on top of my tongue hints of bitter lemon skins. There is something to be said about a good session beer, but Ill have to get back to you on that because my glass is empty.


UFOs are still Unidentified Flying Objects, Bigfoot apparently has big feet, and Eliot Ness is anything but mythical. I imagine that no matter what fate may have conspired during those tumultuous days, a pint of amber in hand would have made it all OK.
Pours a nice rich amber color with a tan head.  Aroma is malty, caramel, biscuit, and some light spicy notes.  Flavor is caramel, biscuit, malty, and a nice spicy finish.

Presentation: It was poured from a brown 12oz bottle into a pint glass. It was sampled on 6-4-09 and had a best before date of 6-19-09 on the label. 

Appearance: The body has an inviting deep reddish amber color with very good clarity. On top there is a modest sized, just off white colored head that hangs on well and makes some nice lacing on the glass.

Smell: The aroma has some sweet and toasted malty character with light mineral and leafy hop notes.

Taste/Mouth: Its flavor has a sweet malty and toasted bread base with notes of brown sugar, caramel and toasted malt. Hop flavor is solid and matches the sweetness of the malt with earthy, leafy and mineral flavors and balanced bitterness. The finish has toasted grains and hops fading slowly off the tongue. Its texture is smooth and slick with soft carbonation.

Notes: This is an outstanding Vienna Lager!!! The balance of sweet, toasty and hops is spot on. Well done Great Lakes!!!

Bottle. Amber brown pour, minimal carbonation and a pronounced nutty and caramel aroma.  Flavor is rich, silky, sweet caramel and finished with a little bitterness.  Decent beer, but nothing too amazing.

Bottle. Aroma is some caramel and funk. A bit of bread. Pours a really nice shade of red. Taste is a whole lot of odd sweetness, some sweat, and a mystery fruit. It all seems to come together pretty well for what it is, with a strange dry aftertaste. Better than the last Vienna I had.

12 oz from Weilands Gourmet Market.  Pours dark amber with an off-white head.  Nose is bread, malt, toast, caramel, and sweetness.  Flavor is smooth toasted malt, caramel, sweet and fruity (plum?), with nice depth.  Finish is sweetness in this medium-bodied Vienna.  Outstanding.
12oz bottle. amber color, small, lasting fluffy tan head. aroma of hops and a bit of sweetness. love the taste. nice balance between the hop and malt, the finish being very smooth.

Some head with decent lacing.  Dark orange-brownish body.  Strong floral hop aroma belies a very balanced brew.  Significant but not overbearing hoppy bitterness with a well-balanced chocolate malt presence.

(bottle from OSLO) Pours out dark amber with a thin white head that quickly subsides.  The aroma is nice and toasty initially, with scents of light caramel and peanut brittle.  As this warms a vegetal aroma arises, and lends a stir-fried pea pod quality to the aroma.  The taste was also quite toasty and salty, which reminded me of roasted peanuts.  There is a light sweetness in the beginning as well.  The finish is fairly dry and lightly bitter with a medium mouthfeel and smooth carbonation.  A simple, yet easily approachable and downright drinkable beer.  Thanks Al!

[Bottle] Pours clear reddish-amber with a small beige head. Aroma is floral hops, snap peas, and some alcohol. Taste has lots and lots of barley, light sweetness up front, and some subdued bitterness. Medium-thin mouthfeel, very smooth, and has an extremely long finish. Very simple, but enjoyable, and something that would be an outstanding session beer.

Bottle.  Clear deep crimson with a medium to large white head.  Grainy, light malt, touch of sweetness.  Thin to medium body, lightly sweet, touch of caramel.  Finishes with almost a hint of a metallic twang, and a refined gentle bitterness.

Bottle.  Pours dark amber with a foamy beige head.  Aroma is slightly hoppy, yet smooth and balanced.  Flavor is a perfect blend of hops and malt; this beer is neither too bitter nor too malty.  Pretty good.

I had this on tap, it poured a nice dark color.  I didnt know what kind of beer it was when I ordered it, and I was wary, thinking it might have been a stout when it arrived at the table because it was pretty dark.  It had a nice malty caramel aroma.   Tasted pretty good too.  It was sweet, but had a nice mouthfeel, light carbonation and a pretty malty taste.  Overall, pretty good beverage.

From a bottle. Pours dark brown/amber. Simultaneously nutty and hoppy aroma. Extremely well-balanced and drinkable. A nice level of chocolatey roast inter-mingled with a fresh dose of hops and precise carbonation. One of those beers you can drink all night. Different and tasty enough to be fantastic.

12 oz. bottle. Pours copper with thin off-white head. Aroma is malty with pine notes and slight alcohol. Taste is sweet caramel malt and nuts with a nice hop finish. Extremely well balanced. A little too dry in the finish perhaps. Still, this might be the best dark lager Ive ever had--admittedly Im not usually an aficionado of the style. Very good, worth seeking out.

Dark amber pour from a 12oz bottle. Two fingers of off whit ehead that collapses with lacing down the sides of the glass. Malty aroma with gentle hops and slight ethanol overtone. Overall tasty beer - sweet malt at the start with a hoppy bite at the finish, well balanced. A litttle on the sweet side but not in a bad way.

I dont even know what the hell a Vienna is.  I just consider this an Amber Lager.... which I guess is apparently a Vienna.  Hmm...ok interesting.  Anyways, I only drink this on tap at the Sports Deck in Kettering because its the best beer they have available. It has a nice deep amber color and decent aroma.  Flavor is mild to moderate sweet and malty.  Some caramel. Crisp finish.
Bottle at a restaurant, no glass.  Aroma is hoppy and grassy with maltier bud lite flavor and some carbonation.  Finishes dry and forgetable.  Find this boring maybe I just dont like the style.

Brewed in the USA....... Courtesy of The Capt, thanks Mark !!  Pours a copper color with a medium foamy head. Aroma is of caramel, sweet malts and toffee. Taste of biscuits, nuts and caramel . This Vienna style is clean, sweet and very enjoyable !!!
12oz bottle. Pours a brownish red color. with medium off white head. Aroma of caramelized malt. Taste sweet, and somewhat reminds me of an oriental taste.

pours an amber red with a sweet malty taste.  Really a great vienna.

12 oz. bottle

12oz, thanks kmyers8807! Pours clear dark orange with a thick and lacy pale orange head. Piles of sweet caramel and bread in the aroma. Medium-full body and light carbonation. Full, rounded taste of stewed prunes, caramel, nuts and noble hops. Dry finish. Nice balance.
Bottle. Pours a reddish orange with a thick creamy head. Aroma is malty, almost orange scented. Tastes of wood, pine, with a sharp hop bite that fades to a caramelly aftertaste. A well balanced beer.

Rich copper, barely tan head.  Dry caramel roast aroma.  Fairly full bodied, dry and dusty, though not like old stale malt, this is woodsy with a brown sugar finish.  Maybe heavy for the style, but I enjoyed it.

Enjoyed via draft and 12 oz bottle.  Pours a light to medium copper color.  Notes of Munich malt dominate the nose, almost rendering one the feeling of being in a pub in Vienna, or perhaps at some large festival eating bratwurst.  Similar notes come through in the palate.  A wondrous malt note - simple in terms of flavor, but extremely satisfying - comes through on the palate.  This is easily the best Vienna Lager Ive ever tasted, and, for the money, one of the best beers made in the United States.

Bottle. Pours a deep brown amber color with a smaller head.  Aroma is sweet caramel and malts.  The taste is surprisingly sweet and matly.  Palate was nice, but too sweet to drink more than a few. . . Not sure if this is typical of a vienna

Bottle. A bright copper color body with a medium sized white head,medium carbonation,nice spotty lacing . Aroma is awesome  light toasty grains and bread with just a bit of sweet fruit and spicy hops. Flavor is as good as the aroma fruity,spicy,smokey,very balanced,very complex,toasty nutty caramel, a crisp full mouthfeel,very quaffable, A very very good brew

 Thank you GLB , nice work !

Bottle.  Pours a rich amber with a thin head.  Aroma is sweet malts and yeast.  Notes of bread, pine, caramel, and hops come out as well.  Taste is hoppy than I expected, but the finish is dry and stronf with malts and dark fruit.  I am not a big lager fan, but this one is drinkable.

Bottle - Beautiful copper pour with a big foamy head. Sweet caramelly malt on teh nose -- smells clean and crisp. Taste is hoppier than I expected -- theres a good snap when the beer hits the back of your mouth. I actually want a bit more malt to balance it, though its still very drinkable. Smooth and non-offensive in the mouth. Nice, clean, and sessionable.
bottle.  Poured amber with a nice head.  A very smooth med. mouth feel.  Balanced like most Great Lakes brews Ive tried.  Very stout like and very drinkable.

Sweet ass bottle. Eliot Ness is the man. Nice clear amber color with a decent sized head.Really great smell of malt and some hops. Real drinkable but with some great hops and a hint of sweet malt
This beer tastes awesome! Definitely my favorite Great Lakes to this point would buy again
user_location: The World of Beer, Texas, USA

text: Pours a clear copper/brown color with a medium head. Good head retention and lacing. Aroma of sweet malts, grain, caramel and hops with a bit of a pine note. Taste is toasted malts with sweet-like fruit notes and grassy hops. Light-to-medium bodied.   Smooth, and very easy to drink.
This was awesome. So rich and creamy. Nice body and wonderful aroma. Bready, yeast some spice and a light hop presence. Taste is smooth and highly drinkable.

Thanks George.
I poured this bottle into my Pilsener glass and it produced a finger worth of white head that turned to a thick lace. The body of the brew was amber to brown.

Aromas of caramel malts and bread filled my head. The flavor was malt forward and with a light bitter finish. It had a nice light and crisp feel in my mouth with great carbonation.

I really like drinking these great lagers; it is a great change of pace
UPDATED: JUL 5, 2009 Pours a lovely amber with a nice head.  Slightly hoppy, balanced with malt and a little bitterness. Excellent stuff.
Poured amber with a white head. Aroma of caramel and fruit. Sweet candy caramel with a hint of fruit. Not bad.

Bottle.  Amber hue, thin head.  Nose is a balance of hops and malt.  Smooth body, taste similar to aroma- sweet malt and faint hops for balance.  This isnt terribly complex, but I dont think thats what they were going for either.  This is a real nice quaffer.  Reminds me of a Sam Adams Boston Lager with a touch of cinnamon at the end and a bit more alcohol present.  Well made.
copper pour with small white head. greta amber lager, i will drink this again

12 oz bottle.  Pours copper with an average fizzy off white head.  Smells of roasted grain and caramel.  Some tastes of hops, but mostly roasted malt, toffee, and bread crust.  Aftertaste is bitter.  Nice body and mouthfeel.
Good beer to give a non beer drinker.  i really like this beer.  will drink again

12 oz. bottle from the Binnys Singles Rack (Orland Park, IL). I may have a cellar full of beers that need to be drank.. but somehow I cant pass the Binnys Singles Rack! Curses! Pours a beautiful sunstruck copper, dark notes, transparent, well carbonated, with moderate khaki head that subsides to a decent amount and laces. Aromas apparent straight from the pour with very nice toasty malt notes, biscuits, toffee, and bready notes without being too intimidating. Light hoppy bouquet, but malt dominant. Initial has a good body for the style, light but sustaining, having nice bready and biscuity malts balanced with a very formidible bitter noble hoppiness. Very well balanced, light, yet extremely flavorful as the malt sticks to the palate, and the hops balance and stick to the aftertaste. This is a wonderful sessioner! Cheers!

Wow!  Just wanted to get that out there first.  Ok.  12 oz bottle, pours a lovely reddish amber color, significant head, great lacing.  Aroma is caramel malt, toffee.  Flavor is a strong berry taste up front, surprisingly, followed by a wash of malt and hops.  Caramel aftertaste.  Body is a bit thin, but not too thin.  Overall, this is excellent.
A typical micro but a great brew pub if you get the chance.  Amber color, creamy head.  Maybe a touch of spice.  Good but nothing special.

UPDATED: JUL 4, 2010 Draft. Included as part of a sampler at the brewpub in Cleveland. I remembered liking pretty much everything but do not remember specifics.  Do remember that they have an excellent brewpub with excellent beer.

7/2/10 - Had another one of these while at an Indians game passing through Cleveland. Better than average for ballpark beer but did not find it to be anything special this time around.

Bottle bought in WI.
Good rust amber color.  Nose - mix of pines and sweetness like caramel. Flavor - Roasted malt, sweet apples, broen sugar. Finish - Hops dryness with bitter-sweetness. Interesting!

12oz bottle.  A deep unfiltered amber-brown color.  Malty brewery mash smell.  Amber and caramel malts dominate the flavor, with a far off balanced hopping which adds some crispness.  Smooth and sweet.  This one is past the best by date and shows in the aroma, I certainly remember the fresher version with higher regard.
Bottle.  Pours amber with a creamy head. Aroma:  Sweet malty nose. Malty with just a little hop bite at the end.

Bottle thanks to ilovedarkbeer. Pours with a large, foamy, off-white head and a clear copper body underneath. Good lacing and retention. Aroma of honey, caramel and honey comb cereal with a hint of hop. Taste is cereal, huskiness and caramel.  Lively bubbles and a dry mouthfeel.
bottle. had this one with some enchiladas, what a choice. great malty flavors with a good balance of hops. nice clean finish. nice medium body. a very very satisfying drink, indeed.
Not a real fan of ambers but this is very good. Nice head and lace. Finishes clean and dry. Recommend to anyone just starting to try something other than the usual.
Reddish amber in color with a nice persistent off white head.  Good smell that has a balance of hop and malt.  Nice hop bite in the taste that fades into a light malty sweetness.
12oz.  Pours a good reddish copper with a decent head.  Aroma is mostly grass and sweet malt.  Body is surprisingly dry and hoppy, perhaps a bit soft on the palate.

12 ounce bottle courtesy of dankman38. Pours a clear reddish brown color with a medium head. Good head retention and lacing. Aroma of sweet malts, grain, caramel and hops with a bit of a soapy note. Taste is toasted malts with peach-like fruit notes and grassy hops. Medium bodied.

Poured from the bottle into a double walled pint glass.  Pour produced a dark amber body, topped with an off white head of foam, featuring decent lacing.  Sweet, nutty aroma, kind of like pecan pie.  Crisp mouthfeel, with a sour flavor, crossing over to dry bitterness at the end.  Citrus notes on the palate, with a dry hops note lingering at the end.  The beer goes down easily enough, though the bitterness lingers a little too long for my liking.
From bottle... poured amber with small white head. It was sparkling too. Aroma was nutty with some hops. Somewhat sweet flavor with slightly bitter ending. Not great, but nice.

12oz bottle. Pours a clear amber body with a small, creamy, beige head that dissipates slowly and leaves a nice lacing. Aroma is malt dominated with a good amount of caramel and toffee. Some nuttiness and hop characters. Taste is similar to the aroma. Well rounded and sweet. Finishes with a little bit of lingering bitterness. Medium bodied and creamy. Overall, its a nice, smooth, easy drinking beer that doesnt stand out, but is quite enjoyable.
Bottle. Pours amber with minimal off white head. Aroma is malty, caramel, slight hop citrus. Flavor starts sweet, finishes slightly bitter from hops. Dry finish with a slight bitterness.

Great Lakes Eliot Ness is a very clear, very sparkling amber beer with a very dense, creamy, off-white head that shows outstanding retention and lacing.  It has a very fresh, malty aroma with maybe a bit of citrus.  It has a medium-light body with a dry finish.  It’s a mellow flavor that’s a touch sweet, with a slightly fruity bitterness.

Bottle.  Poured a clear amber color with minimal tan head.  Had a hint of caramel melt and grassy hops in the aroma.  Beer had a light body, thin texture, soft carbonation, and an abrupt finish.  The flavor was somewhat sweet, somewhat bitter.  Overall, I have never been a fan of amber beers and this one did not change that opinion.  This may not be the best opinion to judge this beer on, but I was not a fan.
Very nice amber color, with a light head, there isnt really much aroma. but there is some lacing when drinking it.  The taste has hops. with some caramel.

I’m starting to run out of things to say about all these beers.  The problem is that this, like so many is a good beer, but its not great, there’s nothing to put this in my upper echelon, so in a few months I’ll most likely forget all about it.
Nice copper like pour, with a small light beige color head. Nice malt smell, and taste with a hint of caramel and hops. Well done beer.

Orange-copper pour with a thin straw colored lace and little head.  Big earthy biscuit malt aroma with a hint of molasses, honey, cinnamon, and some ale yeast fruitiness that I can’t quite place.  Lots and lots of chewy bread, dough, biscuit, and caramel malt flavors with some fresh fruit and spicy hops on the finish.  Solid medium body with plentiful carbonation and a crisp finish.  A very tasty and complex, almost ale like lager.
Bottle.  Pours an amber body, sweet and malty.   Light hoppiness, caramel malt bready with a touch of nuttyness.  A solid lager!

12oz bottle served in a lager glass. Beautiful sunset amber body topped by nearly two inches of lasting off-white head. The nose is very balanced with some nice malt sweetness and spicy hops struggling for dominance. Flavors of bread, toffee, nuts, and grass. Hops win the battle at the finish though not by much. Superb balance throughout. An excellent, well crafted lager.

12 oz. bottle. Pours a clear, beautiful amber-red with a frothy beige head that lasts throughout and leaves good lacing. The aroma is sweet malt. Flavor is sweet malty goodness with a hint of caramel.  Nice hop balance.  Light to medium body. Finish is short and sweet.
12oz bottle.  Pours a dark amber, almost red with a 2 inch head.  Sweet and roasty aroma.  Flavor is sweet caramel with subtle hops on the finish.  Not my favorite style, but very well put together.
Bottle@Home. Fruity, herbal aroma with a hint of rust. Amber color, beige head, good lace. Very sweet, malty, light bitter, fruity, hint of cookies. Quite full, almost syrupy. Well balanced.
Amber pour with gooey head and lace. Aroma of roasted malt. A maltiness balanced by a decent medium bitter. Medum bodied with good carbonation. A pretty special beer overall.
bottle. has a bit of a roasted aroma. pours a nice amber color with a thick light tan head. has a very good carmel taste with a very smooth finish.

Pours a beautiful ruby/amber with a thin white head.  Aroma is dominated by malt, with some notes of caramel and some roast.  Like the aroma, flavor is dominated by malt balanced by a good hop finish.  Another enjoyable offereing from GLBC.
Clear ruby red with nice thick off white head.  Aroma is sweet malts with nice citrus hops. Flavor is the same but more sweet.  Finishes clean.

12 oz bottle, about 1.5 weeks past its best by date.  Pours clear amber with a small white head.  Malty biscuit aroma, slightly sweet honey.  Sweet honey biscuit flavor with a touch of hops.  Honey mostly gives way to more biscuit after a few sips.  This is a good, flavorful lager.
Draught @ Cole’s. Clear amber with thick off-white head. Bright hoppy aroma over a bready body. Quaffable with medium carbonation. Nice bready character. Diggin it.
12oz bottle.  Pours a clear, medium amber color with a reddish tint.  Nose of toasted malt with some hops.  Flavor carried hop bitterness with a very clean finish.
Getting notebook online. Bottle. Beautiful red amber with a creamy head. Crisp fruity nose. Taste begins with bitters with a sweet fruity finish. Enjoy this one with a pizza. Very good.

Had this in the bottle at Gracie’s underground in Ferndale, MI. I got this beer because of it’s name, and not really knowing the style, but I figured that any beer named after the man responsible for prohiibition was worth a shot.  It pours a hazy amber, with a good head. The flavor was a little too bitter for me. It was quite malty, with some piney notes right on the finish. Not a bad beer, but nothing I would ever get again.

From bottle.  August Dayton Beer Tasting event - Favorite Summer Brews.   
Pours a amber color with a decent off-white head. Very malty aroma with more hops than expected.  Good mouthfeel with a lingering floral taste.  A very good Vienna lager.......

Bottle.  Pours pefectly celar amber with a thin off-white head.  No lacing.  Aroma is potently malty, rich with some evident hop notes.  Some spicy hops on the tongue, bready malt and a nice lingering bitteness.  Quite good for a Vienna!  Full bodied.
typical amber pour, beige head. Nice malt profile, and just enough hops. Extremely well balanced, and i could drink this forever. One of the most balanced beers i have ever had, a true session beer.

Reminds me a lot of a Sam Adams... only slightly better.  Pours a nice amber color with small head and decent lacing.  Smell of hops and sweet malt are present. Mouth feel is quite heavy for a lager.  Spicy and crisp hop finish with a bit of sweetness.

Pours a reddish amber color with a one-finger off-white head.  Aroma is mostly malty, with some hops and sweetness in the offering.  Spicy hoppyness is evident as it comes across the tongue.  Medium mouthfeel with a lingering floral taste.  Nice beer.

12 oz. bottle.  Pours amber with a medium sized frothy cream head.  Aroma is caramel, malt, biscuit, and overall very inviting.  Taste follows with rich malt sweetness and a surprising hop bite in the finish to keep it from being too cloying.  Incredibly drinkable.
12oz bottle. Pours deep amber with a nice creamy head. Perfectly balanced malts and hops with subtle caramel sweetness make this an extremely drinkable brew. A real winner.

WARNING! May have had a bad sample, based on others’ ratings. The aroma was malt-dominated with slight hop overtones. Taste is lacking hops completely and malt tastes funny. Not a good funny either. Cloying sour flavor with minimal sweetness. Strange from such a malty brew. Disappointing. There are much better ambers out there.

12oz - Nice amber pour under dark tan head, substantial froth of small bubbles.  Honey on nose.  Light wood in the front, offsetting a bitter, flat aftertaste.  This tastes like a bad bottle.  Looking at nearby recent ratings I’m wondering if they’ve had a bad batch.

UPDATED: APR 27, 2010 4/27/2010  Pours a deep beautiful amber with a tan creamy head that leaves these terrific legs behind to lust after.  The aromas are rich with smells of biscuits, dough, and fresh baked bread, which is, of course, a wonderful aroma to enjoy.  The malts really come out nice in this one.  There is also this spring field, flowery smell coming through as well, not so much like a hoppiness, but more the smell of clover flower.  Very unique.  There is a level of deepness to this beer that is just terrific.  The incredible aromas of a bakery transfer terrifically to the palate...not only does it smell like fresh baked bread, but it also tastes like it.  There is also a nuttiness that is a real treat.  This is a really good beer, very sessionable, just all around a real pleasure.  


8/9/2008 On tap at brewery.  Pours a lovely carmel color.  The head is cream colored and is wonderfully thick and full.  It remains throughout and laces the glass nicely.  The aroma is malty and spicy.  The flavor is noticably hoppy with some light spice and caramel notes.  Finishes rather dry along side the sweet malty background.

Glowing copper color with a tight head. Malty caramel aroma with mild pit fruit spiciness. Smooth medium body. Taste is malt driven caramel/toffee sweetness with some nice fruity floral flavors. Draft@ Lakes CLE airport.
user_location: Same Trailer, Different Park, Louisiana, USA

text: 12 oz bottle.  Poured a deep ruby red color with a small off-white head.  Aroma was very sweet malt.  Taste was malty with an aftertaste that was a little off.
Draught in a sampler at GBL. Clear coppery color. Thick in mouth with notable coffee and caramel malts.
Dark amber, malty, bitter, vegital ? metalic? strange.  I didn’t like it.

Pours brown in color with ruby brown highlights around the edges.  Nice frothy inch of head forms on the pour.  Smell is all malt and some sweetness.  Very metallic/off flavor in the taste.  Gets a bit cloying as well.  First beer I’ve had from Great Lakes that has been subpar.
Bottle shared by aspidites, attractive clear, bright yet dark amber pour, but the rest was downhil. Very vegital in the nose, and it carried into the flavor.

(Sampled 7-14-08 at Brownings Brewery) Dark amber in color, tan head that laced.  Faint aroma of malt.  Hits the mouth with a medium body, malt comes in nicely, a turpentine bitterness appears in the middle and lasts well after the finish.  Old keg?  Up for a rerate down the line...

Cleveland, Oh - Progressive Field - Indians/Twins game - 12 oz bottle. Medium copper pour, thick khaki colored head, nice lace. Hint of chocolate in the aroma. Sweet flavor with hints of caramel, toffee and some cotton candy. Thickish mouthfeel. Pretty solid.

I am not a big fan of Great Lakes, the finish  on most of their beers really puts me off for some reason and Eliot Ness follows suit.

Aroma is nice and sweet with hints orange.  Hints of orange hit me through the entire experience.  Color is and amber/orange with an off-white head.  Nice matly flavor up front that becomes more bitter towards then end and finishes with an odd bitter flavor that hangs in my mouth unenjoyably.

The thanks go out to Crizay tonight!  Pours reddish burnt orange with an off-white head, more substantial than German counterparts, but still dissipating.  Aroma of toast, toffee, slight dark fruit, light hazelnut.  Hops are faint, but fruity on the nose.  Well blended aroma.  Sweet caramel taste, some toffee, light bread crust and earthy dirtlike hop flavor.  Finishes with a leafy hop taste, toast, bark, with some lingering caramel flavor intermingling with the earthy bitterness.  Light mouthfeel, but full flavors make it seem better.  Medium carbonation.  This is very good, what more could you want from a Vienna?

Great Lakes Sample Pack from Woodmans Oak Creek. 
Great Color Red bordering burnt orange. Crystal clear, with impressive carbonation and an ivory head. Aroma is toffee, caramel, and a hint of roasted nuts. Flavor is mostly malt, with just enough hops to balance it out. Highly drinkable...clean and refreshing.

Poured reddish with a nice whitish head.  Nice sweetish aroma.  Good blend of maltiness and hop bite, kind of non-descript, but is very drinkable.  This brewery seems to do a consistenly good job with the middle of the road brew styles and making them a little more interesting.
user_location: from Michigan now in Charlotte, North Carolina, USA

text: First time rating this style so I can’t compare to others.  On tap, reddish amber with an impressive head.  Malty aroma with some nose tingling hops in there.  Sweet and bitter flavor almost like a backwards Burning River.  Very clean mouthfeel and finish.  This beer is not overpowering in any area but still has a lot of flavor.
12oz Bottle Pours out a nice amber topped with a cream head. Aroma of malt and a touch of hops. Tast more on the malty side with a light bitterness at the end. A good Vienna
Nice amber tone and fruity aroma.  has a somewhat sharp citrus taste with a smooth finish.

Bottle acquired via trade with polomagnifico...THANKS RYAN!!!  This is a great beer.  Of late, Ive noticed that many "amber" beers feel like they have to kick in an overwhelming amount of hops.  With Lagunitas Lucky 13, I thought it worked.  With Green Flashs Hop Head Red, I didnt.  This one is a throw back to the traditional amber we all used to know and love.  Red bordering burnt orange in color.  Crystal clear, with impressive carbonation and an ivory head that leaves significant lacing inside of the glass.  Aroma is toffee, caramel, and a hint of roasted nuts.  Flavor is mostly malt, with just enough hops to balance it out.  Highly drinkable...clean and refreshing.  Wish this was available in AZ!!!

Amber color......thick, fluffy head.  Faint malt aroma.  Sweet malt flavor in the front......slightly crisp mouthfeel.  Malty richness develops in the back, with a finish that has a slight bitterness.

Amber, red, Vienna?  Whatever the style, this lager bores me.  Maybe it is just the style that bores me because Eliot Ness is the top rated beer in its class.  Dark amber in color without much of an aroma, this beer is full of caramel malts and light hops.  But overall, this beer is pretty nondescript and not much in the way of unique or special flavors.

Tomato and fruity aroma. Reddish amber color with a miminimal head.  Flavor is lightly bitter with a sweet caramelized sugar balance.  Palate is medium creamy with a zippy carbonation.  Very good Vienna.

Oh my god im in heaven Bottle. Pours a dark amber color with a decent beige head. The aroma is caramel and toffee with some citrus and floral hops. The flavor is similar with the malts being ever so slightly more present than the hops. Overall this is pretty well balanced. Medium bodied with good carbonation.

In short: A fruity and slightly sweet dark larger.  Good beer but a bit overrated
How: Bottle 12oz, from Beerman6686.  Thanks a lot Dan!
The look: Clear amber body with a short-lived beige head
In long: Candy-like crisp toffee sweetness.  Quite a bit of dried fruits of all kinds, like taking mouthful of one of those grocery store mix-bag dried fruits.  I personally found the floral hopping insufficient.  This is a good beer and undoubtedly one of the best American dark lager Ive had.  But I pub-crawled the land of dark lagers (Czech Republic) and this Eliot Ness doesnt measure up to the good Czech Viennas, it barely measures up to the average Czech Viennas.  I basically found the quality reputation of this Eliot Ness as exaggerated as the real accomplishments of the man by the same name.

12 oz bottle.  Heres my simple analysis: this is one of the better lagers out there IMO, and I dont particularly like lagers.  It reminded me of SA Boston Lager, but fresher, less hops, and just a bit better.  If you like lagers you will probably like this.

bottle by way StFun. dark reddish copper color with a thin off white head. straight forward aromas of toffee, brown sugar, earthy hops and grain. same with the flavors... caramel grain, grass and  earthy prickly hops with a touch of tartness. bright and crisp dry finish cleans the palate nicely.  medium body with prickly carbonation. perfectly balanced easy drinker for the summer months... makes me wonder why beers like this are not made in AZ...
This beer was mighty tastey! It was rich in an reddish coloured pour. Soft fluffy medium sized head with malty taste. Caramel flavor was prevalent, and it was a really filling brew.
At Savor. Kick ass amber! Heavier than most viennas but who cares. Caramel and toffee throughout. Perfect malt/hop interplay with a tight slightly bitter dry finish. Yum

Bottle courtesy of mreusch. Best by 03/22/08. Pours a clear, dark copper with a finger of creamy, beige head. The nose is a fairly straightforward blend of  bready malt and lightly spicy/earthy hops. Medium-bodied and slick with creamy carbonation and a toasty, bitter finish. Toasted caramel malt with a solid noble-hopped backing; nicely balanced. Even past its "best by" date, this beer is well deserving of its status as the highest rated Vienna on this site. The next time I get the opportunity to buy more of this, I wont hesitate to do so. Thanks again for this bottle, Matt!

Forget where I got this one from, found in my cellar clean out recently. Pours out a nice clear amber with a thin two finger head. Aroma is nice and malty with a touch of bitterness. Taste is straight forward and very clean. Nice malty tastes with some good bite in there too. Drinkable
A really tasty beer. Pours a nice medium amber with medium head. Malty semi sweet taste and medium carbonation. A really fine lager that I will continue to drink

Pours clear, amber red.  Aroma of soft, toasty caramel malts.  Lagered touches of overripe red fruits and pears, with a drying waft of noble grassiness.  White pepper.  Toffee.  Pristinely clean.  Flavor of deep, toasty grains, slightly buttery, soaked in this calm, soothing fruit tone of blackberry and apple.  Glowing malt characters arrange themselves with artful care and precision.  Almost contemplative in its ease and simplicity.  Like fresh baked wheat bread, buttered warmly and lightly spiced, and taken with a side of unsweetened cranberries.  Medium body is generous and expansive in the mouth.  Finishes very cleanly, with the lightest kick of noble hops drawing out.  A smart, comfortable, pitch-perfect vienna.  Thanks Bill!
Bottle from Canals, Coppery amber pur with a caramel malt aroma. Sweet malt flavors that actually taste full in the mouth. There is a bitter finish to it but I liked it.

Sample at West Lakeview Liquors, Chicago, Great Lakes Tasting.  Interesting to see that this is the top-rated vienna.  Good job Great Lakes.  Darker amber color with medium off-white head.  Aroma is very much caramel and noble, spicy hops.  Flavor is along the same lines with some graininess as well.  Medium to thin body and well carbonated.  Not bad.

Pretty bitter, as compared to the typical beer i drink, but very good.  you can definitely taste the caramel and the hops.  i had this out of a great lakes variety pack.  i probably wouldnt buy it as its own six pack, because i like to drink a bunch of this flavors at a time.
UPDATED: APR 29, 2008 Tap good aroma pours with a thin white head taste of hops is just right a nice winner for this brewery. I shall get this on tap again when I visit this restaurant

This was in a great lakes variety pack, and I went into it thinking that I would "like" the beer, but not love it.  I was wrong.  This is a GREAT lager.  I was surprised to see that this thing that came with variety pack was the top rated Vienna...  Pours a nice amber, with a decent head that more or less lasts for the whole beer.  Tremendous malts, clean taste, and noble hops on the back end.  As one who normally finds lagers to be too "green" this one is as balanced as the day is long.  Malts lend a full mouthfeel to this one.  I will get this one again.

Bottle pours a dark amber color.  Has a thin white head that does not last very long.  Has a malty aroma followed by a medium mouthfeel.  Tastes like a lightly spicy malt brew with little hop flavor or aroma.  Good beer for the style.

Bottle courtesy of fiver29.  You da man John!  Pours a crystal clear amber color with a 2 finger head that creates spotty lacing.  Nose is grassy malts and a touch of sweet caramel.  Palate is thin, with sweet malt with a some citrusy hop bite at the end with a fairly dry finish.  Not bad.
Bottled. Golden and reddish in colour with a medium sized white head. Somewhat malty with notes of grain, grass and a hint of meltal.

UPDATED: APR 15, 2008 Pours a darker, but clear, reddish amber with a medium frothy/creamy off-white head, pretty nice pour for a vienna.   Sweet bready / toasty malt aroma.  Yum...great malt beer... ever so slightly toasty, buttery, and a bit of caramel.   The hops are in perfect light balance as a compliment to the malt.  Some breadiness...almost like rye.  Very soft and smooth palate.  This is an excellent Vienna.  FANTASTIC!

Bottle. Reddish amber color. Milk chocolate, caramel and pear in the aroma and flavor. Grassy hops and some black berries. Sweetish with a somewhat sticky mouthfeel, but well balanced. Tobacco in the aftertaste.

[Draft @ TDR SH] Poured a clear amber color with a small, white head that left nice lacing on the glass.  Aroma of nuts, caramel, toasted malts, and light floral hops.  Taste of sweeter caramel, light nuts, citrus fruits, toffee, light toast, and a bit of hops in the finish.

Bottle.
Clear orange coloured with a small off white head.
Sweet aroma of caramel and dried fruits with oxidated notes.
Sweet flavour of caramel and dried fruits with oxidated notes.

Bottle. Pours a transparent rusty red with a short light tan head. Aroma of light earthy, grassy/citrus hops, toasted malt, caramel, light booze soaked fruits. Flavors of caramel, candied fruit, earthy hops, bready toasted malt and even a tinge of light smoke. Medium body, sturdy carbonation...malty/sweet/slightly dry with a earthy/bittersweet/malty finish. Overall pretty well balanced all around...a great session brew for spring/fall.

A Mes rate: Bottle at Toms UGT Pt. 2.Dark amber with a thin white rim. Rich bready malt aroma. Roasted malt flavour with a bit of alcohol showing in the finish. Straight down the line and rather dull.
Bottle at the cads disco piere dance-off. Alround rating: The best of a bad bunch, malty one dimentional, sweetens up as it goes on, quite drinkable saves it.

bottle.  dark copper with clarity.  spotty off white head.  aroma is sweet.  caramel and roasted nuts.  remarkably smooth.  moderate roasted burnt malts, caramel and corn.  nicely balanced.  Id enjoy this beer any time.
amber to orange in appearence,poured with big soft light tan head,very nice mildness to hops arrangement , clean crisp and vaery easy drinking

Thanks to Miketd for this one.  It is the best Vienna I can remember having since traveling in central Europe.  Amber color and moderate carbonation.  Smooth, full malt flavor throughout, lightly roasted grain, mildly bitter, and some bread taste.
Deep amber with thin off-white head.  Aroma of caramel malt & light spice.  Pretty much the same in the taste with a mild dry finish.  Perhaps a little thin but overall pretty good.

Very good.  I think its nice to find a lager with character, and this is exactly that.  Its aroma is present with some hoppy notes.  Its appearance was a bit flat, but rather tempting still with its dark amber.  Its flavor a bit malty, a bit hoppy.  Its palate is exceptionally crisp and clean.  Solid stuff.
Bottle at Toms Glasgow tasting 2 ... Copper colour ... sweet yeasty nose ... yeasty fruity ... some malts ... bit dull nothing jum out but nothing offends

12 oz bottle:  Three words to describe Great Lakes Brewing "Consistently good beers"  not all of them knock it out of the park, but a lot of them are damn good.  Pours a clear amber color with a small sized carbonated tan head that lingers.  Aroma is caramel, roasty notes, almost a grainy fresh sweet corn note (not the corn note for Bud and other) candy, and sweet.  Taste is really nice rich caramel notes, nice lightly burnt notes, malt characteristic is very present.  Palate is nicely carbonated, somewhat sweet on the lips,  and tongue coating.  Overall, This is darn good Vienna,  Nice stuff.

Bottle from the Beerman6686. Nice amber color with a thin lasting head. Aroma is nice sweet toasted bread with a touch of fruity darker caramel malts. Flavor is sweet and toasted, a bit fruity with a super clean crisp finish. Not overly hoppy, just enough bitterness to clean the palate. Just plain well made and easy to drink.
Perfect color for style, nice head, good flavor.  Much too hppy for a true Vienna Lager.  The hops overpower the malt.  Still a very good beer, just not great for the style.
Bottle.  amber color with small white head.  easy to drink. not dull but also not too much flavor.  nice tasting but not too special
Nice amber pour with thin white head, great malt flavor with perfect hop balance. Easy to drink.

bottle.  Aroma is nice and malty with some hops present near the finish.  Notes of bread, malt, caramel.  Sparkling red amber with an average sized off-white head that diminished but remained and left good lace.  Flavor is bread, caramel, malt, and a little bitter on the finish.  Palate is light bodied and lively carbonation.  Quite nice actually.  A good one.
On tap, pours amber with a thin off white head.  Both the aroma and the flavor of the beer is of malt and caramel.  Easily drinkable and another solid brew from Great Lakes.

12oz bottle-A light to medium amber body with a small ring for a head and an aroma of roasted malt and a little caramel. Taste of this medium bodied brew is of malt and sweetness. A nice tasting brew.

Thanks to Mike for this one.  Dark amber color with a creamy beige head that doesnt last long but leaves a thick ring at the edge of the glass.  Aroma is light.  Caramel malt mostly.  Flavor has a velvety texture mingling with the heavy malt flavors, lightly balanced with hops.
Nice copper color with a nice head.  Malty sweet smell emanates from the beer.Great sweet malty taste with slight alcohol and hops flavors.  Great carbonation to add to the mouth feel.
A nice full body and color.  Not a bad brew, interesting flavor and maltiness.  Doesnt produce an aftertaste, which makes it very drinkable and goes well with food.

Odd but faint aroma. Had me thinking whisky but its mostly some hops and a bit of roastiness. As it warms theres some caramel too. Perhaps its vanilla that makes me think of whisky; barrels that is.

Hardly any roastiness in the flavour but more of a full, even minty from the hops, caramel. Not what I expected. Different, intersing and pretty good.
Poured amber with an off white head. Aroma of malt and some fruit. Lots of sweet malt with some fruit hints in the finish. Easy drinking.

Rich, amber body with an off-white head. Fairly good lacing, too. Malt and hop both present in the aroma, but the malt plays a larger role. The flavor is quite malty at first, but the hops appear in the middle to balance things out. Average carbonation, and it has an overall smooth mouthfeel. This is a good Vienna, but not the best Ive had.

Pours a deep red amber color with a spongy, cream colored head.  Thin sheets of delicate lacing traipse about the glass.  The aroma is heavy on caramel malt, but balanced well by notes of freshly harvest wheat, dry cereal grains, and mildly spicy floral hops.  The flavor is as even keeled as the nose hints, proudly displaying the aforementioned components in a harmonious, pleasing way.  The balance is fantastic, enhanced no doubt by a smoothing creaminess that pulls everything together.  Medium bodied, smooth, and well carbonated, this one is a crowd pleaser.  This brew would make a great break-in beer for someone new to the craft beer world.  Excellent example of the Vienna style.

I get this stuff for $8 per six pack up the street ... they usually have the bottles that are past their expire date but it still is good relatively speaking ...Get fresh stuff if  you can .
Great all around beer my friends ... and oh , what a session beer ...
I want to go to Vienna and taste the real deal someday ... but I bet this is just as good, something tells me ...

bottle - Pours clear amber with a one finger white head.  It has a light aroma of caramel malt and citrus hops.  The flavor has the expected caramel malt and a well balanced hops flavor.  Light to medium body and very drinkable, its a fine session brew without being outstanding.

Bottle from miketd.  Golden amber and tawny brown colored body, near perfect clarity.  Wonderfully rich nose of dry nutty wood, crisp caramel malt and fruity, dried leaves.  Vinuous, held togethor well but not thick; fresh and delicious light sweetness that turns moderately dry, bready and nutty (chestnuts) in the finish.  Really good stuff.

Had this one on draught at Bennigans in St. Charles, Illinois.  Nice, dark amber pour with a medium, fluffy white head.  Medium mouthfeel.  Nose of light, citrusy hops and bready malts.  Some milk chocolate balanced with piney hops flavor.  Balanced, clean finish.  Very nice.

12 oz. bottle.  A beautiful ruby red with a healthy white head.  Malty aroma with some biscuit character.  Flavor has some caramel and toasted malt.  Has a crisp lager finish that is slightly sweet.  Well made for the style, not too exciting, but well balanced, clean and easy to enjoy.

This bottle was from a variety pack. A pretty decent variety pack with 3 bottles each of this, Burning River Pale Ale and the Edmond Fitzgerald Porter. I havent tried the other yet. It poured a dark copper/amber color with a 1" thick creamy head. Nice lacing throughout the glass. The aroma was mild of malt and sweetness of caramel. The flavor hit with a nice crisp taste with a nice bite and a nice combination of a caramel sweetness to give a mellow taste. A very nice drinking beer!!!

UPDATED: FEB 18, 2008 Looks beautiful in a glass, a nice deep red. Its hard not to want to put the glass on the windowsill as a permanent fixture to your home; but doing so would be denying yourself the pleasure of tasting this brilliant brew. The aroma is intoxicating; and the flavor is rich and full of malty goodness. Goes down easy.

This beer poured from the bottle a really nice deep red Honey color.  The  initial aroma was only faint and more of hops.  There was a hint of redcabbage and saurkraut when poured.  The head was modest but nice lace.  The taste was veryy well balanced with just a good level of sweetness followed by mild bitter hops.  tirstquenching for sure

Bottle. Pours orange/copper with a big off white head. Sweet malt aroma with caramel and spice notes, as well as a hint of floral hops. Medium body. Flavor is caramel malt with a bit of spice. Hops are noticeable. Pretty good.

The color was medium copper.  The head was thick, frothy, off-white, and laced the glass.  The aroma was some spice, sweet, caramel malt, and pumpkin.  The flavor was coppery, somewhat hoppy, sweet, and caramel malt.  The palate was thin and barely carbonated.  The finish was clean

Thanks polomagnifico. Pours a very nice pretty auburn with a billowing creamy tan head. Smells like autumn, leaves, sweet malt, caramel, pumpkin, sweet spice. The flavor is nice and malty, sweet malts, light grassy hops, pumpkin meat, easy to drink. The palate is a little strange, absolutely zero carbonation in my sample despite the profuse head.

Bottle but I see from other raters can get this on tap, would like to have it on tape also and re-rate.  Amber pour Lager, small head nice lacing but disappears quick.  Malt and hops mix with a crisp kind of bitter sweet finish.  Another from a sampler pack, would like to try this again.
Pours dark amber with a thick frothy tan head. Aroma of malt and molasses. Malt and yeast flavor that turns into a dry hop finish. Light to medium body. Overall a good lager.

It looked pretty...that much Ill say for it.  A deep amber/red pour with a thick head.  The aroma was very wheaty and malty.  To this point, it seemed as if it would be a terrific drink.  Sadly, while the finish was crisp and clean, it tasted very much like rubbing alcohol with a bit of malt and hops mixed in.  Judging by the other reviews on this board, I am certainly in the minority, but Ive tried this drink on several occasions from both tap and bottle and my opinion hasnt been changed.  Not a drink a recommend and, in my opinion, far inferior to a number of offerings from the same brewery.

If a pour can be described as pretty, this is that pour:  garnet red with a very thick white head that diminishes pretty quick and leaves very nice lacing.  Light wheat and caramel malt aroma.  Flavor is more intense than the aroma with a bready flavor up front that quickly translates into a hoppy mixture with pretty strong bitterness.  The finish has a great residual sweetness from the caramel malt flavors, one of the better finishes Ive had in some time!  Light, yet smooth on the palate with some slight oiliness.  Ive had a few other offerings by GL in the past, but this is the first one Ive rated, and I dont think I can remember one better than the Ness!

Draft at Fatheads in Pittsburgh. Pours a very nice copper amber with a thin off white wisp of a head. Faint bready aroma. Lots of wet grain and bread up front, but that is countered by a nice Noble hop bitterness. There is just the right amount of residual sweetness to compliment the hops. Finish is smooth and clean, with some subtle toastiness. This a very solid and enjoyable Vienna, right up there with Triumph and Boulevard, which are some of my favorite Viennas.

A good amber ale to have any time.  Pours a nice red brown color.  The head is slight and is an off white color.  The flavor is very smooth and consists of a malt and sugar with a somewhat bread like finish.

Bottle dated 2/16/08. Clear amber color with puffy off-white head. Malty, caramel aroma. The flavor is along those lines as well but has a nice hop balance. Finish is fairly dry. The body is medium with average amount of carbonation. It doesnt come across as too light or too rich.

UPDATED: AUG 29, 2008 Pours nice clear amber color, with beigeish head. Aroma is excellent, very malty, mostly caramel with some roastiness at the finish.  Flavor is also very good, sweet malts start off, with a bready finish, very well balanced. A great beer in a style that is usually disappointing.

Deep amber color on top of a thin yet fizzy off white head. Sweet malts, caramel, and yeasty dough domintate. Some hints of fresh citrus and piney hops, especially on the finish. Light to medium in body with a well balanced sweetness to it. Finishes slightly dry and hoppy.
Pours auburn and transparent with fizzy off white head.  Big malty aroma.  Caramel malts up front hops, roast and fresh bread on the backside.  I wish I had access to great lakes beer on the regular

Pours amber with a two fingers of tan-white head.  Maltiness dominates the odor.  Starts off light, but builds with a really nice, soft caramel maltiness with an aftertaste of hops and burnt toast.  An interesting, flavorful beer.

Bottle.  Pours amber with one finger white head that reduces to lacing.  Aroma is slighly hoppy, but predominantly toasty maltiness.  One of the most flavorful Viennas Ive ever had.  Toasty, with some caramel malt, and some hops at the end.  More hoppy than I expected.  Pretty delicious.
Bottle. Clear amber-orange with a nice white head. Aroma of hops and citrus. Pleasant taste of hops and malt. Not a very strong flavor but still tasty.

Bottle.  Please enjoy by:  01/13/08.  Pours a clear, deep amber body with a one finger-thick tan head.  Rich caramel maltiness in the aroma.  Solidly medium-bodied.  Lots of rich caramel and sweetly roasted maltiness start things off.  Finishes with some drying, Corn Flakes-ish graininess.  Another excellent job by Great Lakes at a style nobody cares about.

Dec. 2005 - Beer poured amber color (really red) with nice little head and lacing. Aroma was sweet malt as was the flavor. Flavor really improved as it warmed. Sweetness and bitter hop finish were nicely balanced. Nice.

A very talked-about brew that we dont get to see much here in the Northeast.  Looked forward to trying it.

Good lager.  Not great, but good.  Pours a ruby brown color with a decent head.  The aroma was a touch disappointing - faint (very) hoppy notes and a mild citrus note as it warmed.  Flavor was smooth...  mild hop bitterness on rear palate after gentle sweetness on the front.  Not as balanced as a Sam Boston Lager, but still a good beer.  This bottle may have been slightly over-aged.  Not sure about that, but its a possibility.

Appearance: Pours a clear, reddish-hued body with a foamy off-white head.

Smell: A well-balanced blend of sweet-smelling caramel maltiness and a spicy, white pepper hop scent. Faint hint of grains.

Taste: Smooth, sweet maltiness with a toasted caramel taste. Light graininess. A tangy jolt midway. Spicy, herbal hop flavors. Mild bitterness that lingers into the aftertaste. Finishes crisp. 

Mouthfeel: Medium-bodied. Medium carbonation. 

Drinkability: A very lovely Vienna. I would have had another right this very minute if I had one chilled and ready. I would have been GLAD to!

UPDATED: DEC 27, 2007 I like Viennas, and perhaps this is the best example of the style. But likely, that is because it has more hops (and thus is less accurate to the style) than the others. It pours a copper color with a head that tries to linger longer than it can. Full flavored with a great balance of malt and hops (noble rather than west coast). Not too sweet. A serious beer. Excellent.
Reddish amber in color with a nice persistent off white head.  Good smell that has a balance of hop and malt.  Nice hop bite in the taste that fades into a light malty sweetness.

12 oz. bottle from my Winter 2007 Secret Santa.  Pour is a clear amber, with a dirty white head.  Aroma of caramel malt.  Taste is mostly the sweet caramel malt, with some nice burnt roastiness in the middle, and a slight hop bite to the finish.  Nicely made, and thoroughly enjoyable.
Draft. Amber pour, orangish head. Aroma is caramel. Flavor was sweet but smooth caramel, a little bit of hops touched through. This beer got even better as it warmed up a touch. Nice balance.
Nice amber color with a minimal white head.  The crystal malt and sugar experience is my favorite thing about this guy.  Some bitter hops in the flavor but only slightly.
Dark amber lager with a roasted malt & slight hoppy aroma.  Has a sweet malt flavor with balanced with hops.  Great example of an underrepresented lager style.

light brownish red hue, aroma is malty with hints of hops.  Flavor was clean sweet lager flavor with hops in the swallow.  Im not a big fan of this style, and i kno great lakes is a good company, but i was extremely surprised and impressed by this beer
12 oz bottle. Ruby amber with a thin off-white head. Big malty aroma. Nicely balanced flavor with the malt shining through. Clean lager finish. Extremely drinkable.
Bottle, pretty good overall beer. Nothing too special. Crisp clean smooth tasting lager.
A great lager, available at many of the local bars-- but best at the brewery. Very nice balance of hops and malt. Easy to drink.
One of the best lagers out there.  Great lakes is doing great.  Their porter and pale are are far and away  tops.
Beautiful ruby color with small tan head and little lacing. Aroma and flavor have rich caramelly malt and nice balance of hops. Easy to drink and great all around.

Holy crap what a superb vienna. This blows away any other that Ive had. Aroma was good...caramel malt and some hops. Pour was a dark amber with a one finger off white head. Taste was very strong...caramel malt all the way with just a bit of hops in the background. Medium mouthfeel and decent carbonation. Very strong and tasty for a vienna.
user_location: Moon Twp, suburb of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, USA

text: poured a thin looking amber color with a thin white head.  Aroma was a mix of caramel and some floral hops.  Flavor was a tad nutty with a mild sweet finish.  kinda watery.
Not bad, but not great.  I found it to be a bit nutty.  It isnt a very strong taste or very hoppy.  Great Lakes is a good brewery but I find this a bit boring.
Amber pour with little head. Sweet caramel malts up front with a hoppy finish. Very well balanced and enjoyable.

This lager poured a dark orange colour with a nice off white head. To the nose it had scents of apple sauce, sweet malt, caramel and dough just to name a few. Tasted very hoppy with a bitter finish. Almost a light flavour of cider and caramel. Palate was hoppy with the bitterness lasting.
On tap @ Coles Buffalo NY. Medium amber color with sweet caramel malt nose. Medium body, malty sweet flavor, mild bitterness. Pretty tasty
Pours an amber color with very little head.  Aroma is malty with a hint of caramel.  Up front it tastes malty, then gets a little bitter, and finishes off slightly nutty.
This was a very good version of a vienna lager.  I would drink this more often if I could find it.
Bottle. Pours a rich amber with little head. Mild caramel aroma. Thin on the palate with caramel malt and spice finish. Not bad, but not my favorite amber lager.

Bottle poured a clear reddish amber with a large lasting light amber head. Aromas of carmel, bread, light earthiness and a hint of fruitiness. Palate waslight bodied and smooth. Flavors of carmel, bread, some graininess and a light hint of spice with a smooth malty finish.

Granted, the bottle that I am rating is slightly out of date (best before June 07), but I dont think drinking it 4-5 months past its "prime" will make much of a difference. Or does it? This beer just wasnt very good, which is strange because I absolutely love Great Lakes. An aroma of iced tea, lightly sweet with a bit of a twang to it. Appearance is stunning. A beautiful reddish/orange hue, mostly clear with a nice 1 inch head on pour which disipated to a thin scummy foam. The thing about the flavor was the tartness/sour factor which wasnt pleasing at all, especially in a lager. I would almost dismiss it as hop bitterness, but it reminds me of some kind of bug spray. I will definitely have to hunt down a fresher bottle and will re-rate if/when I do. But until that time, this beer was a letdown.
UPDATED: FEB 14, 2008 10/10/07 bottle.  All I can say about this is: BURNING MALT.  That is all I can taste and all that I have to say... well and I kinda like that about this brew.

UPDATED: MAY 8, 2008 <bottle from Archer Liquors>   Have to say Im surprised at the scores for this one.  I wasnt impressed at all.  
Pours a maroon transluscent color with a medium head.  Smell is a bit sour, slightly skunky, and metallic tart maltiness.   Not terrible, but not inviting...Taste is not crisp at all, but rather sour smooth caramel.  While drinkable, I wouldnt recommend it.  If this as as good as the style gets, maybe I just dont like Viennas as much as I though I did..

12 oz bottle-pours a big light tan head and reddish copper color.  Aroma is musty malt-some caramel and bread, some fruit.  Taste is musty malt-some caramel and bread, some fruit, some/faint light/spicy hops.  OK effervescence.  Thanks E Notch for bringing this one back.

Bottle; poured an amber color  with an off white head.  Aroma of caramel and fruit juice.  Nice palate; flavor of caramel, bread, fruit juice and caramel; sweet.  Well done for the style, but to me this is rated to high.
From a bottle at The Rusty Bucket.  It had a very bold and full taste for a Lager.  I would agree that it has its own taste.

UPDATED: JUN 16, 2008 a reasonable enough vienna, nice and malty lager with plenty of character. I think what I like about this beer is that it is quite original while maintaining its old school roots. nice.

9/12/2007:  Great Lakes Eliot Ness is amber in color with a foamy beige head.  The aroma and flavor are earthy and contain a nice caramel/toffee maltiness and just enough earthy bittereness to create a very well-balanced beer.  This medium-bodied beer is smooth and very drinkable.  This is a solid Vienna lager that will hopefully get more and more people interested in the the style.
12 fl. oz. bottle at the Newtown Village Tavern.  Thanks for buying the rounds Tom (Tmoney99).  I really appreciate it!  Rating #451 for this beer...

A tasty looking clear amber with a big foamy white head, vanishing.  Sweet caramel doppelbock smell with a hint of floral to peppery hops.  A bit of toast and oddly, cinnamon?  Full on the palate.  Substantial with low carbonation.  Still not too thick of the style.  full rich sweet malt.  Caramel, a bit of toast.  Floral to peppery hops with a hint of alcohol popping in.  this sems more doppelbock than vienna, but very nice.  A bit chewy.  Some diacetyl.  Tannic toast, alcoholic bit in the finish.

The aroma is malty, sweet caramel. The appearance is a clear amber, the head is off white, mostly diminishing, good lacing. The initial flavor is a slight sweet and a little bitter. The finish is slightly watered own from the initial taste. Teh body is light, the texture mostly watery with a slight creaminess. The carbonation is soft.
350 ml bottle mail order form Archerliquor.  Clear reddish amber with a fizzy white head.  Wheat bread aroma.  Sweet caramel and bready taste with a nice crisp finish.  Not bad.

12oz bottle.  Best by 10/22/07.  Pours a deep amber color with a small, quickly fading white head.  Aroma is pretty standard lager, though pleasant.  Honey, slightly toasted malts, a tad sweet, grainy.  Crisp, sweet, carmel taste.  Smooth and light bodied. Very clean yet still flavorful.  Im not a big lager guy but Great Lakes certainly makes some of the best in the country.

Thanks for the bottle from The_Epeeist.    Darker amber color.  1/2 finger head with a strong pour.  Hoppy aroma on pour fades to a medium intensity melanoidal caramelized malt aroma.  Nice aroma.  Medium sweet to dry.  No off flavors.  Nice amber!
UPDATED: AUG 20, 2007 quite sweet caramel notes, crisp and refreshing like the other great lakes...

In the bottle at the 2007 Baburek backyard vintage beer tasting. Deep reddish amber in color with an off white head. This has a great toasted aroma. Flavors is mildly coffee roasted with a marshmellow sweetness blended in.  Caramel perhaps. Tasty.
A beautiful amber colored Vienna.  The malt flavor is incredibly rich and creamy.  Caramel sweet flavors with a perfect bitter finish.

This is my favorite lager produced in this region. If I were to describe this beer in two words they would have to be "fruity malt" then Id add in words like carmel and hops, shortly after Id add the question "Hey, can I get another?".
Amber in colour with thick orangy head that dissipated quickly.  Sweet malty smell with a mix of fruits and some alcohol.  Tastes a little caramel and sweet but has quite a hoppy bitter aftertaste.

An excellent beer withall the qualities a beer should have. Words cannot describe beer made like this one.
If you want an accurate review of this beer, buy some. You wont be sorry.

(Bottle) Pours an amber brown color with off-white head. Full malty character, with lots of caramel and some light toffee notes. Above average mouthfeel, with a relatively low level of carbonation. A nice session beer.
@ GLBC Beer School, my first vienna, lots of carmel in this brew, almost over powering, but nice and easy drinking very smooth

Bottle pours a nice brownish color with a frothy head.  The glass laves nicely as a drink.  There is a very sweet malty flavor to this one with a touch of toastyness and caramel.  The finish is sweet and smooth,  A tasty beer!
