[381-20070630] Tap @ Great Lakes (Cleveland, OH). Faintly hoppy grains aroma. Clear, amber red body with a medium-lasting foamy white head. Grainy flavour. Medium body is smooth. Relatively bland compared to its brothers on the table but is repeatable and hides the alcohol well.

The color is amber with a red tint and It has a white head with a red tint.  Smells of malt and a bit of hop.  The flavor is similar to the aroma.  The second Great Lake brew Ive tried and both are very good.

Bottle.  Pours a dark amber color with a decent beige head.  The aroma is caramel and toffee with some citrus and floral hops.  The flavor is similar with the malts being ever so slightly more present than the hops.  Overall this is pretty well balanced.  Medium bodied with good carbonation.  I believe this was my first Vienna.
UPDATED: AUG 20, 2007 Smells really nice. Dont uaually like this style but this was really enjoyable. Another well balanced beer from Great Lakes.

12oz bottle, kmweaver-exclusive non-RBSG pity-party tasting 2007, courtesy of Monger.  Thanks, James!!  Pours a clear, medium amber color; whitish head with good retention and fine-bubbled lacing.  Light, candy sugar and tea-like malts in the aroma.  Medium mouthfeel: plenty of lightly toasted malts and candy sugar; slightly dry in the mouth (almost tea-like), with a pleasant, dense red ale character; hints of citrus and earthy notes.  Lengthy, dry malty finish; lightly toasted (like me).
A spritz reddish yellow with tan head.  Aroma of toasted malt.  A robust caramel flavor and mellow hop balance.  This is a fantastically smooth Vienna.
12 0z. bottle.  Deep red color.  Small, quickly disapating cream head.  Malty aroma.  Very malty start fading to a mild hoppy finish.  slight after taste of malt.  Overall, pretty good lager.

12 ounce bottle poured into a tankard mug.  Amber red with a lasting beige head.  Theres even some nice lace left behind.  The aroma is toasted and nutty, with lots of noble hop character.  The flavor is the same toasted malts with a sturdy hop flavor and bitterness.  Very easy to drink.  This beer kicks all kinds of ass.
A nice, caramelly, malty beer.  A slight hop character with a smooth finish.  A good beer, but nothing outstanding.  Was a good vienna.  Good session beer.

Never seen this until I picked it up on an overnight Ohio stop driving x-country. Great deep lager character with enough hops to hold it up, super drinkable finish. Most excellent for the style - and refreshing enough to drop a few easily after driving 12 hours.
a strong hop character for the style but is balanced and overall I would consider a high quality good vienna
Pours a clear amber red with a medium beige head.  Aroma of sweet malts, caramel and sourness.  Taste is light malty with caramel and toffee hints.  Not bad.

From the bottle, courtesy of MrBendo, pours a deep coppery red with a thick but disipating off white head, nice lacing.  Smells of malts as well as cinnamon.  Surprising and interesting aroma.  Taste is earthy, with some malts and clove-like spice.  Thin, but not watery.  As it warms, the flavor does tail off a bit.

Rated 2/18/06:  Yet another wonderful beer from Great Lakes. This lager pours a rich amber color and is topped with a thick creamy tan head. Mild carbonation and minimal lacing, this beer simply looks smooth. The aroma primarily consists of sweet malts, I am not able to catch the faint hop nose that is promised on the bottle. The flavor is outstanding for this style. The sweet malts are dominant, the hops although minimal do make themselves present in the taste. Maybe Mr. Ness just needed to warm up a bit. Thick creamy mouthfeel with a smooth finish. Excellent
Had on tap at local bar...Poured a nice light copper color. Very malty. Which I loved. Taste is almost pure sweet malt, maybe a hint of toffee or caramel. Very drinkable!

UPDATED: AUG 5, 2010 Draft, Clevleand airport. Copper-red with small head that hangs and leaves nice frosty lace. Aroma is malty and sourish. I think this beer and some others sampled at this location have seen some hours at elevated keg temperatures; I suspect in transport from the brewery. Flavor is caramel, toasted nut and grain, with nice slight orange and wood-hop balance. Palate is light-medium and fizzy, with some hop tingle at the end. Hop more noticeable in the aftertaste, pretty nice.

Pours a nice reddish amber color with a off white one finger head with fair retention and lacing. Aroma is all sweet malts. Taste is slightly offputting to me -- this might be an old bottle. Smooth malts with hints of sweetness with a slightly sour off flavor. Mouthfeel is smooth and refreshing. Very drinkable.

Nice pour.  Creamy head and orange amber clear color.  Full flavor with a great balance.  Another great effort from great lakes.  Toffee caramel with lingering bitterness that is just right.  Great from the first sip to the last.  Yes, Ill have another.

Nicely done! Reddish amber color, one finger khaki head, foaming and lasting. Somewhaqt mild aroma, but hints at a toffee like sweetness, a deep earthiness, and some green noble hop. Flavor exquisitely balanced, with a full rounded bready sweetness and a lightly spicy and floral hop character that leads to a medium bitter finish. Clean and well brewed.

Not their best work, but a pretty solid beer. Good balance of malts and decent hopping for an old-school Vienna. Dark chocolate notes and a hint of woody dried fruit. Bit flat in the body and not much in the way of aromatics. Very fresh-tasting.
An interestingly full bodies amber lager with a quality bite. Overall a great taste for the price. If you can find this beer... enjoy
Nice, and inexpensive at the local grocery store.  Will definitely go back to this bottle.  Good taste and Great Lakes put out another nice beer.

UPDATED: AUG 27, 2007 Sampled from a 12 oz brown bottle this beer poured a beautiful ruby-chestnut color with a large dark tan head. The aroma was sour, tangy and very malty. The flavor was tangy, bitter, nutty, very malty and had a moderate floral hop presence. The finish was long and malty. The body was surprisingly thick. Nice.
Pours amber with malt aroma and some hops.  Some sweetness to it.  Hints of hoppyness. Overall decent.

Maybe I got a funky bottle, but this is the only GL beer Ive had so far that I wouldnt get again. Smell is way too malty and look is very carbanted. The taste is very malty and a little plaiting, nothing that I really like.
Bottle sampled with stegosaurus. Pours a amber color with a white head. Aroma of caramel malts Taste is crips and malty with a touch of hop bitterness. a good brew.
UPDATED: APR 4, 2007 My favorite great lakes so far. Enjoyed this beer incredibly. Makes me feel like a man. Which is sad, cause I am a man.

I admit that this is not my favorite style, but I would expect more from Great Lakes. I like the idea of them having a lager, and the front end of it is tasty and refreshing, but the sweet finish is really uneccesary. Its pretty much a brown ale, and not very good. I wish they would have erred more on the side of pilsner. Too sweet.
pretty flavorful beer, some caramel flavor to it, slight aftertaste. worth the try but probably not a repeat.

UPDATED: JUL 3, 2007 June 2007. Draft at the brewpub. Dark amber body, small white head. Toasty malt aroma, and something I cant place - like toffee/caramel, but not quite that. Similarly toasty malt in the flavour, light balancing bitterness. Alcohol is deceptively absent. Average palate. Decent. I had hoped for a significant improvement over my bottled sample, but while the draft was better, it was not a dramatic improvement. 6+/3/7/3/14 3.4

March 2007. Bottle. Rich amber brown body, small creamy beige head (3+). Fruity, malty aroma that smells a lot like the sweet caramel and malt of fresh malt extract (not saying they used extract, just that it has similar aromas). Malty flavour, caramel, light bitterness in the finish. Tangy aftertaste. Average to medium palate is a touch undercarbonated. Pleasant but does not knock my socks off. Less hoppy than I expected - It is nearing the expiry date so perhaps it is not 100%. Reminds me of HOTD for some reason. 6/3/6/3/12 - 3

On tap at Capones during the Great Lakes tasting. Pours a lightly hazy golden with just hints of some amber and a medium foamy white lacing head.  Aroma of citurs hops, kind of grassy, lemony, foral with more fresh hoppiness than I expected from the style.  Flavor had a very intersting spiciness going on at first, bready, kind of earthy, yeast and tea.

Bottle sampled from Capones. Pours deep copper with an off-white head. Aroma of toasted caramel malts, nuts, and slight traces of hops in the nose. The flavor is is toast, caramel, nuts, and a mild bitter finish. Good brew.
Pours a rich amber color with a hoppy nose and thin reddish head. Nice taste that goes down easy and has a lasting finish. Hops are a bit weak in the taste but overall this is a decent beer.

After reading many great reviews  I bought a six pack of E.N. along with another another great lakes label. Neither one lived up to the hype i had read but this one seemed somewhat drinkable but not worth the money in my opinion.

Dark honey color, thick creamy white head. Toasty caramel aroma and flavor. Mild bitterness. Not really a whole lot to say about this. Its certainly a well made lager, enjoyable and good to have around, yet nothing spectacular.

From a 12oz. bottle 

Eliot Ness poured a very nice, very clear amber. Some red highlights when held to the light. The head was white and creamy with a few larger bubbles mixed in. Only about quarter inch head which disappeared rather quickly to just a light sprinkling on top throughout the drink. Minimal lacing. This beer looked real good except for the head dissapating so quickly.

The smell is just average. Smells of grain and maybe a little husk? Its strange but for some reason theres something in there that brings to mind a wet dog. I also pick up a tiny touch of sweet malt and when it warms a little alcohol.

The taste is very good. A slight sourness on the tongue at first followed by quickly maltiness and a touch of bitterness to finish things off. As it warms it brings out a tiny bit of alcohol.

Medium bodied. Not a whole lot of carbonation. Tastes right.

glbc.  Pours a nice deep gold with a fluffy lasting head and great lacing.  Aroma of nutty toasty and bready malts with a nice light metallic and moslty herbal hop character.  Toasty malt flavors with light munichs or vienna malts, nutty, and biscuity with a slight sweetness and a great crisp bitterness.  Nice and easy to drink.
A well made Vienna pretty much says it, I have liked everything I have had from this brewery. Page196 of Michael Jacksons Great Beer Guide only 376 out of his 500 Classic Brews to go.

Poured a bronze gold but ended up a amber in the glass, a few bubbles with some lacing, fragrances of sweet and malt, syrup scents, very little hop aroma, taste of malt, little hop bite, sweet in the mouth,
touch of caramel on the tongue.

Service in a pilsner style glass.

Nice amber colour with a nice tan head that left little lace.   Smell was fairly empty with a minimal aroma that was slightly sweet and nutty.  
Taste exceeded the smell.  Very Nutty malted taste which was pleasant and not overpowering and meshed well with the other undertones of toffee.  
Nice mouthfeel that had a nice balance of carbonation.
overall an enjoyable and drinkable beer that i would be delighted to have again.

UPDATED: SEP 29, 2007 Amber with big, creamy tan head / Light sweet malt nose / Medium, creamy body with lively spritz and fine, sweet finish / Flavors of malt and caramel with cotton-candy, burnt sugar finish, and balanced by surprisingly assertive hops / A superb example of this style.

bottle: beautiful clear reddish amber colour with big fluffy head. aroma has sents of sweet malts. flavour of caramel malts and some real nice toastyness that blends well with the mellow bitterness of the hop finish. very nice beer.
Clear amber brown with tan head.  Aroma has a hint on cinnamon spice and even malt?  Taste has that same spice flavoring with hint of hops for a dry finish.  For style this is a great beer.
Sweet malt aroma.Pours a deep copper with a reddish tint.Lots of caramel malts in the flavor.Medium mouthfeel with a sweet malt finish.
Excellent Vienna style amber that is full of flavor without being overpowering. Great beer to drink with Chicago style pizza
(Bottle)  Pours a clear amber body with a small creamy beige head.  Aroma of toasted malt and caramel.  Flavor of caramel, nuts, and mild hops.

Attractive copper pour that produces a huge, tight, long lasting creamy head.
Clean malt aroma.
Light sweetness with a touch of hop bitterness that leads to a dryness in the finish. I could drink a few of these.

12 oz bottle via trade with Monger, Thanks for the hookup.  This is my first Vienna rating, and its been a while since I can remember looking forward to a lager.  Pours light amber with a puffy white head that lost half its steam and settled a finger height above the brew.  The smell is malty and fresh.  Taste is crips and malty, but clearly a different animal when compared to ales.  It has a nice full mouth feeling and is quite drinkable.

On tap at the brewery. Clear pale amber pour with a thin light brown head. Good aroma and flavor of biscuity malt and caramel, the malt is round and flavorfull. The body is medium with an oily texture and soft carbonation. A very solid vienna.

Thanks to RagallachMC for the bottle. Clear orange/copper with almost no head. Aroma is generally light, with caramel and nutty malts. Some bitter taste comes in too. Especially at the finish. Medium body. Soft carbonation. Certainly better than average for the style.

Pours red amber in color with a light tan head that disappears by mid-beer.  Very little carbonation in the glass.  Small caramel malt aroma.  Satisfying caramel taste.  Gentle frothy, slightly warm mouth feel, but a little flat and syrupy.

Great Lakes is one of a select few breweries that seem to never disappoint, and this is another quality offering from them.  I was expecting very little from an amber lager (based on many disappointing amber ales Ive had), but this beer over-delivered on appearance and taste.

It poured a vibrant copper-red color that gleamed in the glass.  Head formation was great, but looked slightly soapy when it went away.

Aroma was a bit faint, but more abundant than a lot of amber ales, and is malty and bready.

Taste is of caramel malt with some sweetness at the finish, and is quite good.

Mouthfeel is extremely substantial for a lager, and feels appropriate.  I found this beer to be very drinkable.

Bottle.   Pours a dark amber color with a fairly large light tan head.   Aroma is sweet fruit, malt, caramel.   Flavor is dried fruit, malt, caramel, some floral hops.   Palate is medium light, medium carbonation, clean finish.   Another great beer.   Crowd pleaser.
UPDATED: JAN 2, 2007 Pours a nice amber with a good sized light tan head. Very nice aroma, caramel and light flowery hops. Nice sweetness.

Dark amber with a fluffy head that falls into leaving a film of bubbles....the nose is just as described, malty but mostly caramel that lead into a taste that gives a creamy caramel flavor. Nice Vienna in this taste of Great Lakes Day.

Dark amber pour with light tan head that quickly disappears. Nose is filled with sweet malts, caramel, toast, flowery hops, grain. Very sweet and only a hint of bitterness at the finish. Moderately acidic. Moderately long finish, too. Medium to full body, watery texture and fizzy carbonation. Well put together. Very good.

Wow! Now this is a great brew.  Pours out a deep amber color with a thick beige head.  Aroma is sweet, malty and a bit fruity.  Flavor is very much the same.  I found it very difficult not to gulp this brew.  Outstanding job!
Bottle from bgburdman9. Amber color with small lacing type head. Malty/milky aroma. The taste was malty and nutty with clean roasted finish. Good brew.

Pours a bright amber with a one and a half finger head.  Aroma is of malts and hops with some fruity tones.  Taste is smooth and malty and the hops really shine through as well.  One of my favorite lagers for a long time, definitely worth a try if you havent had one before.
Color is pure copper.  Light malty aroma. Dark fruit flavor. Bitter finish, kind of makes me pucker a bit but good.

clear and red.  limited head. smells earthy, caramel-appleish.  sweet malty aroma, kinda lagerish, which surprised me since i was expecting an amber ale.  somewhat empty flavor.  surprisingly carbonated.  after a few sips i like the sorta lingering syrupy finish. a bit light on the flavor/palate overall, but i can appreciate this.
Clear amber color with a medium white head. Aroma of caramel and malt. Slightly bitter aftertaste, malty, some spice. Nice Beer.
12 oz bottle. Clear amber color with white head. Aroma of caramel and spice. Dry taste of malt and spice with bitter after taste.

UPDATED: FEB 14, 2007 pours a clear copper, amber color with a nice one finger off white head. aroma is a faint hops with a better than average faint lager smell. has a light body with some lacing. the flavor is a little sweet better than average lager taste and there is a flavor that i can not make out, but it is good like a little sugar cane or something. it also has a small dry hoppy aftertaste as well. awsome lager one of the best i have had i would mark it higher if it had a stronger aroma.

Had to fight pretty hard to get a decent head on this one.  Off white and thin with minimal carbonation.  Weak aroma with some bready malts, bit of bitter hops and yes as willblake says, pretzel like.  Color is a bright dark amber.  Light malts and a bit of sweetness.  Hint of bitterness from the hops.  Little dry and astringent at the finish.  Decent brew.

23.11.06  12oz bottle dated best before Oct06, thanks to OhioDad.  I know Ive had this an Im surprised Ive never rated it.  Well, its good as I recalled.  Nice pretzel-like malt profile, medium to full bodied, slightly sweet with notes of honey, plum, and graham, and a quick, herbal, earthy hop finish.  Reminds of Flying Fish Oktoberfish.
UPDATED: NOV 9, 2006 Pours a dark amber.  Aroma of hops, vanilla, and caramel.  Tastes like that as well.  One of my favorites from Great Lakes, along with the Fitzgerald.
orangeish-brown color, aftertaste is good but not strong, some caramel flavor.  Doesnt live up entirely to its high expectations.
Great. Poured a nice red with a lacing foam. Aroma is hoppy and sweet caramel. Flavor is hops at first, but is very balanced by sweet caramel.

(Bottle (best by 10/21/06) via trade with OhioDad, thanks Scott!) Nice, but a little timid for flavor...Pours clear burnt orange with a few fingers of orange-tinted cream-colored head. Nose of vanilla and caramel. Mouthfeel smooth but fairly prickly. Sloppy lacing. Tastes of toasted caramel maltiness with some bitterness in finish. A nice flavor but on the weaker side IMO. Would rank it below Brooklyn Lager or even Z Street Vienna.

From 12oz Bottle.  Lovely,
transparent pour of rich mahogany, topped with a well sustaining head of ivory foam.  Pleasant malty aromas of light vanilla, maple, and almond skins waft from my glass, accompanied by a touch of herbal hops for balance.  Crisply carbonated, light, refreshing mouthfeel.  Mmm... very nice.  Subtly layered malt flavors roll gracefully across the tongue.  Some nice caramelized maply syrup melds nicely with some woody bark before finishing with a final smack of nutty, light chocolate brownies.  Thanks, Tom!

UPDATED: JAN 16, 2007 Pours a darkish clear amber with a decent but quick fading head. Beautiful color. Light malts and hops. Has a nice clean crisp taste. It is not the best beer in the world but whenever I see some I buy it. A great on to have on hand at all times.

UPDATED: NOV 5, 2006 Yeast aroma upon opening the bottle.  Taste is better than the dortmunder and the burning river probably because bitter hops turns my taste buds. Has a good finish without the lingering bitterness of the other two. I must say this is only slightly better than your typical pale yellow american beer.  Will not buy again.
So far, edmund fitz is the best of the variety pack.  I still must taste holy moses, but dont care for that name.
user_location: Beaver Valley, Beaver County, Pennsylvania, USA

text: Bottle from Scott, Thanks!  Pours out a dark brown color without much of a head at all.  Smell is rich and fruity, with some caramel and malt hints.  Taste is smooth and refreshing, mouthfeel is pretty smooth.  Certainly deserving of its top in this style, as Ive not had a better Vienna.  Good beer, very good session beer.

Another cant miss from Great Lakes.  Disappointed that they have decided to distribute the Holy Moses instead of this beer.  Nicely hopped with carmelized malts.  I have enjoyed this for years, and will now have a harder time finding it.

Bottle from The_Epeeist; Thanks Chris; Nose of grain and caramel malt; kind of lagerish; color of oxidized copper with a small, quick to disappear, beige haed; flavor of malt, caramel, and raisins, with a molasses hint, leading to a small hop finish.

Bottle. Dark amber body with a thick film of bubbles. Nose-apple, hay, caramel. Taste-sweet husk, lactic, hay, low-medium bitterness, apple juice, lightly syrupy. Pretty good, but can be easily summed up in four words: apple juice and husk.
12 oz bottle with gputty. Clear amber with a thin tan head. Caramel and light spice in the nose. Malty, spicy flavor, a bit of raisin. Solid.

<!-- i -->Draft, at The Map Room, Chicago.<!-- /I --><!-- br --> Deep walnut colour with a smooth malt/hop blend. Very drinkable.  Great bar with first class hospitality, both in front of and behind the bar!!

UPDATED: JUL 4, 2007 Sampled at Great Lakes.  This one got sort of lost in the bunch at the great lakes samplefest.  Got to see the bullet holes on the tour by the by... anyway, the beer pours a nice dark amber.  Spicy raisin hops and dark fruit on the palate.  Moderately thorough roasted malts and some lighter dry malts thrown in.  A smooth brew that I will need to redrink.
From bottle.  Dark amber pour with tan head.  Nose of caramel malts, spicy hops and raisin underneath.  Flavor follows with some light fruits as well.  Nice.
Bottle: Pours amber in color. Smells of caramel and some dark fruits. Taste was a bit nutty with caramel hints. Lightly carbonated.

An amber beer with a disappearing orange head. The aroma is sweet and very fruity combined with notes of caramel, and a touch of alcohol. The flavor has primary notes of caramel, and a dry mouthfeel that starts quite early, and leads to a bitter hoppy end.

Brownish red.  Large tan head fades at a medium pace and leaves a small lacing.  Malt dominated the aroma, caramel, raisin, oak.  Medium to full body, lightly carbonated.  Big malty flavor with very little hop presence.  Low bitterness.  Clean finish.  I think this is the highest rated vienna, but for my money Brooklyn Lager blows this away.
(Bottle 35,5 cl) Clear amber golden with a small, off-white head. Fat aroma of caramel and aroma hops. Very full, sweetish body with lots of caramel and malt. Dry finish. Very pleasant. 290806

Great looking beer!  It is a cool orange color with a tan head.  There is a ton of malt in the aroma and in the taste.  Very sweet with a nice little bitter bite that stays around.  There is also a lot of dark fruit that adds a nice complexity.  Some caramel hints can be found as well.  Great beer!

Bottle.  A very good lager.  Lagers are not my beer of choice but Ill give anything from GL a shot.  I found this beer to be much more favorable on tap.  Nice amber, copper color with off head average head.  Smell is a bit flat, malty, tea. Flavor is malty, a hint of fruit, tea, nutty a bit.  A touch of hoppiness at the finish.  A smooth lager.

Bottled. Amber coloured. Uncleaer. Light brown head. Sweet and herbal nose with light caramelly notes. Flavour is herbal and caramelly. Light cocoanotes and flowery. Medium body. Herbal bitterness in the end. Thanks to Probiere for this very nice beer.
Bottled. Amber coloured. Nutty and malty aroma with notes of old fruits. Malty flavour with notes of tea and some hops in the finish.
Im actually shocked how high this was rated. I had been waiting a long time to try it. Thought it was thin, overly carbonated and a tad sour. On tap somewhere in Cleveland.

brown-copper clear liquid with not much head save for a light white ring around the edge (hopefully a result of the glass and not the beer) .  smells like a caramel helles, clean yeast notes and minimal hops presence but sweet and darker than a regular dortmunder or helles.  nothing wrong with this beer, which is perhaps the biggest compliment someone can give a normal lager.  refreshing, but ill take their dortmunder gold over this.

12 Oz Bottle. A tall cool drink of crystalline florid rock salt plunks down on the table. Carbonation expands, taking with it viscous foams of ivory. I walk by a fresh caramel corn stand in a Des Moines mall. From across the hall a Flower Stands open and cuts their rose stems. A Hmong women opens a pack of M&M peanuts, hands two to her children, drops one and eats the rest in a fell swoop. Outside, my humours entertain a late April breeze, while savouring lightly roasted Carne Asada from a roadside stand in the Salton Valley, fresh with grilled corn and chicken. The tortilla is salty. My fresh local multi-grain pops from the toaster and I slather it with honey butter. On the long draw, I gather some sweet grass.

Refined. Exacted. A deft and delectable Vienna with scrumptous malt and well-played noticable hops. Palate is near perfection. Fantastic.

Beautiful amber with a white head that nearly disappears.  Carmel/malt nose.  More of the same in the flavor.  Smooth finish.  Very nice and drinkable, but I agree with Adverse2Bitter that it seems a bit over rated.
Pours amber in color (shocking huh?).  Wonderful malt aroma.  Fairly good mouthfeel.  Good malt center with nice bitterness at the end.  Great balance.

Pours a red/amber color, with a frothy off-white head. Aroma is of sweet caramel, earthy notes, and malt. Flavor is of caramel, cane sugar, dark fruit, and mild hops. The finish is nice and crisp. Very well balanced.

My 600th rating... weee!  Anyways big thanks to Degarth for sending this to me in my SecretSanta box.  Great reddish-mahogony colored body along with a nice creamy white head.  Nice wood chip and malty aroma.  Wood chip, hoppy with malt taste, nice light fruit accents.  Sweet with a light spice ending.
Clear caramel color with a small white head. Sweet caramel and floral hop aroma. Light caramel flavor with lots of floral hops.
Not sure what all the fuss is about this beer. Really nothing unusual. Well made for sure, but nothing to go crazy about. Good on a hot day.

UPDATED: SEP 29, 2006 Malty, grain, yeast, green olive and licorice. Not too much carbonation. Acidic with subtle sweet counterbalance and body is not too heavy. Even citrus. Many notes without being muddled. Not my thing but well made.

Bottle. Pours a nice rich dark amber color with a medium off white head. Very nice hop aroma. Taste of toasted malts with a hint of brown sugar. Finishes with a bit of caramel and hoppy bitterness on the after taste. A great beer from Great Lakes!

UPDATED: OCT 2, 2006 bottle.  Aroma:  Toasted malts, and a hint of roasted nuts.  Also getting a touch of fresh grain.  Appearance:  Rich coppery red and clear.  Head was full and off-white, but diminished quickly. Light lacing.  Flavor:  Lots of toasty malt with notes of citrus and grass.  Also getting a little brown sugar.  Bitterness was just right and melded well with the malt flavor.  Palate:  Medium bodied.  Moderate carbonation.  Finish was crisp, but could have been a little crisper.  Overall:  A nice, smooth, easy drinking beer with enough flavor to keep it interesting.

Copper color, when poured properly it has very little head.  Noteable hop and grain aroma.  Both bitter and sweet at the same time, wholly unlike ligher lagers or black lager- much richer.  Tasting notes: Nuts, yeast, grain and a hint of brown spice; taste lingers well after the beer is gone.

12 oz bottle.  Clear amber brown with an airy, dirty tan head that quickly deflates.  Woody and nutty; some molasses and green olives.  Mild carb yields to licorice and orange pith, but subtle.  A new style for me.  Like a porter-lager mix.  Somewhat flat.
Deep copper pour with a thin whit-sh head.   NIce Malty Aromoa.  Nice malty falvor, maybe some fruit.  Definatly has a bitter bite to it. Good Beer, easy to drink.

Thanks to Secret Santa for this one.  Pours deep coppery with 2-finger off-white head.  Aroma of muffiny malts, caramel, toffee, some vinous notes, and some hopcitrus.  The flavor is caramel malty, with some hopcitrus and vinous winey notes, along with some slight nuts and fruit.

The Elliot Ness has a great dark amber color to it. I like the change of pace you go through drinking this lager. It has a great smooth mouthfeel with a nice sweet malt taste. The end is has a sharp bitter edge to it, as does the aftertaste. A nice beer to sit and sip on, and another great product from the Great Lakes Brewery."

Thanks OhioDad.  Gorgeous clear deep amber beer, thin off-white head.  Sweet toast and caramel, Munich malt, very clean, but rich malt character.  Flavour is toasty with a hint of brown sugar.  Noble hop aroma and flavour throughout.  Great balance and flavour.  Creamy body.  LIngering breadiness with herbal noble hops.  Refreshing, complex, clean and very well made.  Their lagers are first-rate.
On draft.  Pours amber with white head.  Nose is sweet and malty.  Sweet, caramel flavor with a chewy mouthfeel.

Bottle from trade with OhioDad. Poured a deep amber color, almost red, with a thin tan head. The aroma was of wheat bread and some caramel hints. The flavor found malts, wheat, and a hint of citrus hops and fruit background. Medium body that was mainly sweet but had a light bitter hit at the end. Nice! Thanks Scott!!

Appearance is dark brown/amber almost pruple-y, with virtually no head.  Aroma is faily indistinct with some carmel and wheat malt.  Flavor is carmel and wheat malt with some molasses and brown sugar and a hint of fruitiness like grapes and lemon.

via trade with OhioDad - Pours a very clear deep amber color (almost red).  Initial head fades to nothing quickly.  Very light carbonation.  Has a nice grain, grass aroma.  Has a light malt sweetness flavor.  A smooth hop bitterness comes through at the end.  Medium body.  A nice, smooth easy drinking beer.  Thanks Scott.

I hesitate to call it a well crafted amber lager but I feel it deserves to be. Pours a wonderful deep red with a dissapointing head. The flavors are rich full of sweet malts. These wonderful flavors need to stand out more and give me a good kick.

Bright amber color with medium tan head that lingers thru half glass and good lacing. Aroma was apples and bananas, with a hint of grapes. Initial flavor was the fruits, some hops and malt. At mid-glass, taste became more malty, and alcohol, though only 6.2 ABV, was more noticeable. A good smooth warming finish.  I had heard there were freshness and dating questions with these Great Lakes Brews, but Ive had no complaints so far with this or Dortmunder.

Thanks again to doulos for this one. Poured a deep orange color with a very small head and just about no lacing. The aroma was bready, sweet malts. Typical for the style, but weak. The flavor followed on this theme and also had a light spicing to it. Mouthfeel was thick and approached almost that of a maibock.
Roasty smell, pours to a beautiful carmel color. Complex taste of roasted grains, with a nice, hoppy finish. Probably the best amber Ive had.
At Gooskis, PGH, PA. Bottle. Pours clear red amber with only a trace of a white head. Aroma is sweet wheat. Flavor is the same with a bit of bitterness.
Bottle. Light orange in color with little or no head. Malty aroma. Light tasting. Thin bodied.  Finish is sweet. Ok beer.

#4 fro COTF 5/06. 12 oz bottle. Small head sits on an amber body. Taste is light and smooth with just the faintest amount of sweet malt. Maybe Im missing something but Im not getting hardly anything else excelpt maybe some biscuit.

Pour is nice ruddy amber with a dense 1/4 inch tan head...smell is sweet and grainy with nice caramel and molasses notes...taste is nice and sweet thourhgout, but not overly so...more of a subtle roasty malt flavor...nice lush mouthfeel...who knew a vienna could be so tasty?

Clear, cherrywood red-brown.  Nice malty aroma.  Sweet and woody, mildly astringent.  Goes a bit milky towards the finish.  Fruit, mild sourness.  Biscuits and trace cocoa.  Surprisingly complex - a bit of an ABV sting here and there.  Smooth and tangy finish, medium body.

On tap at the brewery. Great reddish color. A little hop aroma but mostly malt. Sweet malty flavor with a very slight bitter bite. Great example of a vienna lager. Great summer beer with a nice dry finish.
OK.  Seems like it had a vegetal note to it.  Still some nice caramel aromas and flavors to it.  Not my favorite GL beer, but not bad.
Beer at the Pier. Nice reddish color. Nice malt aroma. The flavor is of hops and caramelized malt. A very good beer.
One of the better vienna, pilsner style beers ive had. Nice clean aroma, texture and palate. Good Beer.

On tap @ Eddie Georges grill, and actually sitting next to Eddie George. Amber pour with an off white head. Aroma has some caramel and hops. Flavor has is mostly caramel up front followed by a nice hoppiness that makes this really drinkable. To this day I really dont know why there isnt a sixer of this in my fridge at all times. I could probably be happy drinking exclusively from Great Lakes, but wheres the fun in that?

Thanks for sharing Derek! Great stuff. Sampled along side Sam Adams Boston Lager. Both good, but this one stands out as the winner. Deep copper pour with a thin beige froth. Lots of caramel in the nose, followed by lots of munich and some hops to balance. Also, slight smoke is there. Very sweet malt flavours, with smoked peatm burnt sugars, and balancing dry hoppiness. Silky smooth! Why cant this be my everyday drinker? Ohh I know, cause I cant get it here. :) THanks Derek!

Pours reddish copper with a small white head.  The aroma is roasted malt with some clean caramel.  It is medium bodied with a slick feel and medium/sharp carbonation.  The tast is rich roasted caramel with a sharp hop bite.  The taste is crisper than the description suggest.  The finish is sour hoppy - the sourness seems right, not like something went wrong causing it.  The finish becomes more of a clear bitterness further down the glass.  Nice beer.

UPDATED: APR 27, 2006 12oz bottle acquired in trade with OhioDad (thanks!). Poured a deeper, and clear, copper color with a smaller sized off white head. Aromas of caramel, a little earthy and somewhat spicy. Tastes of caramel, biscuit, and toasted nuts. Body a tad on the thin side.

This was OK. I didnt dislike it but it is a hoppy beer which is something I dont like. The sourness is what turns be off. I like flavor and the sweetness found here is pleasent, but the over hopping keep it from being a beer I would seek out again. Looks good color wise but though I was born in Cleveland this is only average

UPDATED: JUL 6, 2007 12oz bottle, please enjoy by JUN 07/06.  Pours a clear brownish amber with a small eggshell head.  Aromas of spicy hops, caramel and toffee malts.  Some nuttiness up front  followed by the same sweet caramel and toffee into a mildly bitter finish.  Some biscuity malts toward the end as well.  Mildly carbonated, soft on the palate with a medium body.  Good, but not fantastic.
user_location: Ocean Beach, San Diego, California, USA

text: Nice look, weak aroma.  Body is a dark brownish copper... tarnished penny, with a foamy head.  Aroma is grainy and a little yeasty.  Mouthfeel is a little watery, but flavor is pretty nice.  Flavor is grainy with toffee/caramel notes of sweetness and a bit of hops crispness in the finish.  Very refreshing, but not very hearty.
user_location: The Wet Side of a Dry Town, Pennsylvania, USA

text: From a 12 oz. long neck brown bottle with a blurb about the lager and a best before on the side of label. Made a good appearance, poured a red hued amber with a small foamy pale tan head that settled into a thin, semi-clingy lacing, good, active carbonation. Had a nice toasted grainy nose with whiffs of floral and herbal hops and a quiet sweetness around the edges. A smooth, chewy, full feeling, light bodied mouth feel, very good drinkability. A big, delicious toasted grainy and caramel malty taste, a gentle herbal bitterness showing up towards the middle and a dry, semi-sweet, grainy finish, highly quaffable.
deep amber color, strong aroma, sweet and smokey.  The palate is awesome. Thick in the mouth, a great palate for a lager. Great taste, not too strong aftertaste. I was really impressed with this one

And I thought it would be a real bummer to have Eliot Ness show up to a beer tasting, eleven brews in.  Quite the contrary.  An amber lager with a kind note of malty-sweetness.  Untouchably refreshing.  Drinking this is better than smashing a cart full of barrels. Unless of course, youre Eliot Ness.

Deep red pour, quickly fading head.  Deep strong aroma.  Cloudy to the point of being near opaque.  Fruit and spice in the scent, sweet caramel notes.  Very bitter for a lager.  Licorice taste with caramel.  Very weak aftertaste.  Alcohol content suprised me as I didnt note it in the taste and only noticed after.
This has always been one of my favorites.  This beer pours a reddish dark amber with an aroma of hops.  The body is full and the finish is long.  Too bad I was driving or, Id have had a second.
user_location: Peoples Republic of Athens, Ohio, USA

text: Pour was a dark amber with a reddish tint and a off-white head. Aroma was caramel malt with a touch of hops in the background. The flavor is wonderful. The sweet caramel malts make this a medium  bodied beer.  The initial sweet flavor is followed by just enough bitter bite to let you know the hops are there. Leaves you craving more.
Malty bready aroma, perfectly clear dark amber color. Great mouthfeel for a lager and complex flavor. An above average dark lager with good hops balance, slightly sweet. my kind of beer!

Bottle.  Pours a deep amber with a medium head.  The aroma is sweet, with hints of malt.  The flavor has a nice balance of hops and caramel malts.  Very smooth, clean finish.  Excellent beer.  Wish they could get distributed in Indiana again!

Pours a deep brownish amber with a thick off-white head that fades down to swils of foam. Nose is sweet and malty. Flavor is a bit thick for a lager, but its still a lager. Rich and malty with some hop bitterness in the end. Nice and smooth. A beer junkies lager for sure.
"Poured a dark orange with just a little cloudy, samll head and didnt lace at all. Aroma was malty. Flavor was a little thin, almost watered down with the malts and breadyness in there."

16-Feb-06 (12 oz bottle: Obtained 01-Nov-05 in trade with OhioDad, thanks Scott!) "Enjoy by 30-Nov-05" but its been in my fridge for the 3 months Ive had the beer, so I should be fine.  With the first sip, its caramely and mildly sweet, more flavorful than most other amber lagers, but not just being sweet and caramely.  Better balance, too, provided by a mild bitterness.  While the beer isnt nearly as earthy and mushroomy like the last time I tried this beer, I have to admit, after several sips, mild earthy flavors start to build on the palate.  Medium bodied from the start right through to the finish, so no thinning with this beer.  Medium amber color, good clarity, a fingers width worth of off-white head on the pour settles to a ring after several minutes.  A very solid amber lager, possibly one of the best Ive tried.01-Oct-05 (12 oz bottle: Obtained in trade with bkelley68, thanks Brian!) Uh oh, I kind of lost track of this beer, and now its seen significant time in the bottle, so I guess well see how well this has aged over the past year.  Well, it has a fairly pungent and earthy aroma.  And the flavor is earthy, malty, sweet and mushroomy.  Medium bodied.  Deep amber in color.  The light tan head pours to an average size and settles to a small ring, leaving only a few spots of lace.  So its aged fine by my tastes, but its clearly not the same beer, so I should rerate this at some point.

A beer that is much better drank cold. Started out with rich malts backup by strong german earthy hop pressence, very smooth, lots of caramel and cookie flavors... as it warmed it lost pretty much all hops and was overcome by almond and cookie flavors. Not bad warm at all but not as strong.

(02.06.06) 12 oz brown bottle purchased from DiCarlos, Mundelein, IL.  ABV 6.2%.  Bottle states to enjoy before 3/21/06.  Clear amber ale having a small white head.  No discernable carbonation.  Caramel/sweet malt aromas.  Medium bodied that starts with light malt sweetness and fruity/caramel flavors.  Finishes dry with light hop bitterness. Well-balanced. A very enjoyable amber ale.
pours deep brownish amber with slight head. smells of caramel and starts off with hearty flavors like a stout, but finishes cleanly and crispy like a lager. a delicious mix of flavors
Pours a deep amber red not much of  head Aromas were rich with hops and carmel malt some fruit in there as well .Flavor was balanced with with fruit malt and hops.

Malty, sweet Ruby brew. Actually easier drinking than I was expecting, but more of a plus for this one. I really am not too much of a fan of the style, but this one is great, cant wait to have again!

Bottle.  Nice deep clear amber on the pour.  Very nice head.  Scents of fruit and malt.  Some bitterness on the palate, but also peach and apples and some sweetness.  Very smooth and balanced.  Thanks Beervana.
Always a fan of Great Lakes.  My personal prefernece is toward less sweet.  That acknowledged I feel its a fine session beer.

12 oz bottle:  Medium copper w/ a lasting off white head.  Heavy toasty malt aroma w/ some light caramel and the faintest hint of roast; clean!  Well balanced, clean toasty malt flavor w/ a hint of caramel.  Malt dominated flavor into the finish which is semi dry; aftertaste is a bit of bitterness, but again, clean.  Fuller light body, medium carb., smooth.  A good solid beer from GLBC.  Flavorful enough to keep your attention and want more!
Bottle obtained on campus at OSU. Very taste stuff. Reddish amber color and great aroma. Well balanced between sweet and bitter.

Obtained via trade with Beeryum. Pours somewhat cloudy reddish brown with a medium beige head. Aroma of caramel, apple and slight roastiness. Flavor has notes of toasted malt, caramel, pear, dark fruit and noble hops. Pleasantly sweet, plenty of bitterness in there for great balance. Very full, round and creamy on the palate with lively carbonation. Very good.

this was some good stuff!  nice reddish amber hue...small white head; aroma of caramels, sweet malts, fruits, and mild hops...flavor was a big surprise, and was huge in fruity malts, caramelized sugars, and light fruit...great mouthfeel
Pours a dark amber color with a thin white head.  Aroma is malty and fruity.  Flavor is similar to the aroma with a slightly hoppy finish.  A good, smooth brew

On Tap @ Great Lakes Brewhouse

Poured dark amber, with a white head. Nice lacing on the glass. Aroma sweet, malty, and fruity. Flavor had a mild sweetness and a mild bitterness that mixed well. Caramel notes also present, nice complex brew, flavors really mixed well. Very smooth and easy to drink. Ive never had a vienna before.
pours an amber color with a medium white head. the aroma is light with some fruits, malts, and hops. Tastes similar to the aroma with some bitterness from the hops, but not too much. A good brew.
Very good beer.  Paired this with a medium rare flatiron steak at the brewpub and was an excellent match.
Pours copper/amber, with a tan head. Aromas are sweet malt, caramel, and some fruit. Flavors are caramel, malt, and hops, with a touch of fruit.
This is a smooth beer.  Has a funny sour and caramel character.  Not bad for a lager...and never had a vienna before.
Didnt like this as much as their other lager on tap, but it was pretty good.  It does have a very smooth drinkability, and fantastic colour and aroma.

This bottled brew poured a large sized head of foamy fine to medium sized mostly lasting light brown colored bubbles that left behind an unnoted lacing.  The body contained average carbonation, was unnoted and dark caramel brown in color.  Its aroma contained notes of mild caramel malt .  Its mouth feel is initially tingly smooth with a lingering  palate and a caramel malt aftertaste.  Its flavor contained malty caramel  notes.  The flavor lasts a long time into the finish.  Very yummy.

Pours a clear amber with a thick off-white head, lasting, nice lacing. Aroma is caramel, toffee, and a hint of grassy hops. The flavor is rich and malty, caramel and grapes. The mouthfeel is soft and round, finish is slightly bitter. Nice lager.

Bottle (12oz).  Poured bright clear ruby-mahogany with a smallish diminishing head.  Aroma of gentle fruity yeast, mild hops, sweetish light roast malt.  Taste is much the same, starts a bit sweet and finishes slightly hop-bitter.  Mouthfeel is slightly watery, sory of flat, average body for the style I guess.  Very nice vienna.

The name says it all, Eliot Ness, the man that took out the ulitmate gangster.....This beer takes out the ultimate, nonchallaging beers out there.  If your ready for a change, sit yourself down to a cold Eliot Ness beer.  Perhaps, one of the best Amber Lagers out there....period.

This beer introduces itself with a mild aroma of yeast.  It is a mildly cloudy dark copper color with a good head.  The taste is gentle upon entering the mouth and produces a small bitter hoppy taste that continues to be smooth even after swallowing.

Best before January 13, 2006 bottle received in a wonderful trade with StewardofGondor and drunk on 12/15/05.Pours a dark amber, with light beige and tarnished brass notes.  Head is initially large and beige, receding eventually to a light covering, but providing for a fair amount of lace.  Aroma is packed with intense bready and nutty malts.  Yeasty, doughy, grainy and quite strong.  Light soily hops and touches of caramel and toffee, but lots of breadiness.  The flavor is quite similar, having a good amount of breadiness (brown bread) and plenty of nuts and caramel.  Light notes of vanilla and a moderate yeastiness on end.  The flavor is quite strong and really builds on the your palate.  Low acidity, which is somewhat surprising, as these highly bready notes can often times impart that.  Texture is lightly creamy/watery, with lively, but unobtrusive carbonation.  I almost think I note some alcohol in the finish, after it has warmed significantly, but perhaps not (was sort of a peaty, dry, whiskey note).  Could stand some crisper hops, or more of a lager yeast bite, to clear the palate and the texture can be a bit too aerated/bubbly at times.

UPDATED: DEC 8, 2005 Bottle out of Great Lakes sampler. Dark amber color with a creamy off white head.  Aroma sweet, also some spiceness as well.  Slightly floral scent.  Head is soft and creamy.  Taste is a bit sweet, some toffee and maybe caramel.  Some fruitiness like apples.  Tiny bit of hops.  The mouthfeel of the beer is excellent.  Definitely the best Lager Ive had so far.
Deep amber color with a small beige head. A sweet malt flavor, a dash of honey hiding within, with nutty undertones. The floral hops combine well with the sweet malt. This is one of my favorites.
Poured with a good creamy head, a brilliant red color, and a nice aroma of sweet malt. It warmed up slightly as I drank it, and made for a nice smooth syrupy finish.
Sweet malty aroma.  Has a rich amber color.  Had a honey malt flavor with a crisp finish.

Pours with a  brilliantly clear amber color that shows a rich brownish tinged ruby color when held up to the light.  It is topped by frothy, almost creamy, light tan colored head.  Wow the aroma is quite rich with a malty sweetness that I was not expecting from a Vienna.  The aroma is so sweet it almost takes on a fruity note that is a bit like raisins, or even perhaps a hint of cherry.  There is also a light spicy hop note here that accentuates the fruit character found in the nose.  Underneath the sweetness is a bit of dry toasted malt aromatics that are just noticeable.

The taste is definitely sweet, though thankfully not nearly as much as the aroma might expect.  There are fruity notes of raisins and again a hint of cherry.  The hops have a nice, though subtle, contribution here that is lightly spicy, every so slightly herbal and a nice balancing bitterness in the finish.  As the beer warms up the sweetness picks up a bit, at times it becomes a bit too much.  Most of the time it is held in check by the hopping levels and the under-current of dry maltiness; like notes of biscuits and lightly toasted malt.  This beer certainly blows most examples of the style out of the water, but I cant help but think that this would be that much better if it had not finished a little bit drier; it would be a bit more in balance and all that much more quaffable.

Poured cloudy amber, orange highlights. Wispy head, ring of bubbles clings to edge of glass. Aroma combines caramel, light hops and some nutty roasty malt. Citrusy hops appear first in the flavour, caramel sweetness follows, finish shows some more of nutty malt. Very easy to drink.
Pours a clear ruby/amber body with a small bubbly biege head. Very good hoppy, roasted fruity aroma. Sweet roasted malty flavor. Soapy, medium bodied. Nice drinkable beer.
A very good beer. One that will be kept on a regular basis in the beer fridge. Now to try out their other varieties.

Light mahogany with a foamy, off white head. Stringy lacing. Smells of dry hay, husky. Warm biscuits and a hint of spice and caramel. Bitter hops and caramel in the flavor. A touch of spicy sourness. Musky, dry finish that is malty and bitter.

brown pour with a creamy slightly yellow pour.  malty brown sugar and roach clip(faint but there) nose. taste is straw, brachs rootbeer candy,  a sticky brew. waffle cone finish. enough floral hop taste mixed in there to keep it level.
Dark amber with thick tan head.  Brown sugar and caramel aroma.  Full malt taste, a touch of hops and the full flavor delivers on the promise of the great nose.  Loved it.

UPDATED: OCT 9, 2005 this being my third Great Lakes brew, im really starting to get a feel for these guys, and im loving them. This would be second next to the Holy Moses. Even though the moses rated lower than this, I personally loved it. I had this in a bottle. little hops present in this, but smells slightly sweet with a subtle sugary caramel aroma. Flavor has a sweet finish, but has a deep malt palate, and a sticky finish, medium bodied, by the way, dark amber in color. Well balanced. I enjoyed this beer alot. I will make a second purchase in the future. I chose this over the Sam Smiths Oatmeal Stout, I think that I made a good choice. but we will see. I think these guys may be better than Bells, but hey, thats just my opinion, take or leave it. Either way they are making theirselves known immensely in the midwest.
Deep clear amber  with a nice lasting head. Predominate malt aroma and flavor with notes of caramel. Delicately hopped. Well balanced and enjoyable.
I picked thisup in Morgantown WV while visiting my daughter in WVU.  Amber in color with tan head.  Slight hops aroma and flavor.  slightly sweet and smooth.  Very enjoyable.
Poured a dark brown, with the aroma of caramel corn. Sweet with a toasted malt back. A little light bodied, but it just works. A classic lager. Thanks to OhioDad for the great trade.
Bottle.  Clear dark amber pour.  Nice toasty nutty caramel sweet malt aromas and flavors, some light spicy hop.  Clean finish and decent body.  Good vienna lager.

Thanks to OhioDad for this beer.

Poured a clear effervescent dark amber with a small fizzy off-white head which dissipated completely.  Aroma of spicy caramel and a touch of hops.  Taste is somewhat sweet caramel and molasses with a grassy hop finish that is rather clean and refreshing.  Definitely has its simple roots, but also enough complexity that says that this isnt any run-of-the-mill session lager.  Nicely done.

Deep amber colored body with a perfectly proportioned beige head made this a very attractive looking beer. The beer was well carbonated, but not fizzy.  Aromatically clean and unobtrusive, the beer had a malty, floral, sweetish smell.  The taste was also pleasant, with a toffee like sweetness, spicy hops, and a touch of mandarin orange sourness.  There was not much hop bitterness, but the well attenuated beer did not suffer much because of it.  Very clean and easy drinking beer with a simple but flawless construction typical of classic German styles.

Bready, toasty malts and some light vegetal tones in the aroma.  Deep copper-amber with low white head that recedes to partial cover and ring.  Leafy hops, bready malts and fairly assertive and lasting bitterness.  Light body with moderate to strong, pinpoint prickly carbonation.  Bottle (BB9/30/05) sampled with Olivier_MTL and Rastacouere.

OhioDad, thanks. Poured a deep fizzy amber. Tanh creamy head. Nose is hops, but a bit nutty, and something else. The taste has nose buttery notes, I have to say, this was not the best from Great Lakes.
Bottle. Pours medium amber w/ small light tan head. Nose is caramel and nutty. NIce and thick with lots of nuts, caramel. Light hopps come through in the nose and taste as the beer warms.

Definately my favorite selection in the Great Lakes Brewing Company sampler pack I purchased in South Bend,  Indiana.  This darkly ruddy beer has all the flavor of roasted malts, hops, caramel that one would want.  Fantastic aroma gives way to fantastic flavor, a nice full experience.  I really enjoyed this one.

UPDATED: OCT 16, 2005 Sweet malt aroma with an unusual hint of sweet potato. Copper with little head. Very light and refreshing with hints of caramel malt. The malt profile becomes more pronounced as it warms. A very nice reward after mowing grass in the Florida summer heat.

This beer has a very nice color and body, but a slim fading head.  The smell and taste are sweet, with maybe some roast, and full of flavor on the palate.  The aftertaste is bitter-sweet.  A very, very good Vienna.

Bright red with an average head that unfortunately didnt last long.  Subtle caramel carries the aroma.  The flavor is likewise caramel-based, with a syrupy-grape finish.  Decent enough to drink some more.

Diminishing white head, clear earthy amber bnody. Leafy, slightly caramely nose. A slight earthiness matches the generous cerealic malts with ease. Dark grapes and biscuit flavors are plentiful, but I certainly expected one of the top vienna to be richer, it is a fairly hoppy example, in a most leafy way, possibly spalt hops or a similar type. Slightly vegetal, heavy munich malt does, almost roasty at times, dryish. light bodied, gentle soft carbonation.
A light malt smell with some hops.  Amber color in appearnace.  Starts with some hop bitterness and finishes sweet.
A toastiness that cooled me off on a hot summer day.  I need to make an hour trip up north to visit this fine brewery.

Amber copper colored beer.  Very malty aroma.  Carmel malts and mild hops make a nice aroma.  Nice smooth flavor and a great malt sweetness.  Again, carmel malts are taking the upfront possition with citrus hops sitting in the background.  Nice clean beer.

Drink by April, 2005.  Pours an amber-brick color.  Not 100% clear but not hazy.  Minimal carbonation and a small white head.  Sweet malt and lightly fruitish hops on the nose.   Flavor is very well balanced.  Malt and hops (citrus and spice) compete for some dominance but none really gets a big leg up.  Malt is ultimately what you have to discuss here.  Sweet caramel and general maltyness (toasty is an after thought).  Really very nice and quaffable.  Not a huge lager fan but his one is on the money.

12 oz. bottle.  Deep red with a brown tinge to it and a good light tan head.  Aroma is dominated by fruity hops and caramel malt.  Taste starts bitter then is balanced by the roasted malt flavor.  Bitter, smoky finish that rounds it out nicely.  A very good beer (although I would still pick Lakefronts Riverwest Stein over this one).

From a bottle, at home, into a pub glass.  Wonderful deep red/orange color with a modest, rocky and well maintained head.  Nice aroma from this one (others tasted like they werent stored well for some reason), smells like a lager, but a tad more rich, with a bit more fruity hops.  Taste follows the aroma with a bit more emphasis on a deeper version of the typical lager malt flavour.  A beer does lots of things well but is not in any way exceptional, nice and casual, great with grilled food (such as  german sausages).
Bottle at Paninis on the OSU campus.  Sorry, but had to blow through this one and get a draft of Blue Moon - another example of a style of beer that just doesnt do it for me.

Mild toasted sweet malts and butterscotch. Nice fruity hops, mild orange blossom. Dark amber clear with thin off-white lacing head. Medium body with medium carbonation. Starts mildly acidic and bitter, with toasted malt and sugary quality. A bit sweet in the finish with nutty bitterness and some salty after. Decent lager but not remarkable.
Colored like Jim Beam, cream colored head, light malt flavor, hint of hops, clean finish.

Bottle:  Aroma of caramel with light hops.  Pours a transparent amber with a small white head.  Fruit and buttery caramel up front with a well balanced a very tastey grapefruit hop finish.  Very good.

Reddish-amber pour with a thin beige head.  Very nice malty aroma, with some toffee, caramel, and lighter spices noted.  Mouthfeel was very smooth, with flavors of bread, caramel, and brown sugar.  Finish was of roasted malts and subtle hops.  Very good brew, especially for the style!  Would make a fine session beer.

Amber orange color, nice layer of head & lacing. Nose of rich malts; toffee & creme, a soufle of scents. The flavor has a rich reduced flavor, candy cane sweetness & underlying balance. Best Vienna Ever.
One is greeted by a great roasted  malt aroma when the beer is poured out. Flavor is much the same, malt and roast fill the palate nicely. Good beer.

UPDATED: JUL 18, 2010 Very Sweet/malty aroma when cracking the bottle, Deep amber pour, crisp yet flavorful finish...Light roasted malt finish, but all in all a fine combo with the malt/ hop/Yeast flavor!

Bottle.  Amber in colour with a beige coloured head.  The aroma was malty ( lots of bread, caramel and cookies) with some citrus.  The flavour was of cookie dough, roasted nuts, caramel.  Smooth mouthfeel, medium body, medium carbonation.  Finishes with a medium lingering bitterness.  Quite enjoyable.

Crimson colored with a small, off-white head.  First whiff was a pleasant toasted malt aroma followed by some soft fruitiness.  Smooth textured mouthfeel with moderate amount of carbonation.  Earthiness in the finish.
amber, beige head.  toasty malt aroma with some caramel and mild orange.  juicy malt flavour with more caramel and mild spiciness.  whole wheat and earth flavour in the finish.  nice.

Pours copper with a decent offwhite head that laces a little. Mild citrus and mostly caramel malt aroma.  The flavor is malty, some brown sugar notes and maple syrup.  Very smooth on the palate and creamy.  Quite a tasty brew and it leaves a very sweet doughy aftertase that made me want to get the next one out of the cooler.  All viennas should be judged by this one.  Delicious!!

Bottled.  Soft, sweet, mildly fruity and malty aroma.  Medium-dark copper-brown color, clear, with a slight, fading head.  Flavor profile is mild and lightly sweet, some light brown sugar and gentle nutty breadiness mingling at the finish with some lightly spicy hop and lingering dark grainy sweetness.  Smooth, lightly carbonated palate with a light-medium body.  Highly drinkable and would make for an excellent session beer.  At least, if I had more than the one bottle, it would.

UPDATED: JAN 9, 2006 Bright golden brown in color with not much of a head.  Souring aroma.  Smells mighty malty, like a Marzen sans hops.  Some brown sugar and maple syrup in the smell as well.  Spice completion ignites the smooth, subtle flavoring.  Nuts and caramel protrude.  Much creamier than expected.  Finishes like a cinnamon roll.  Not very eventful, but good.

UPDATED: JUN 22, 2007 Pours amber with a fully receding wispy white head. Aroma of toffee, caramel, and malty lager yeast. Taste of chewy caramel malt with bready yeast.  Alcohol is somewhat noticable. Mouthfeel is medium bodied with dense carbonation.  Reminds me very much of an Oktoberfest I just brewed, this yeast is very similar to Wy2308.  Enjoyable.
I have to say that I have enjoyed every Great Lakes beer that I have had so far, very smooth, great taste and aroma, when I have the money, I will go for the variety pack
Poured a nice dark amber color with a decent lingering head.  Taste is of nuts with some lingering fruit qualities in the backdrop.

Bottle: Poured a mid-brown color beer with an above average white foamy head with good retention. Nice malty aroma with some roastiness and some nuts. Taste is quite malty with a smooth creamy taste and light bitterness at the end. Body is fuller then expected and probably fuller then most Vienna I tasted before. Overall, this is real good stuff.
Malt and a bit of nuts in aroma.  Nice and full body with a very tasty malt.  A bit chewy and roasty.  Ends with a little hops.  Very good stuff.

Nice presenting pale ruby brew. Decent creamy head. Light slightly woody aroma, sweet with noticeable alcohol at the finish. Medium bodied, sweet malts with off raw cabbage like aftertaste. Light bitter finish.

A very tight and well-balanced beer.  Caramel malts and some crisp, floral hops are the main tastes.  Taste goes malty, then hoppy, then malty again, and ends with a slight bitter and slight nutty taste.  Very nice, very refreshing.
Light candied malt aroma,  copper, pours a large toffee head. Soft malt taste, some light hops too. Light bodied, some bitterness at the finish. A nice beer.
Had this in a sample pack, i enjoyed it very malty and hoppy with a bitter finish i was kind of hoping for more but still a really good brew
bottle. copper colour, flat head. caramel malt aroma. body mainly consists of sweet soft malt flavours. smooth medium body. a very quaffable beer. I enjoyed it.

Bottle. Thanks to jeffc666 for this! Lovely copper body underneath a foamy tan head. Nose is caramel, sweet malts, light hoppiness, and light toffee. Very nice! Taste is nutty and hoppy with some earthy notes, light caramel and sweet malts. Body is medium with lots of carbonation feel to it. Finish is very nutty and malty. Light caramel, hoppy earthy notes, and almost a wood-like finish. Nice!
Lots of sweetcaramel malt go along with some floaral hops from this rich copper coloured beer. Nice malty toffee flavours with a good medium mouthfeel and lingering finish. Solid.
As respectable as a lager gets, and thats finally saying a lot.  Take this one seriously, beer lovers.  I dont think I have any descriptive notes to add over and above the others.

Dark amber with a small off white head...wonderful sweet malty, carmel, and toffee aroma.  Smooth and sweet body of malt and carmel....very drinkable and well balanced, not overtly sweet.  Great everyday brew.
Cloudy amber with tight cream head that fades quickly.  Sweet malt aroma.  Taste falls flat - old bottle.  Need to re-rate.
Pours amber with decent off-white head that fades fast. Sweet malt aroma and flavor. Nice lacing. Smooth easy drink.
a pretty mild fruity hop aroma. a nice round but rich lager taste.   just really good.  and good high alcohol content.
Malty aroma and flavor.   Very drinkable and smooth going down.  Medium body, good mouthfeel.  A great session beer.

Thanks to slikwily for this one.  Pours cloudy copper to an ambered brown with a small light brown rocky head.  Sweet malted barley with sugary notes and a hoppy nose with vanilla hints.  Warm and sweet creamy caramel flavor greets your tonue with the first draw and leaves you with a creamy hoppiness.  Medium-bodied and creamy/fizzy palate.
Beautiful amber color, malty nose, pleasant enough malt taste, characteristic of this style, maybe a little fuller and sweeter than others
i really liked this beer.  amber color with a nice malty nose.  flavor is slightly earthy, malty sweetness.  body is nice and smooth.
A Red lager that has a sweet smell and a hearty mouth feel of malt.  I think this would be a great beer to entertain with.
Pleasant aroma of a good malty lager.  This beer was all about the malt.  Smooth drinking and refreshing all the way, as a lager should be.
Great Lakes , what a wondelful Brewing co. This Great Deep amber lager has a very nice balance of malt and hops. alittle bitter, love that real nice refreshing finish.
In a blind taste test I say no way this is a lager...too full flavored (roasted malt and hoppy bitterness) with a rich mouthfeel and nice crisp bitter finish.  Pretty good.
It has a tangy taste.  Brilliant red color, bad atmittedly I picked it because of the color.  Nutty complicated flavor.  Fruity and nutty all at once.  Thick palat feel in my opinion.

Pours a cloudy amber hue, with a small halo of a slight off-white head.  Aromas of roasted malts, honey, a hint of caramel.  Mouthfeel is medium bodied wiith  flavots of caramel, grain,  caramel, and a little bit of roasted nuts.  Very nice finish....wow, I am not the biggest vienna fan, not to mention lager fan, but this is very tasty.
Nice ruddy color and a light tan, fluffy head. Some toasted malt in the nose. Sweet and caramelly malt, though not overpowering. A little bitter and decent hop blend. Good balance and a smooth brew.
Red liquid with nice head. Light malt aroma. Nice malt flavour and hop balance Nice hop finish. A drinkable and enjoyable beer.

Good, but doesnt seem to have any real distinguishing qualities; intermediate in bitterness among the great lakes brews.  Good balance of hops and malt.  Pleasant aroma.  Rich flavour without being weird in any way.  I gladly drink it, but I think some of the other Great Lakes brews are a bit more exciting.

Bottle. Medium sized ivory head that mostly diminished, fair lacing, fine sized bubbles, carbonated, and a dark orange hue. Malty, caramel, hoppy, sweet aroma. Flavor was sweet, malty and hoppy with a slght aftertaste. Tingly, hoppy and dry palate. Medium bodied beer. Quaffable.

UPDATED: JAN 13, 2006 Pours a more red of an amber color with a slight beige head. Real good flavor to it, can really taste sweet caramel  and its malty, nice hop kick and actually alcohol kick to it that give it a nice bite.

Deep sparkling copper body topped by a foamy light tan head with stringy lacing. The aroma is pure malty vienna lager. Lightly nutty, notes of butter and hops. Subtle but nice aroma. The flavor is briliant. Nutty sweet bitterness that is simply divine. Extremely drinkable. Medium body lightly dry finsih. One of the best viennas out there. Thanks Dan, though you still owe me. ;)

Out of the bottle this brew pours a cloudy sunset red with a tall off-white head. Amazing hop aroma, sicky hops, with a caramel sweetness beside it. Taste starts with a melty sweet caramel malt, very well balanced with a nice finishing bitterness. This brew has a thick body, almost syrupy on the palate. Great brew with a nice crispness.

Pours a two-fingered white head that fades slowly leaving some lace.  Cloudy amber color.  Hoppy nose.  Medium carbonation and medium bodied.  Starts with a mix of hops and malt with the hops dominating, some sweetness, finish is clean and hoppy with some bitter after taste. $1.49 for a 12oz bottle from Liquor Barn Lexington, KY.

UPDATED: FEB 1, 2005 The commercial description says it for me.  This deep amber brew is full of solid malt flavor with a nice balance on the hops.  Full-bodied and refreshing with a crisp finish, this beer reminds a hop-head like me that lagers can be damned good drinks.

Clear reddish amber in color, with a good white head that left some lace.  The aroma is malt, reminiscent of pistachios, and spicey yeast similar to a bock, with a light floral hop fragrance.  Taste is smooth toasted and nutty malt with some bitterness, this beer is clean and crisp.  There is a nice balance of body and carbonation.  A perfect beer for drinking all evening.
Light amber colour beige head.. thick light malty flowery aroma.. cloying sugar dry bitters...
OK beer from a great brewery.  They play it safe with this style not traveling far from the middle.  Other styles from GLBC better and more daring. Solid brew in regards to other Viennas.

Fruity and hoppy nose.
Dark amber, low head.
Medium matiness, ok balance to aromatic hops.
lightish body.
Slight herbal aftertaste.
Pours a dark "merlot" color. With a small white fluffy head. Aroma of light malt and spice. Flavor is deep and rich, malt.  Alcohol and spicy hops also present. Palate is very full. A very nice brew!

Dark amber color with a light tan head.  The nose shows malt as the main thing, but there is a nice little bit of spice underneath the carmel notes.  Very smooth on the palate, with soft carbonation.  Flavors of carmel and a touch of dark fruit up front and a clean, dry finish.  Super beer.  I wish everyone could try this at least once.
Nose is nice rich brown sugar malt, hoppier than I expected.  Very nice sweet rich malt.  A little dusty.  Brown sugar, plum, a little alcohol.  Bitter at the back of my tounge.  Damn fine
Not a huge fan of lagers, but this stuff is super.  Great amber color and rich head.  Great malty aroma.

UPDATED: AUG 3, 2006 Tried at the Boneyard in Cleveland.  Prolly the best looking Amber I have ever tried.  Almost a glowing amber color with a thick foamy had with great lacing and retention.  I was in a bar, so there were far too many other smells to really pin down the nose.  Taste was clean, smooth, with good body and very nice flavor.

Hazy bright reddish-copper color with a nice light tan head that last, leaves great lacing in my glass. Toasted nut and brown sugar aromas, nutty caramel flavors, medium bodied with a full and creamy mouthfeel, perfect carbonation, finishes clean with some sweetness. I believe this is the best amber lager I have ever had.

Perfectly clear, brilliantly ambered hue...delicate, diaphonous lacey, foam, elegantly drifting down in size...aroma bursts out from first cracking the crown, fruity, yeasty, malty, a perfect combination...beautiful...soft, yet still a little spicy...
Time to drink up!
Mmmm!Nice, little hoppiness, then the mouth is washed over with caramel malt, toasty, rich, and smooth...notes of cherries and nuts on the palate...light bodied, but with a luscious, ever-tasty finish, clean and easy, but quite happy in the mouth.
Oh, this is good! Ohioans, you must be slap-happy to have this around, the best amber lager to slip past my lips!

UPDATED: OCT 17, 2004 Bottle ...thanks Brooklynboy...I may have made a mistake by waiting for oktoberfest to crack this beer (dated best befrore Sept 29 ) but I wanted to stack it against some Oktoberfest Vienna/Marzen/Oktoberfest beers out this time of year....It came out flying despite the 10 day lapsed freshness date. 2 inch deep sand colored sticky cap after a hard pour. Beautiful deep copper-red hue. Nose is of toffee-caramel sweet graininess, slight wisps of spicy-mustiness. Nice substantial chewy malt delivery up front...silky mouth feel...malt sweetness is kept in tow with woody, rustic hop departure leaving a light toasty- toffee and fresh cut maple impression. Finish is moderate with the hops coming forward and leaving a musty sweet toasty taste. Damn fine rendition of the Vienna style....I wish this was available in Ontario, It would be my favorite Fall quaff.
Reddish/Amber Coloring.  Good Malt and Hops Flavors. Balanced Well. Some Spice, Bread Dough, Grains... Very Nice Brew.

Deep Red.

Moderately aromatic with notes of toasted and caramel malts, slight spice and apples.

Solidly crafted, nice malt body, apples and caramel with toasted malt and berries. 

Another well crafted brew from Great Lakes. It wasnt quite what I was expecting but very good nonetheless.

355 ml bottle courtesy of jsquire. Bright red amber colour with a creamy and frothy off-white head. Caramel, nutty,  and lightly fruity aroma. Caramel, toasty, and dark fruit flavours with a roasty and fruity bitter finish. Medium bodied and smooth.
Bottle - sweet malty aroma.  Deep, dark amber color.  Aggressive hop and malt flavor.  A nice balance and contrast at the same time.  A Vienna lager that is interesting and quite delicious.
Reddish color, small white head.  Smells of sweet malts and caramel.  Tastes very sweet with caremel and small hints of toffee.  Hardly tastes like it is over 6%.  Quality beer.

Huge light tan head.  Clear dark amber.  Sweet caramel aroma.  Flavor moderatley sweet with the taste of caramel.  Finish is mostly malt with a light bitter background to balance it out.  Light to medium bodied.
Pours dark amber with a tannish head. Strong malt aroma. Taste is sweet malt and very rich.  Caramel aftertones. This beer is very high in flavor. Well done.

Lovely dark red/purple/brown color, starting with a two-finger light brown head that disappears into nothingness.  Aroma very sweet, lots of malts and a sharp sweetness, perhaps cherry.  Yummy with the caramelized malts in the beginning; the middle is sweet and subdued; the finish brings out the hops as the malt flavor mostly wears off; nice, mellow balance.  Medium thickness, slightly sugary/syrupy.  Very different from the last "vienna" I had; for the best-of-the-best, this isnt "that good."  But it is very solid and pleasant to drink.  Good beer.

A lot of quality in here, but these heavy, hoppy beers (a la Sierra Nevada) seem a dime a dozen to me.  If I want to take a half hour-40 minutes to drink 1 beer, Ill take a bourbon or a glass of wine.

UPDATED: AUG 24, 2004 Bottle Pours a red/copper with a very large foamy off-white head.  After this finally settles, a thin layer remains to bolster the decent lacing. Aroma is malt and applesauce.  Som edakr roasted grain.  Nice rich flavors. Carmel, hops and a little smokey.  Deep and..well...noble...   Rounded complex taste.  Feel is rich and soft, with a woody and not bitter after taste.  Quite good.
Thanks to EddieG for the trade.
I really enjoyed this beer.  Had an amberish colored appearance with a very nice aroma.  Has a great taste too.
A very good vienna.  Crisp, with a full flavor and nice color.  Really a pleasant brew and easy drinking.  Another worthy offering from Great Lakes.
This one poured a thick tan head over a very dark burgundy-hued body, witha malty, caramelly odor.  Its tasty was fruity and complex... an excellent Vienna-style brew!

UPDATED: MAR 24, 2012 I just bought a GL sampler for $6 what a deal, this was one of them.  Carmel colored, translucent pours with a small tan head.    Amora is carmel malt, sweet with a touch of saaz or hallertau.  Flavor is bitter/sweet.  Balanced finish.  Very good beer

Pours a big rich tan head.  Beer is slightly cloudy, deep red brown (as ambers go, anyway).  Nice caramel nose.  Full malt flavor.  Caramel or toffee, maybe honey.  Rich and heavy on the palate.  Nice use of hops.  Surprisingly high alcohol.  Very good overall, just a bit too heavy for this style.

Lightly hazed copper body with beige head.  Aroma is moderately sweet, strong toffee/caramel.  Taste is medium sweet, toffee/caramel, light earthy.  Light-medium body.  The toffee, without more, is just too overpowering to me.

UPDATED: SEP 27, 2009 Dark amber color with a medium white head. Toasty, caramel  malt aroma. Lightly sweet malts with notes of caramel, toffee, and toast. Well balanced by moderate hop bitterness. Finishes with some honey and light fruity sweetness. Very enjoyable.
UPDATED: APR 25, 2005 First real Vienna.  Pretty good.  Red with a tan head, with a great balance of malt and hops.  There was one interesting fruity flavor that I cant identify.
malty brown sugar carmel aroma, slightly foggy ruby colr, thick tan head, slightly bitter finish with a little lime, barley malts, a little fruity and a little chocolately, interesting flavor

(Best by Sep/20/04) I really like the color of this beer, sort of chestnut red. The nose is full of Hallertau and light sweet malts. The head only lasted for a little while, but there still is a small ring holding onto the rim of the glass. Malt and spicy hops meld effortlessly to produce a tasty brew. I taste bitter chocolate and smooth coffee and cream. This beer is nice and malty, but it is not overly sweet. Actually, the beer finishes dry and hoppy. A good interpretation of the style.

my dad held a bowl glass filled with miller lite while i held a stem glass full of this: honey/reddish brown body with a lingering and airy off-white head. caramel malt announced nicely enough while it seems the hops bring something floral. slightly sweet, watery, but its very drinkable. the aftertaste is a little bitter with some veggies. it finishes nicely, a bit sweet. it's a quiet beer and i like that. not much else than any other lager, in my opinion, but it has just enough more to edge most of the others out. good lager. but today, at least, i preferred my dad's miller lite. happy father's day everybody!

Good beer from Great Lakes.  Deep amber/copper body with frothy biege head.  Nice malt aroma with the fleeting hint of vegetables.  Light to medium in the body.  Flavor was malt and caramel and very pleasant.  Quite good.

Bottle pours translucent caramel, small milkish cream colored head, lively carbonation, with decent lacing.   Malts, biscuit, cookie dough, and floral esters on the nose.   Malty, chewy, caramel, cookie dough, slightly sweet, very smooth, oh yeah this is damn tasty!   WOW, by far the best Vienna I have had.   No real bitterness, just a nice malty flavor with hints of caramel.   Clean, crisp, with a nice finish.   Body and mouthfeel are very appropriate.   I would easly have this one again.   Thanks goes out to TChrome for the trade!

Bottled.  Pour produced an average sized beige head that fell to a thin layer after a few minutes; fair lacing.  Clear med-dark amber color.  Aroma was a harmoniously layered complex of toasty caramel malt, floral hop nose, and some esteriness.  It was marred somewhat by a subtle but discordant sulfury off-note.  Flavor was a nice balance of bitter/sweet up front with some esteriness that emerged mid-palate.  It finished with the same balanced bitter/sweet character accompanied by a pleasant yeastiness.  A gentle but present hop character was evident throughout. Palate was creamy and medium to full bodied with a lively carbonation.  A nice amber (Vienna) lager that was enjoyably crisp and refreshing and easy drinking.
