It had a definite American craftbrew character i liked  that was manifest in its subtle but present hop flavor and aroma.  My enjoyment of this lovely brew was only marred a bit by the sulfury not in the aroma though this off-note wasnt apparent in the flavor.  Thanks Drew!

UPDATED: DEC 10, 2008 [draft - 10th Annual PA Microbrewers Fest, Pennsylvania Brewing Co. - Pittsburgh, PA] Had to do a little research to find out exactly which Great Lakes Brewing beer I had. Poured a nice amber color with a thin and fizzy white head. Thick and chewy roasted aroma with a nice caramelly malt hint. Strong malt flavor with a good sweet touch of that caramel that I caught in the aroma. The sweet malts give way to a nice roasted finish with a clean aftertaste.

Another in the line of "what the hell happened to my damn notes??"  - that I can fairly clearly remember it attests to the quality of this fine brew. Superb roasty, toasty malt and excellent accompaniment in the bitterness. Me want more.

Got a bottle from civforprez. Pours a dark amber with very little head. The light aroma made me think of cheddar cheese. This has a thin body with a flour-y mouthfeel. The taste is slightly bitter with a cheesy finish. This is more interesting than most ambers.
Pours red with no head.  There is a noticeable amount of yeast in the aroma, not much else.  Flavor is of malt and barley, with a sweet finish.  Disappointing compared to other Great Lakes lagers.

Pretty, clear mahogany with a yellow khaki head that builds up nicely but fades quickly. Toasted malty aroma is followed by a lightly sweet toast flavor with a bit of bright hop bitterness in the finish. Great Lakes really excels with its lagers.

beautiful clear dull red color with a frothy off white thick but average sized head, beautiful.   Light cereal aroma, a bit of carmel, very light chocolate nose too.  Sweet and malty above all, light toasted grain.  very drinkable, great body, light black mlats too.  all around good

UPDATED: JUN 25, 2005 Deep, vaguely hazy reddish-copper, with a thin, nicely firmed lasting head.  Great nose, very malty with lots of caramel, also a bit sweet.  Wonderful flavor, simply huge malts, nicely caramel-sweet with butterscotch and maybe a slight bit of apple tartness.  Palate is the best part, very sticky and full.  Great, great stuff, currently voted in as the best lager Ive ever had.  I would bathe in this on a daily basis had I that option.

A sharp, well-rounded malt fest, with dark brown sugar, toast, biscuits, maybe some caramel.  Slighty woody, herbal hop overtones.  Smooth, firm mouthfeel.  Great sandwich beer.  Thanks to cb and TAR for a great night out!

Bright copper color with slight reddish tint, medium white head that dissipated quickly. Sweetish malty aroma, hints of pine. Rich and malty, dark and sweet, like eating a loaf of bread. Ever so slightly roasted, tobacco, buttery smooth. Lingering bread finish, little bit metallic. Very well balanced. Delicious! Great Lakes brings the lager to the US.
Light amber color with an off white head. Aroma is carmel and malty. Malty flavor profile with a thicker palate. Slight clove taste which detracts, but overall a good beer.
Ruby red in color with an off white head that is retained.  The aroma is bready/malty.  The flavor is sweet malt with light roastiness.  Easy going drinker with quite good flavor.
very good German style beer. Goes well with food, perfect for appetizers. Well balanced.
My favorite Great Lakes beer.Very good, very strong the whole way down.Traditionaly an Octoberfest style,however,great for all seasons(espesialy christmas)

UPDATED: MAY 31, 2006 It has ben over 2 years nice I have had this got in in a trade with LeopoldStoch. poured a nice dark amber, with a light tan head that left some lacing.aroma  brown sugar, malts a little sourness. flavor a nice sweet malt with a caramel kick to it followed by a touch of hops. just going to tweek the rating just a bit.4/30/04amber with nice lasting head nice copper color nice smooth malty with a little fruit with a touch of bitterness . GOOD BEER
Nice amber color, very drinkable. Lots of flavor.  Great Lakes does it again.
UPDATED: JUN 21, 2005 Lovely aroma of malts and raisins almost.  Great smooth malty fruity taste.  Sits very nicely on the palate and goes down perfectly.  Excellent beer.
Amber with a big lasting beige head. Aroma of malt and hops. Flavor is sweet, malty, caramel, and a little fruit. This is the first Vienna that I've really liked.

UPDATED: AUG 6, 2007 This beer looks great in the glass, glows like a copper sunset with a surprisingly thin head. Body instantly has a malty sweetness with hints of dried raisins and a somewhat nutty presence. Aroma is of candied fruits and rasted coffee beans with a hint of natural carbonation. A very, very drinkable beer available widely in the great lakes region, one of my favorite "drinking" beers!
Light malt aroma. Average off-white frothy head. Moderate hoppy flavor and long lasting light sweet finish. Very drinkable.

No aroma.  Color was  med-dark brown, with no head.  Color was  consistent.  Flavor was malty.  Rich malt flavor, and a little sweet.  More amber than lager.  Slightly dry finish.  Palate was not too bad, not too good.  Overall, it is what it says.  Clearly more of an more amber than lager.  Sweet and malty, and not my style.

I'm not sure what all the fuss is about theis beer.  I thought it was middle of the road amber.  Zero head to speak of and lasted about 3 seconds.  I thought it almost tasted like "candy" it was so sweet and it didn't last long on my palate.  Would be a great beer if I didn't pay $10 a sixer!

The beer after seceding from the bottle pours a deep translucent burnished copper color, the head cyclopean in size, the texture spumescent and the color a resplendent light tan with the lace a glutinous sheet to eclipse the glass. Nose is a slightly musky with a big malt sweet backing and the start mildly sweet with a pleasing malt presence, the top moderate in its feel to the palate. Finish is pesky in its acidity, the hops bountiful and pleasing in their spiciness, droughty aftertaste that lingers long on the palate, a great beer from a great brewery.

Solid rust/coppery color with a slight chill haze, medium, softly topped chicken meat colored head that sits a good while before settling to a favorable skim and thin, speckled curtains of lace sticking as we go. Aroma is quite light on the nose with some light toasty grains and bread with just a bit of sweetened fruitiness. As it warms a nice smokey-like dryness, roasty hazel nuts, and hard caramel appear in the nose making it much nicer and even a bit stronger. Taste is mild but eager with a small easy start that remains in some mixed maltyness of slight sweetness and light toastyness, but that gains with a gradual presence of uniquely thick seven grain pancake-like toasty roundness. Perfectly milding light grassy spice and hops poke through. Add in the teriffic finish of smokened grains and malts slightly drying and lifting into the finishwith mixed roasty nuttyness. Very intriguing flavors indeed, well put together with a delicately rich and smooth body that keeps convalescing. A true showmanship of the meaning behind hand crafted. Wow, what a recipe, great stuff!  Try it and see, you'll be impressed no doubt! Absolutely drinkable to the fullest! My new Vienna/Marzen to keep around at all costs! Yum times ten!
Amber color w/ tan head. Aroma is slightly malty, with that typical lager bite ia the finish. Fla vor is smooth slightly -sweet a touch of bitterness in the finish Palate is a little thin

Reddish orange color with an offwhite head that was decently lasting.  Also some carbination through out the tasting.  Aroma of sweet dried fruits,, alot like the apricots I have, and a bit of dates as well.  Malty taste up front, followed briefly by those dried fruits, and a stong hop finish.  Usually I am not a fan of Vienna's but this one blew my mind.

Nice bottle, mentions on the label that Eliot Ness is "untouchable".

Nice, deep amber color with a tannish head which proves ephemeral. A touch of spotty lacing remains.

Smells like a caramel factory. Sweet burned sugar aromas and hints of molasses and toasted raisin bread.

Big malt up front, riding on just enough hops to carry it through. Well carbonated, this beer has a medium to full mouthfeel and a sweet finish. Faint hints of caramel and chocolate abound. Final kick of mild hops really makes this drinkable.

Mahogany like color with an off-white head that lasts the whole way down the glass.  Lots of malt flavor and aroma, but something that distinguishes it from a doppelbock.  Maybe it's a hint of fruit or citrus?  Doubt it, but that's all I can guess on.  Maybe just more hops.  Anyway, it's a very nice and drinkable beer.  It doesn't have that "whole meal" feeling like a doppelbock.

UPDATED: SEP 9, 2004 Beautiful dark amber with a LOT of carbonation (up the whole glass, and stayed that way). Smells decent, not great. Taste is a bit on the sweet side, but not TOO much. Mouthfeel was a bit too heavy for my liking, making me wonder just how many I could have before I felt bloated (two). It's a drinkable beer, but not nearly as drinkable as some of the others in the Great Lakes line.

Bright red-amber. Creamy beige head. Sweet, buttery, malty aroma w/ notes of honey & lightly roasted nuts. Soft, creamy feel. Rich, buttery malt flavour of caramel, cane sugar, & honey. Slightly sour w/ some smokey & oaky notes. Clean finish w/ fresh bitterness. Elegantly balanced.

Good looking glass of beer-amber ruby hue with a fine head that left rings as it went down and a malty floral aroma. Smooth and medium bodied with caramel toffee flavors, a bready note to it like a honey bun and a subtle warmth. The finish was mild and bitter sweet. My aunt brought me this from Cleveland and when I saw what it was I told her I was going to take it out and dump it in the gutter. She almost looked offended until she "got it" ha ha. Good beer.

12 oz: pours a clear red amber.  A generous head forms and then quickly dies. . . aroma contains large amounts of whole grains, wheat and a hint of piney hops.  Palate is smooth and soft.  Flavours have some great malt and a bit of dry fruit.  Hops come in a very clean finish that contains some pepper and nuts.  Thanks Santa, aofoxxy.

Pours clear deep amber, with a small tan head that slightly lasts, and leaves a very small bit of lacing.  Aroma strong on sweet caramel, lightly nutty, and some toasted grains.  Flavor starts with caramel spread on some toasted whole grain bread, ends with a slightly spicy hop finish.  Medium body, very drinkable.

Crystal clear amber ale with a large, frothy, khaki-colored head. Great retention and excellent lacing.
The nose is of toffee, caramel, buttermilk, grapefruit and white wine or a very dry port or sherry.
The flavor is a bit on the thin side, but has some nice caramel and butterscotch bursts. Well-balanced, but the malty sweetness wins out over the hops by only the smallest of margins.
Medium-bodied with a watery mouthfeel and lively carbonation. Short, bitter, dry finish. Another great effort from the fine folks at Great Lakes!

This is the best beer that Great lakes produces (I haven't tried Edmund Fitzgerald, but I have sampled dortmunder gold). This beer is full of malty goodness, however, it does not remind me much of Elliot Ness without the label.

Dark reddish brown appearance. Distinctively malty, fruity caramel and toffee aroma. Sweet malts, caramel flavor, nice creaminess and well rounded feel. One of the best Vienna's I've tasted. I'll drink to Elliott Ness on this one.

Clear oarnge/brown. Rising carbonation,with a nice 2inch head. Sticky lace. Clean malty aroma with some hop spice. Smooth mouthfeel,soft carbonation. Medium body. Malty mouth. Clean malt flavors(caramel,toffee,cracker),with a nice balance of hops and malts in the finish. Little more comes out in the flavor than aroma. Another good,clean,balanced lager from Great Lakes.
Wish there was a 3.5 for palate on this one. Extremely well balanced with a respectable depth.
This is a Vienna Lager? I had no idea. Pours coppery brown. Bready, wheaty aroma.  sourish, citrus hopflavor, then earthy bitter finish. Underlying malt gives it a rich mouthfeel.

Darker amber/brown. No head. Smells like sweet yeast, maybe a little cinnamon, hops, caramel. Tastes good. Burst of bitterness and then calms right down. Sweet burnt marshmallow flavor. Dries out quickly. Nice beer from Cleveland.

UPDATED: NOV 7, 2004 Dark amber color, decent head and lacing. Malty, sweet aroma. Sweet malt, roasted flavor with a slight bitterness towards the finish. The finish is slightly dry

Re-Rate 11-07-04
Ive been drinking this beer for a while now, and IMO it has one of the best finishes in beerdom. Slightly bitter, burnt brown sugar goodness. Excellent

I had this on tap at the brewery.  The color is dark.  It has a nice sweet yet hoppy smell.  The flavor does not disappoint.  It is another well balanced great lakes beer.  It tastes like a dark, stronger dortmunder gold.
Great dark amber color, with a medium to almost heavy head. Great lacing on the glass. This beer had a very malty flavor and aftertaste. This is a  sweet beer but not at all to sweet.

This is a good beer for those who like a lot of malt flavor. As I believe to be true with Vienna-style lagers, this beer is predominantly malt aroma and flavor, with enough hops to clean up the finish. At warmer temperatures, this beer exhibits a wonderful sweetness. But it's difficult to let it sit long enough to warm. Not much of a head to speak of, but that is just a minor detraction from the initial impresion of this beer.

Medium sized tight beaded tan head, remains as a slight ring around the inside of my tasting glass. Unfortunate , hazy amber/copper color. A really clean malt, grainy nose, bready. Medium body, kinda slick. Good malt flavors, but as it warms some slight bandaid flavors show up. Fairly dry finish.

UPDATED: AUG 3, 2005 Re-Rated from draft at GLBC in Cleveland: Sweet amber color, kind of lemony, but not unpleasantly so. Very Mellow malts, just a touch of caramel. Hops are equally mellow, with just a little bitterness and graininess. A slight flourish of poerter malts toward the end.
Original rating: 9/16/03, Score: 4.1 Draft. Did not even realize this was a lager beer, thought it was more of a brown ale (thats a compliment). A nice creamy head, almost stoutlike. Had a good beery smell with a touch of fruitiness that led me to think this was an ale. A complex hop taste that I thought had more American hops that the normal German ones. A delightful brew that stands out at any autumn party.

In addition to being a fine Vienna lager, Eliot Ness has a touch of smoke in the aroma and a bit more in the flavor. This may have been a defect in the bottle I tasted but it really made for nice complexity.

The transparent orange color looks tasty sitting on the table under the lamp.  I can smell the toasted malts, and they are the predominate early flavor, followed by a brief hint of sweetness hiding in the strong carbonation. There is a dry, bitter aftertaste which is not unpleasant and fades very slowly until my next sip.
Deep dark amber, tan head. Strong malt prescence. Very smooth. An excellent lager.
Nice Aroma, Nice color, Great taste.  I ordered a Great Lakes Dortmunder Gold, but somehow ended up getting this instead.  Decided it wasn't worth complaining about & I'm glad I didn't.
Amber color, and a whole lot of tan colored head. Decent malt scent. Mmm. Nice malty flavor, with a bit of caramel. Goes down smooth. Good stuff.

Clear amber with a substantial soft light tan head. Light toffee and toast aroma, with undertones of light fruit and floral hops. Malty, buttery toast with a touch of orange marmalade.  Sample seems a bit dated, but malt still comes through, will revisit when a fresher sample presents itself.

(bottled). Deep, bright copper hue with a soft malty nose & a faint floral hop presence.  Medium-bodied feel leads off with chewy toasted malt sweetness and ends with spicy bitterness and a faintly sour plum or fig suggestion that doesn't seem out of character.  Lingering bitterness stays spicy.  Great!
Amber color with medium head and alot of bubbles. Sweet malty aroma that is present in the taste. Nice hoppy kick.Finishes sweet with a hint of alcohol. A solid lager.
Great lager.  Deep red/amber color with nice malty sweetness.  Quite bitter but well balanced and has a dry finish.

UPDATED: JUL 8, 2005  Agreat beer and even better with food. Great Lakes does beer right and this brew is a fine example of their work. Closer to a typical -- though excellent -- American amber ale than a true Vienna lager though. Chewy and fruity with a great balance!
I recall this having a dark red color. Seemed extra harsh to me at the time, perhaps I got a bad pour?

This beer pours an amber color with tons of carbonation on the sides of the glass and a small head that oddly centers itself in the center.  The aroma is not very strong but I can sense home hints of fruit and light malts.  The taste is amazingly smooth and enjoyable.  It's a little sweet and the carbonation makes it more interesting.  The aftertaste is sweet, but reminescent of something earthy - can't pinpoint it.  Very good beer.  I could drink this one all night long.

Nice reddish amber color with minimal head, no lacing, medium-bodied. Aroma hints of caramel, ripe pears, dates, and yes, eiswein. Very nice. Beautifully balanced between tart and sweet, a malty presence followed by a hoppy twang. Creamy mouthfeel and clean, dry finish. Very well made, highly recommended.

Lagering at it's finest. She pours smooth and thunderheaded from the tap but calmes to a nice stratus-cloud that lingers 'til the end. Deep chestnest/amber color that's well backed by mellow hops, brown sugar, caramel apple malts and bready yeasts. This brew has a well balanced hoppy-yeasty prescence and is a great alternative to a market full of ales. Eliot Ness, you are one crafty bastard.

Brownish red color,nice tal tan head that seems to be taking it's time to die down.The aroma is malty sweet,hoppy and some what citrusy.Nice flavor medium sweet,pretty hoppy but not in an over powering manner but quite pleasant.the feel is some what thin meaning a slight watery feel.This has a nice sweet malt hop after taste that has some decent lasting power.Really make me wish i had more of these brews.Thanks to Jskendzel for this one.

Bountiful, fluffy head with wonderful lacing throughout.  Looks beautiful, clear amber color.  Surprising hop aroma.  Doughy flavor and a sweet, crisp finish.  A touch of alcohol.  Very enjoyable lager.
Foamy head that dissipates quickly, but with nice lacing.  Great brown red color.  Good flavor with roasted hops, touch of caramel and nice hops in the finish.  Much better than expected.

definately a beer that i thought would not fit my palate, but did.  im not much for lagers, but this one definately took me by suprise.  malts were huge and hops were there, but subtle.  finishes like a carmal apple.  definately a great lager
Amber colored body, thin head. Sweet fruity, malty aroma. Flavor is sweet caramel, very rich malt, sugary and toasty. Slightly hoppy finish, somewhat metallic and lingering.

Smell of sweet malt and hops.  Slight hint oh citrus.  Great dark amber color, with a bit of cream colored head.  Flavor is decently malty, and some nice hops flavors.  Finish is mostly from the sweet hops.

Great crimson colour with an excellent off-white head that lasts and lasts! Sweet smell with hints of fruit! Nice combination of early hops and latter malt create a nice feel in the mouth, and a great aftertaste. Once again, not one of my favourite styles, but this brewery definately has something going for them!!!
Wonderful bitters that mellow through the bottle.  Somewhat sweet but very nice finish.  Decent copper colored brew with a nice head.

Interesting beer.  Has a sweet malty taste, with a little hops balance.  Overall gives a thin, sweet impression.  Not one of my favorites, but a smooth drink nonetheless.  So far my favorite Great Lakes varieties are the Edmund Fitzgerald Porter and the Dortmunder Gold.

This has a subtle malt aroma dominated by German hops.  Glowing copper with a thin nougat colored head.  The mouthfeel is fizzy and lacks complexity and balance.  The finish was a sticky, stale bitter one.  I'm wondering if maybe I got a bad bottle.

Deep amber with a malty, caramel aroma with a definite sweetness.  Hops present at end; very dry.  Slightly stale sample, doesn't measure up to the other beers I've had from Great Lakes.  Lots of carbonation.

Pours a perfect amber color in my book. Thick beige head. Nice lacing.
Deep malty aromas, almost like there's some biscuit malt in there. Roasted malt is evident in the aroma too.
The noble hops (Saaz?) really shows through in the flavor. The caramelized malts sweetness balances out the nitter hop bite nicely.
Has a very smooth drinkablity. The touch of a lager. Nice.

2/10/03:  bottle.    medium head when poured, lessening to a medium to small ring of carbonation.  evident lacing.  deep, sexy reddish- brown colour.  sweet, malty nose.  impressive palate.  malty with some hops and subtle hints of floral.  nice amount of carbonation left on my tongue.  i’d love to find this one on tap.  a good example of the reason for me falling in love with Amber back in the day.
Nice overall taste and it very smooth.  Lots of flavors with each sip. I look forward to trying some other Great Lakes beers.

UPDATED: MAR 15, 2009 Brilliant.  A deep orange amber color with a nice light tan head.  Aroma is very malty along with the taste.  Slight caramel that blends perfectly with the malt to give the impression you have just eaten a piece of bread right out of the oven.  Along with Lakefronts Riverwest the best Vienna you can get in America.
Good beer, but this really didnt stand out to me.  The flavor is very good, but not anything groundbreaking.  Definitely worth trying if you see it.

Extremely enjoyable Vienna Amber thats worth the search to find it on tap. I regular drink the Eliot Ness and Dortmunder Gold every time I visit Cleveland, but have yet to try either (or any other Great Lakes) brew straight from the bottle although they appear to be readily available citywide. Sadly, these brews are near impossible to find west of the Rockies.

Pours deep red with a real beefy head. Nice blend of hops and malt providing both an enjoyable smell and even better taste. Enjoyable all the way round.

Bottled.  Just a notch below the porter, this is very malty-sweet on the nose, spectacular-looking like the other 2 GL brews I tried, creamy, caramel and oaky on the tongue.  Cant wait until this brewery is more available to me.

Beautiful amber lager which shows off some of the finest malt Ive encountered.  Complex caramel, smoky and toasted flavors which slide down on a creamy palate.  Malt is rather like Mahrs Ungespundet or Stoudts Gold, but more complex.  Superb.
Big caramel nose from this deep red beer.  The first word from my tasting notes says, "chewy".  Teenie-tiny hops presence (35IBU).  Pretty good with the sausage plate appetizer!!!
Loved this brew. Easy drinking malty lager.

Vienna style lager .
Amazing that this beer comes from  Cleveland .   I first had it there .  I am delighted to see that my neighborhood deli. sells it by the sixer .
Its got a mature angle about it.
the nuttyness is nice, especially with certain foods .
It has a certain swarthyness that keeps me coming back for more.
Its great with hearty foods as well .
Really the Summer-time refresher or anytime .
Wish I could get it here in Western Canada !

UPDATED: JUL 29, 2003 A very tasty lager. Nice deep amber color as far as I could tell in the dark restaurant I tried it in. Fresh malty nose. Just a touch of hops but enough to balance the malt. Some vinous notes along with a bit of caramel and toffee complimented perfectly by a slick, buttery mouthfeel.
an excellent lager, not my favorite style but this was very nice, amber colorored malty with hints of caramel, fruit, and spice

Dark amber color, very little head.  Malty flavor and aroma - very clean.  Hides the 6.2% ABV well.  Not much hop flavor or aroma, but well-balanced bitterness.  Im not a big lager drinker, but this is one of my favorites.
A very nice aroma to it....and its got a great caramel taste. It leaves a very snappy aftertaste to it and makes you want more.
Nice and malty. Tasted slightly bockish.  Great aftertaste of smoked black cherries.  One of the better lagers ive tried
This is a really great lager.  Has a woodsy/nutty aroma, nice dark color.  Reminds me of a brown ale, yet is a nice marriage with a lager.  Try this stuff.  Malty lagers=great lagers.

Hey, I hadnt had a nice malty lager in awhile, so this one gets very high ratings from me... what doesnt though really. Great aroma, malty sweet fruit flavor with a hint of nut and a smokey quality that is quite nice... great finish and a lingering satisfaction that comes from knowing that good lagers are indeed still being made! they are being made by great lakes for gods sake! god bless those clevelanders at times
Great color, light aroma, nice head.  This is a great lager, hands down.  The balance of flavor is awsome.  I love the nice bitter after taste also.  Wonderful beer!

had this on a sail boat and I wasnt exactly taking notes... but..I did find it more enjoyable than any other lager Ive ever had, thats not saying anything at all though.. but..Very spicy, very clean, a tad too sweet IMO..but enjoyable!

Dark Amber color, medium head. Malty aroma. A full-bodied Vienna Lager. Big malty flavors, caramel and slightly nutty. Nice hop bite. Well balanced. Great tasting beer. Smooth taste. Finish is clean and slightly dry. Aftertaste is slightly sweet. 

Thanks to jcalabre for the beer.
Sweet hoppy aroma, malty taste with sweet finish.  Beautiful color. Perfect night cap for raking leaves-day.
user_location: Middle of no where, Ohio, USA

text: This is a fabulous amber lager.  Noble hop aroma, With a bit of sweet malt.  Doughy bread malt flavor with really nice caramel sweetness.  Finish is dryish with nice hoppy kick.  Excellent, thanks a ton Dogbrick for sending me this.

Amber in color with minimal head.  Loads of malts with just a hint of balancing hops.  Toast, caramel, noble hops and mild roasty aromas.  Flavors largely mirror aromas with bread, caramel and roasted malt all discernable.  Finish is neutral, leaning towards dry.  Very nice, and thanks to PsychProf for sending this.

UPDATED: FEB 2, 2009 Bottle (BB 03/11/09). Head is initially small, frothy, off-white, mostly diminishing. Body is clear medium to dark amber. Aroma is moderately malty (caramel, cookie, toasted light bread), lightly to moderately hoppy (flowers, apricot), with notes of peach and honey. Flavor is moderately to heavily sweet, lightly acidic, lightly bitter. Finish is lightly to moderately sweet, lightly acidic, moderately bitter.  Medium body, velvety texture, lively carbonation. Uncomfortably sweet, but otherwise very nice.  Lovely to sniff, but kind of difficult to drink much of it.
beautiful amber color w/ a 2" (5cm) head. Crystal clear w/ a big malt nose & well balanced flavors
toasty, caramel, sweet and sour all malt goodness. Absolutley delicious lager..superbly made. I like the hop tinges and slightly more crisp nature of Riverwest Stein, but not by a lot. Wonderful.
user_location: Łódż, Warsaw, Poland; Michigan, Ohio, USA

text: Ruby pour with a creamy head.Sweet malty nose. Nice creamy palate that is very light on the tongue. Malt seems to be the name of the game with just a little hop bite at the end. Very nice beer. Thanks to hopsrus for this one.
Too malty for my tastes.  The dortmunder is definitely the standout in their lager range.

An almost perfect balance of malt and hops lead to a smoothness seldom found in other medium bodied lagers.   The caramelized malt seems to add just the right amount of sweetness to the brew.   The finish is so remarkably clean it immediately leaves you wanting more.   A fine Cleveland product that even someone from Pittsburgh could like!
A pretty decent beer.  A little light for my liking, but still enjoyable.  Nice sweet finish and a very clean taste overall.
The third Great Lakes offering that Ive tried, and they havent failed to impress. Imagine if someone told you twenty years ago that you could get great beer from Cleveland.
UPDATED: DEC 27, 2009 Very good.  Dont see what the fuss is about with the flavor... I think its balanced and pleasant.  Tasty, warm feeling beer.
Think Theakstons old peculiar, and add hops.  Nice color, kept a good mouth feel, but I just didnt like the flavor.  Not necessarily a beer, but I would recommend the peculiar first

Nice malty flavor and texture, it is complex tasting. Carmel and sweet, reminds me of my friend Master Brewer T. Tottys Oktoberfest , damn he can make a good beer, this is good, not the best ,but it is Recommended.

Deep amber in color. Some hints of roasted malt in the nose.  I do have a bit of a problem with this beers taste. It has a very unpleasant phenolic presence that is reminiscent of Band-Aids.  My only regret was I bought a sixer of this.
It made me blink a lot.  Not bad, not great.  An above average beer but not one I truly recommend.  The commercial description is fairly accurate (not as aromatic as they claim).
This beer reminds me a LOT of Sam Adams, except it isnt quite as good for some reason that I just cant put my finger on.  A little more burnt flavor, maybe.

THis has got to be one of their best.  No other Vienna style that Ive had even comes close.  An almost chunky caramel malt with a nice thick-hop flavor (ive never before referred to hops as thick, but it seems to fit here.)  All your Viennas should be compared to this!
Another good beer.  Damn Clevelanders seem to know their beer.  By only complaint was it was a tad on the hoppy side for me
Very creamy and rich.  Reddish color.  Great appetizing finish.  They said this beer is the best to go with a Chicago-style deep dish pizza.
UPDATED: JUL 25, 2003 Malty, flavorful, buttery with a hint of sourness and considerable floral hop bitterness.  This stuff is remarkable!  Where can I get me some more?
Very drinkable.  Malty flavor balanced with light noble hop flavor and aroma.  Slightly buttery but finishes clean.
Nice color, great aroma, nice malty flavor.

My choice of the great Great Lakes beers.  Cleveland is a city where I have many cousins and good warm memories of rich conversation and laughter.  This beer calls those moments to mind as it too is rich and warm, malty without being overpowering.  Yum!
Bottle.  A rich deep orange-red color with a nice head.  A dry malty crisp and clean flavor.  Very nice!
Nice amber color and slight aroma to it. Light head that doesnt hold very well. Nice taste to it, lighter and slightly tangy. Prefer this to Bells
Beautiful beer with a good approach to the vienna style. Malt taste went well
A monstrous amber with a huge malt density. Tastes very smoky and had it with the breweries pizza,... HIGHLY RECOMMENDED!
an overall decent beer...balanced pretty well, the malt flavor is definitely there, but still, i just didnt enjoy this as much as everyone else..perhaps its not my favorite style.
I am continually impressed with the Great Lakes Brewing Company!  I thought the Edmund Fitzgerald was the top of the line - but this one is damn close.  A must try!

UPDATED: FEB 6, 2003 Another winner from Great Lakes. Excellent amber color and thick head. Viennas aren't my favorite but I will make an exception in this case. Nutty aftertaste and sweet flavor with a perfect amount of hops to balance. This is definitely one to keep on hand.

rufous in color (thats birdwatcher talk for chestnut). nice to behold when it crashes into a glass, but then, like the legend of sleepy hollow, we find were about one head short in this drama.  no matter, this fizzes well upon agitation to prove its young and vital.  the aroma is to die for, rich caramel, you could dip apples in this for  haloween treats.  theyd be just for grown ups though, cause i can detect the alcohol too.  hypnotic whiskey bread-pudding aroma, flavor is sweet and full, enough bitterness for complexity. finish (of the glass) is way too soon. my favorite great lakes.

A very deep orange color with a thick tan head that lasted.  Very malty sweetness but balanced with the bitterness.  I laughed when I read ultraspanks comment about the hop burbs because I experienced the same thing but wasnt sure how I could tactfully say anything about it.  This is a very smooth beer that gets nicer as you drink it.
Light copper/orange hue. Robust fruity hop aroma.  Very hoppy, smooth palate.  What all lagers should be.  Nice

UPDATED: FEB 19, 2007 Clear red/copper. Nice head and lace. Toasty, buttery malt nose with hints of caramel. Lively in the mouth with a palate full of burnt caramel and chewy soft malt. Nice spicy hop finish. Well balanced and damn tasty! Seems to vary from bottle to bottle. Can range from amazing to average. I think thats what explains the disparity in ratings.

I had a bottle of this tonight after work.  This brew pours a hazy medium orangish red
hue.  The brew is not pasteurized and has tiny particles of thin density.  The mostly lasting
head is huge, off white and creamy and has excellent lacing.  The aroma is well balanced: a
bit spicy with moderate hints of roasted grains and nuts, also having a moderate resinous
piney hoppy texture, and light yeasty tones.  To be quite honest, I was better able to analyze
more of the hoppy qualities from my burps than from the nose.  The beers initial flavor is
moderately sweet and slightly bitter, transcending to a finish that is lightly sweet with a
moderate sharp roasted bitterness that is slightly nutty.  I enjoyed the medium body and
dry texture.  The carbonation was a bit lively for my liking, and the finish has a moderate
amount of clean astringency.  Overall a very decent brew.

So how did I find this one? You dont just walk into a bar, or even a beer store and ask for Elliott Ness or anything. It was in the back of a friends fridge, perfectly cold and leftover from a party i had passed on. A great beer, more pilsner than anything else, I toureds their brewery before this product came out, and will surely go back soon. Dont mess with Ness!

Light brown in color; thin and effervescent head. Interesting sweet finish that is very subtle. Maybe just a hint of cotton candy. Bready. Mouthfeel is explosive. Gets buttery towrds the end. Much more complex then say a Negra Modelo. Thank you jstu9.
Reddish brown. Nutty aroma. Buttery, slightly roasty. Well balanced bitterness. This beer works well!
Some butter and softly sweet that bends in a good transition to a soft bitter. This is well balanced. The color is a brilliant red. Headless.
Remarkably soft, creamy mouthfeel; unexpected but welcome in this smooth, easy lager.  Nice lightly burnt caramel flavor - GREAT with pizza. Good session beer, another winner from Great Lakes.
A good balance of flavors.
This is one hell of a hearty, full bodied beer with a nice floral accompaniment to the nuttiness.
Pure and professional. Untouchable. Nutty and fruity. Fairly intense and difficult to describe. Sweet, but complemented with alcohol well. Overall, quite the interesting and well-made brew.
Not my favorite style but again well done. The sweetness is not overwhelming

On 4/3/01 I considered this as not my mug of beer but it did get better as I drank more. Ive had it a few times since. It is a nice hoppy beer. Flavorful. Not as hoppy as the Burning River or Nosferatu, but a nice beer.
Nice carmael malt flavor with some hops thrown in. Finishes smooth . Great lakes sure know what theyre doing.
Mildly sweet nose with a sweet, tangy finish.  Mild with moderate hops showing up at the end.  Well moderated and rather ale-like, almost Scottish.
best nut lager ive had
Smelled and looked great but just wasnt my cup of tea. Aftertaste just didnt seem right at all to me. Started off ok though but i just didnt like that aftertaste.
Rich, deep amber colour; chewy nose of fresh malt; crisp, with good, evenly balanced malt flavours, balanced by toasty notes and a well-structured bitterness.

UPDATED: MAR 2, 2003 This could be the best beer in this style that i have ever tasted. It is my only perfect score and deservedly so. Everything about this beer was good. Great Lakes could be the best small brewery in the united states.
A very nice malty vienna style/octoberfest beer.  probably the best american micro in this style.
A silky texture runs throughout the heady cycle of deep malt and sharp hops.  A fine brew!
UPDATED: DEC 24, 2003 Damn!  Nice nice nice and even nicer.  Need I say more.  Can't get any more authentic than this in this lost style just as you can't with the Dort.  Thumbs up!
user_location: Blue Ridge Mountains, North Carolina, USA

text: There is a big roasty malt flavor followed by a hoppy bitterness.  It took me a few sips before I was hooked.  But this is a memorable Vienna lager.  and THE SMELL ROCKS!!

The Great Lakes Brewing Co. is on equal par with Bells for me.  We are blessed in the midwest to have these breweries.  The Elliot Ness is a very nice full flavored smooth as silk offering from GLBC.
I am not the greates lager fan, but this stuff is great. I have not had a sub-par beer from this company yet. Kudos to Great Lakes.
